<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DentalGasDeaths     08-08 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dental Gas Deaths,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Found Dead In Storage Room From Apparent Asphyxiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEDAR CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two young men and two young women who
apparently were inhaling laughing gas to get high were found dead
Monday in a storeroom of a building housing a dental clinic,
authorities said.
   The bodies were found shortly before noon in a small room near
an empty tank of nitrous oxide, a gas used by dentists as an
anesthetic, Iron County prosecutor Scott Burns.
   ``It's believed that they were inhaling the gas,'' he said.
   Burns said there was no sign of forced entry.
   He identified the victims as Owen Marc Gregerson, 18, and Shawn
Williams, 19, both of Cedar City; Christine Cherie Miller, 20, of
Fillmore; and Margaret J. Probert, 20, of Scipio.
   The bodies were sent to the state medical examiner's office for
a determination of the cause of death, but Burns said preliminary
investigation shows they were asphyxiated.
   ``It's just a tragic accident and our hearts go out to the
families,'' he said. ``We've never had injuries or deaths due to
nitrous oxide. It's common throughout the United States for people
to try to gain access to that to try to get high.''
</TEXT>
