<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HaitiPriest     08-08 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti Priest,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expelled Canadian priest said he feared for his life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rene Poirier, a Roman Catholic priest deported
from Haiti after he criticized the military government, said in an
interview Sunday he told his superiors last week that ``something
could happen to me.''
   ``I told them that if they heard I'd received a bullet in my
head, don't be surprised,'' Poirier said in the telephone interview.
   The priest, a native of Cornwall, Ont., arrived in Montreal
Saturday on a flight from New York.
   He was asked why be believed he could be the target of killers
and said ``the system is becoming much more repressive and anything
is possible.''
   Poirier said he was expelled because he spoke out against
injustice and encouraged the poor to organize politically. He
acknowledged he had refused a military demand to provide a list of
parish members who attended one of his recent religious services.
   He said the troopers who seized him Friday did not have a
warrant for his arrest and did not know his name.
   ``All they knew was that I was the (parish) priest and therefore
wicked,'' he said.
   Poirier gave this account of his expulsion:
   Several soldiers entered his parish in Grand Goave, 30 miles
southeast of the capital of Port-au-Prince, and drove him to a
prison where he was not allowed to call the Canadian Embassy.
   The soldiers took him to the airport where he was placed aboard
a commercial jetliner, and when he tried to resist they struck him
with their rifles and threw him face down on the aisle.
   It was a New York-bound flight and after spending the night in
New York he flew to Montreal.
   A Haitian radio station said the government accused Poirier of
making ``insulting public declarations which are liable to disturb
the social and political order established in the country.''
   A statement by the Canadian government said it was ``deeply
distressed and unhappy at the cavalier way that Father Poirier was
deported and (we) will be expressing our dissatisfaction to the
Haitian authorities.''
   Poirier was seized the same day that Haiti's leader, Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy, was touring the Grand Goave region. Namphy said at
that time that Haiti's problems should be solved by Haitians, not
foreigners.
   Namphy, the armed forces commander, ousted civilian President
Leslie Manigat in June and sent him into exile. Namphy headed a
three-man junta that had ruled Haiti for two years after dictator
Jean-Claude Duvalier fled the country during violent protests in
February 1986. Duvalier now lives in France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
