<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalSpill     08-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Spill,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Derailment Causes Spill, Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 cars of a freight train
derailed Monday, causing tankers to break open and spill a
flammable industrial solvent, and forcing the evacuation of about
300 people overnight, authorities said.
   Authorities built a dike, using booms supplied by the U.S. Coast
Guard, to keep the pool of liquid xylene from flowing into nearby
Beaver Dam Creek, said Lucy Justus, spokeswoman for the state
Environmental Protection Division.
   The Elbert County sheriff's department and officials with CSX
Transportation Inc. estimated 57 cars in the 95-car CSX train
derailed about 1:30 p.m. in this rural community.
   Elbert Memorial Hospital reported treating about 20 people who
had breathed fumes from the liquid chemical, which is used in
aviation fuel and as a solvent for resins, enamels and lacquers.
   None were seriously injured and all were released after ``they
were washed down and looked at by a physician,'' said Tom Johnson,
a hospital official.
   ``The primary hazard is that it (xylene) is flammable. There are
vapors and fumes which are mildly toxic by inhalation or
ingestion,'' Ms. Justus said.
   The fractured tanker, which contained about 30,000 gallons of
xylene, leaked its contents at a rate that grew to 3,000 gallons an
hour, she said. A second tanker also was leaking the chemical,
although at a much slower rate, she said. Five of the derailed cars
contained xylene, she said.
   CSX Transportation spokesman Ripley Watson said the train, which
was headed to Hamlet, N.C., from Atlanta, also carried coal, pulp
board, lumber, soybean meal and a number of piggybacked truck
trailers.
   He said the train was going about 35 mph when it derailed. There
was no immediate indication of what caused the derailment.
   Cleanup was expected to begin after daylight Tuesday. Ms. Justus
said the liquid probably would be allowed to soak into the dirt
field where it spilled and the contaminated soil would be dug up
and taken to a hazardous waste landfill.
   The Elberton Civic Center was set up as a clearing house for aid
to the evacuees. Most found shelter at motels or at the homes of
family and friends in the area, although the Rev. Gary Purvis,
pastor of First Baptist Church of Elberton, said he expected some
evacuees would sleep on the pews at his church.
   Middleton is four miles northeast of Elberton, in eastern
Georgia about midway between Atlanta and Columbia, S.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
