<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-08 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parishioners at St. Mark's United Methodist
Church can simply say, ``Charge it,'' the next time the collection
plate comes their way.
   Officers of the church's finance committee decided to accept
donations via MasterCard and Visa, beginning Sunday.
   ``A lot of people may look at it with distaste, but they don't
have to utilize it,'' said Ron Ecklund, chairman of the church
finance committee. ``Some people have requested it and we're a
large enough church that we can accommodate them. I think
convenience is the number one advantage.''
   Any of the 3,000 parishioners who make credit-card donations
will get a receipt they can put in an envelope and drop in the
collection plate.
   ``People still feel good about putting something in the
collection plate,'' Ecklund said. ``I always feel awkward sitting
in the pew and not putting anything in the collection plate when it
is passed.''
   Congregation members also can arrange to have a certain amount
automatically charged to their bank account on a specified day of
the month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She was in Colorado, he was in Turkey. But
the distance between them didn't stop them from exchanging wedding
vows.
   Terry Boatwright and Linda Gardiner became husband and wife by
telephone on Saturday, with a speaker phone standing in for
Boatwright during the ceremony here.
   ``It was different talking to a machine instead of a live person
looking me in the eye,'' said the Rev. Charles Kellim, who
performed the ceremony.
   The couple met a year ago, and Boatwright proposed after the Air
Force shipped him to Ankara, Turkey.
   They decided to get married by telephone because Boatwright
might not have been able to come to Aurora for six more months,
said the bride, who hopes to join her husband within six weeks.
   About 30 people gathered at the bride's home for the ceremony,
but the groom was alone. ``This is a very solemn thing for us, and
I chose to be by myself,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Caterpillar Inc. struts its stuff, it
does it in a big way.
   The company staged a ``power parade'' Sunday, displaying $15
million worth of its finest earth-moving equipment in a showcase of
sophisticated engineering and raw power for 10,000 customers and
employees.
   The Peoria-based Caterpillar trotted out 76 machines _ from the
largest track-type tractor in production on any assembly line, down
to its smallest paving vehicle.
   The demonstration track built near Peoria for the parade looked
like a giant construction site. Scrapers used in highway
construction pulled up dirt and dumped it back. Excavators dug
holes, filled their buckets with dirt and then loaded empty dump
trucks used in mining and construction.
   Graders leveled the rumpled ground and compactors rumbled along,
packing the dirt down again.
   There were tests of strength for hydraulic-powered swing arms.
Other machines did push-ups, intricate driving and even waved to
the crowd in unison.
   But the crowd's favorite was a wheel loader that used one tooth
on its massive front bucket to gently crack an egg.
</TEXT>
