<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Ellerbee     08-08 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ellerbee,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ellerbee Blames Network for Not Trying to Help Anchorwoman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former NBC reporter Linda Ellerbee said she
was afraid that colleague Jessica Savitch was on a suicidal course
because of problems including drug use but her approaches to
network management went unheeded.
   Savitch was killed in a car accident Oct. 26, 1983, in New Hope,
Pa. The accident was not linked to drug use.
   Recent books about Savitch describe her as a tormented women who
was well aware that she had moved up the ladder on her appealing
presence and was resented by more experienced colleagues.
   Her career nose-dived after a disastrous newsbrief in which she
appeared on the air virtually incoherent.
   ``At one point,'' Ellerbee said, ``I went to NBC management and
said, `You have to do something. This woman's in trouble.' An NBC
vice president said to me, `We're afraid to do anything. We're
afraid she'll kill herself on our time.''
   Ellerbee says on the first installment of the new late-night
talk show ``Later with Bob Costas,'' to be broadcast Aug. 22, that
she and her NBC correspondents decided to try to help Savitch.
   Ellerbee said she, former NBC correspondent John Hart and other
NBC News colleagues met in Ellerbee's office and decided Hart would
get advice from his psychiatrist on how to approach Savitch. But
she died in the car wreck that weekend.
   Savitch's story is worth telling, Ellerbee said, ``as a
cautionary tale'' for young women and men entering the television
news field.
   Ellerbee, who now free-lances her commentary and hopes to have a
PBS version of ABC's ``Our World,'' says television news has
changed little in its attitude toward women who go into the
business.
   ``Jessica is just what the business wanted,'' she said. ``Let's
be candid _ what the men who run the business wanted. She looked
the part, and they didn't care that she wasn't a very good reporter
and that she wasn't a very good writer.
   ``They just wanted what they wanted out of her, and it's a
tragedy that they didn't want more. Jessica might have been able to
give more had they expected more from the very beginning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
