<1ST_LINE>r p PM-RepublicanDelegates-VP     08-08 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Republican Delegates-VP,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Delegates Aren't Choosy on Vice President Selection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the Republican National
Convention aren't particularly choosy about a vice presidential
candidate, with the largest group inclined to accept anyone George
Bush selects.
   In an Associated Press survey, the ``candidate'' backed by the
largest group of delegates, 39 percent, was nobody in particular.
   Two former presidential candidates, Jack Kemp and Bob Dole, each
were favored by 14 percent.
   Others mentioned by a smattering of delegates included Chrysler
Corp. Chairman Lee A. Iacocca, major league baseball Commissioner
Peter Ueberroth, former White House communications director Patrick
Buchanan and a couple of otherwise unknowns whose candidacies were
advanced by relatives who happen to be delegates.
   Of the 1,274 GOP delegates responding to the AP survey, 492 said
they had no particular choice for the No. 2 spot on the party's
ticket.
   That sentiment is not at all uncommon as delegates tend to defer
to whatever decision their party's presidential nominee makes on
the issue of a running mate.
   Two-thirds of the Democratic delegates did not name anyone as
their choice for vice president, but when Michael Dukakis picked
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate, that decision was
endorsed by acclamation at last month's convention in Atlanta.
   Bush has said he will not announce his running mate until Aug.
18, the final day of the Republican convention.
   The AP survey did show some sentiment for a female vice
presidential candidate. Polls have shown that Bush lags behind
Dukakis among female voters, and 10 percent of the delegates
responding to the AP survey said one way to overcome this would be
to pick a woman as his running mate.
   Fourteen percent of the GOP delegates scattered their support
among four women: former United Nations Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick, who was named by 82 delegates, former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, supported by 79 delegates, Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum of Kansas with 17 delegates and Supreme Court Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor with five delegates.
   Kassebaum has said she does not want to be considered for the
vice presidential spot, as has California Gov. George Deukmejian,
who was named as the choice of two dozen delegates.
   The delegates' vice presidential choices cut across lines of
education, gender and political experience, with roughly the same
percentages of college graduates supporting Dole as Kemp, for
example.
   The survey was conducted by AP bureaus in all 50 states, as well
as Puerto Rico and is based on responses from 56 percent of the
2,277 delegates who will attend the GOP convention.
</TEXT>
