<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths     08-08 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths,0584</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>J. Skelly Wright</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired federal Judge J. Skelly Wright, who
participated in the Pentagon Papers case and wrote the decree
ending de facto segregation in the nation's capital, died Saturday
of cancer. He was 77.
   His retirement last year after 25 years on the U.S. Court of
Appeals here _ two as chief judge _ and 13 years as a U.S. District
Judge in his native city of New Orleans ended a judicial career in
which he played a key role in many cases involving conflicts
between the rights of citizens and the powers of the federal
government.
   After Wright's 1960 order desegregating the New Orleans school
system, President Kennedy reassigned him to Washington, D.C. In
1967, Wright issued an order that overturned the District school
system's racially separate ``tracking system'' for grouping
students. The ``Wright decree,'' in addressing de facto
segregation, was considered one of the most significant education
rulings since the 1954 Supreme Court decision outlawing ``separate
but equal.''
   In the 1971 Pentagon Papers case that involved an attempt by the
government on national security grounds to restrain publication by
The Washington Post of portions of the documents, Wright dissented
from the ruling of two other judges on a three-member appeals court
panel.
   In favoring the right of the newspaper to publish, he wrote:
``To allow a government to suppress free speech simply through a
system of bureaucratic classification would sell our heritage far,
far too cheaply.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ned Skinner</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   D.E. ``Ned'' Skinner, board chairman and majority
owner of the family-owned Skinner Corp., died Sunday following a
long battle with lung cancer. He was 68.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Richard Kavanaugh</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Kavanaugh, a leading actor at
the Trinity Repertory Company for almost two decades, was found
dead at his home Saturday. He was 47.
   Kavanaugh had been suffering from a bronchial virus for the past
two weeks, family members said.
   Although nominated for a Tony Award for his 1982 performance in
Harold Pinter's ``The Hothouse,'' Kavanaugh was best known for his
role as the fly-eating madman Renfield in ``Dracula.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Mattie Coney</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mattie Rice Coney, a schoolteacher and civic
leader honored for her work with the inner-city poor, died Friday.
She was 79.
   She and her husband, the late Elmo Coney, founded the
neighborhood group Citizens Forum in 1964 to combat housing
discrimination against blacks.
   It grew into an effort to collect trash, plant trees and watch
out for neighbors in poor, inner-city areas. She ran the volunteer
group until she and her husband retired in 1981.
   Groups modeled after Citizens Forum sprang up in Detroit,
Washington, D.C., and other cities. Six times, her work was
recognized in the Congressional Record.
   Born in Tennessee, she moved to Indianapolis at an early age and
taught fourth-grade students for 35 years after graduating from
Butler University.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edwin Owens</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwin John Owens, a retired judge and
the first dean of the Santa Clara University law school, died
Thursday of congestive heart failure. He was 91.
   Owens was an instructor at Boston College law school in 1933
when he was selected to head the fledgling Santa Clara University
law school, a post he held for two decades.
   He was then appointed as a judge to the Santa Clara County
Superior Court, where he served until his retirement in 1966.
</TEXT>
