<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-08 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Worries About Africa's Refugees; Sends Team to Somalia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are sending a team to a remote
part of Somalia this week to see what can be done to help hundreds
of thousands of refugees in the war-ravaged Horn of Africa.
   Rebel fighting in Somalia on Africa's east coast has caused more
than 200,000 refugees to flee into Ethiopia, moving at the rate of
1,000 a day since heavy fighting erupted last May, officials say.
   ``Because of the war, we are in the dark,'' said Bart Kull, a
spokesman for the Agency for International Development. ``Their
purpose is to try to assess what may be needed in terms of
humanitarian assistance.''
   The fighting, however, may prevent the U.S. team from going near
the northern area, officials said. U.N. officials evacuated their
people from the region in June for safety reasons, said Patricia
Fagan, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commission on Refugees.
   ``The whole Horn of Africa is in turmoil,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Yankee Subs Patrolling Reappear in Waters off U.S. East</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Coast
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense officials say the Soviet Union has
resumed sending nuclear submarines to off America's east coast
after refraining from the patrols for several months.
   The officials, who agreed to discuss the matter only if not
identified, disclosed last week that a lone Soviet ``Yankee'' sub
reappeared during the first week of June inside an Atlantic patrol
zone long favored by the Russians.
   The submarine was replaced by another Yankee after completing
its deployment, suggesting the Soviets intend to maintain the
patrols at least for the time being, the officials said.
   Rear Adm. William O. Studeman, the director of naval
intelligence, acknowledged Friday that the Soviets had resumed
U.S.-coast patrols with the Yankee subs. The Navy's intelligence
office added in a statement, without explanation: ``We anticipate
that Yankees will periodically patrol off our coasts, but not on
the regular basis that had been the case prior to 1987.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___^</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators Call For EPA Action Against Ocean Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's two senators are urging the
Environmental Protection Agency to do more to stop ocean dumping of
medical waste and curb pollution.
   ``Their (EPA's) job is to protect the public health and safety
and they are failing in that job,'' Sen. Bill Bradley, a Democrat,
said Sunday on ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley.''
   Bradley, joined by Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg, the EPA
should set up a medical tracking system that would require
hospitals to keep a record of waste to ensure that it is taken to a
disposal facility.
   Bradley said he has introduced legislation in Congress to set up
a tracking system to guard against a recurrence of what happened
this summer when medical waste including vials of contaminated
blood and used bandages washed up on beaches in New York and New
Jersey.
   Lee Thomas, EPA's administrator, defended his agency's record,
saying, ``It's going to take a lot more than just us.''
</TEXT>
