<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0562,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Stocks Lower In Japan Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei and dollar
figures. Pickup 4th graf pvs ```This week...'''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices fell.
   The dollar opened the week at 133.80 yen, up from last Friday's
133.12 yen close, and finished the day at 133.97 yen. Its high was
134.05 yen Monday and its low was 133.72 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 61.20-point loser during Saturday's half-day
session, continued its slide and closed at 28,253.12 points, down
109.60 points or 0.38 percent.
   Traders attributed the U.S. currency's strength against the yen
to its rise on overseas markets late last week. The dollar rose to
a 19-month high against the West German mark in New York last
Friday, propped up in part by strong earnings and payroll figures
in the July U.S. employment report released by the U.S. Labor
Department last week.
   Speculative mark-selling fueled the dollar's rise, the traders
added.
   Dealers on the stock exchange said sluggishness during the
summer holidays contributed to quiet, thin trading.
   ``This week and next week is the holiday season in Japan,'' said
Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
``The market is very quiet and the trading volume is very thin.''
</TEXT>
