<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FujiClimber     08-08 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuji Climber,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>101-Year-Old Becomes Fuji's Oldest Climber, Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 101-year-old former lumberjack climbed to the top
of Mount Fuji today, breaking his own record as the oldest person
to scale Japan's tallest peak.
   Teiichi Igarashi reached the 12,385-foot summit this morning
after an arduous three-day climb during which he slept in huts
along the trail, Kyodo News Service reported.
   Surrounded by 11 relatives, he climbed steadily, stopping to
rest every 30 seconds and supported by his 64-year-old son
Toshikazu, Kyodo said.
   It takes most adults about six hours to climb the mountain.
   Igarashi has scaled the stately peak 13 times since his wife
died in 1975 and he vowed to make the journey in her memory. He
broke the record for most senior climber in 1983 at age 96.
   ``Owing to the kindness of all, I was able to make the climb
again this year ... thank you very much,'' Kyodo quoted Igarashi as
saying at the summit.
   Igarashi was a lumberjack and forest ranger near his home in
Fukushima, about 150 miles northeast of Tokyo, before he retired 11
years ago at age 90.
   Last August, 91-year-old Hulda Crooks of Loma Linda, California
became the oldest woman to reach the summit of the dormant volcano.
</TEXT>
