<2ND_LINE>PM-Botswana-President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Masire Hurt In Plane Accident Over Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with plane's altitude, purpose of summit, other
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Quett Masire and one of his
aides were injured when an engine on the presidential jet exploded
during a flight to a regional summit meeting in Angola, Masire's
office said today.
   The office said the 10-seater British Aerospace jet made an
emergency landing in the central Angolan town of Cuito Bie about
five minutes after the explosion Sunday afternoon.
   The plane reportedly was flying at 38,000 feet when the blast
occurred, about two hours after it left Gaborone for Angola's
capital, Luanda.
   The engine separated from the plane and fragments of it sprayed
into the cabin, injuring Masire and his chief of protocol, Bashi
Ikiitsing, the office said. Masire's injuries were described as
``minor lacerations'' in his back and he was reported to be
hospitalized in Luanda pending arrangements for him to return to
Gaborone.
   The plane was said to be carrying three crew members and seven
passengers, including Foreign Minister Gaositwe Chiepe and
Presidential Affairs Minister Ponatshego Kedikilwe.
   The Botswanans were scheduled to attend a one-day meeting of
leaders of six southern African states to discuss the latest
developments in negotiations to remove foreign troops from Angola
and end South African rule over South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
</TEXT>
