<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Asia-LuckyDay     08-08 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asia-Lucky Day,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>8-8-88 Sparks Weddings, Parties, Business Openings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese throughout Southeast Asia today
celebrated an auspicious once-in-a-century date _ 8-8-88 _ with a
wave of weddings, business openings and lavish parties.
   Some hospitals geared up for maternity ward gridlock as women
sought to bring their children into the world on the propitious day.
   And merchants spared no effort to use the date to promote
everything from fast food to real estate, while Hong Kong gamblers
tested their luck in a special lottery with a sweetened jackpot.
   Cantonese-speaking Chinese, who represent the vast majority of
Hong Kong's 5.7 million people and have large communities in
Singapore and Malaysia, have long considered eight to bring good
fortune.
   In the Cantonese dialect, the word for eight is ``baat,'' which
sounds like ``faat,'' the word for prosperity.
   That similarity of sound makes Aug. 8, 1988, a momentous
occasion for superstitious Chinese.
   ``Not only the Cantonese, but everyone is celebrating,'' said
Peter Lee at the Pure Mind, one of many restaurants reporting
record bookings for dinner in Malaysia, where more than one-third
of the 16 million people are ethnic Chinese.
   The big event in Hong Kong was a ceremony atop the new Bank of
China local headquarters to mark placement of the final beam in the
1,221-foot structure, which contractors claim is the tallest
building outside the United States and the fifth-tallest in the
world.
   Dignitaries assembled on the 70th floor to split a roast pig and
a keg of sake to celebrate the occasion.
   In Singapore, at least five buildings held official openings
today, including the 920-foot Overseas Union Bank Center.
   Many couples figured the best way to ensure a life of marital
bliss was to get married today.
   The Hong Kong government reported 278 couples registered to get
married today, a 130 percent increase from a week earlier. Scores
more tied the knot in Singapore, where a mass ceremony called
``Wedding Of The Century'' was held at Neptune Theater Restaurant.
   In Malaysia, the Subang Medical Center and other hospitals
reported nurses and doctors were asked to work overtime because of
expectant mothers wanting to give birth today, even if the birth
had to be induced.
   Malaysian doctors, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
women with Caesarean sections scheduled for other days this week
had asked that the procedure be done today.
   Businessmen, meanwhile, launched every conceivable promotion to
mark the date.
   In Singapore, one real estate agent offered ``a lucky discount''
of 8,888 Singapore dollars ($4,356.86) on a three-story house. A
Kentucky Fried Chicken restaurant in Malaysia offered 88 children
who turned 8 this month a meal as well as T-shirts sporting
``8888.''
   Several Hong Kong hotels ran promotions tied to the date. Diners
at the Loong Yuen Chinese Restaurant at the Holiday Inn Golden Mile
ate for free if their total bill included four 8s.
   The colony's lottery also held a special drawing today with a
jackpot enlarged by an additional 3,888,888 Hong Kong dollars
(nearly $500,000).
   Despite all the hoopla, local astrologers who consult the
traditional Chinese calendar dismissed suggestions that today was
the century's luckiest day.
   ``It is a good day, but not a special one,'' sniffed astrologer
``Rocky'' Sung Siu-kwong of Hong Kong in a recent interview.
   Indeed, today's scheduled opening of a new light-rail mass
transit system in Hong Kong was put off after a spate of test-run
accidents, including one that killed an 8-year-old boy.
   Little luck rubbed off on the colony's free-wheeling stock
exchange, where prices dropped slightly in light trading. In Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia, however, the commodity exchange launched trading
in cocoa futures to coincide with the date.
   Jiang Jong Yue, a self-described master of geomancy, palmistry,
astrology and name consultant in Malaysia, cautioned that 8-8-88
may not mean prosperity for all.
   He noted the Cantonese pronounciation for four is ``sei,'' the
same as the word that means to die. Since today's date has four
eights, he advised: ``Tread with caution and contain your greed.''
</TEXT>
