<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RetirementHomeFire     08-08 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retirement Home Fire,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, 21 Hurt in Retirement Home Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLANTATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bedroom fire in a retirement home
killed one resident and sent smoke billowing through the rest of
the building, injuring 17 other residents and four rescuers,
officials said.
   ``It's a tragedy because one loss of life occurred,'' Fire Chief
Robert Pudney said after Sunday night's blaze. ``But it could have
been worse.''
   The fire at the Golden Age Retirement Home in this Fort
Lauderdale suburb was extinguished within 11 minutes, said Pudney,
adding that the fire's cause had not been determined. The home had
23 residents.
   The fire began in the room of a 75-year-old man who had been
warned not to smoke, said the home's owner.
   ``He's done this before,'' said Cherian Samuel. ``Twice we've
taken his lighter away.''
   Flames spread to a bathroom and an adjacent hallway, but the
thick black smoke caused most of the injuries.
   The smoke forced residents outside the building into a driving
rainstorm, where they gasped for air as they stood beneath yellow
tarpaulins awaiting transportation to a hospital.
   Frantic relatives began arriving at the home to search for loved
ones. A police spokesman said as many as 30 relatives awaited news.
   The injured were taken to Plantation General Hospital, Humana
Hospital Bennett and Broward General Medical Center. Most suffered
from smoke inhalation.
   The rescuers _ two police officers, a firefighter and a
paramedic _ also were treated for smoke inhalation.
</TEXT>
