<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland-Violence     08-08 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland-Violence,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Dead In Belfast Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants shot and killed two
men in a Roman Catholic district of Belfast today, police said.
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, accused Protestant
extremists of carrying out the attack.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force, said
the gunmen escaped in a car which was found abandoned in a nearby
Protestant area, Shankhill.
   Police said one of the men was killed while delivering beer to a
Catholic working men's club in the Ardoyne. The other was shot on
the street, they said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility. Sinn Fein, the
outlawed Irish Republican Army's legal wing, accused Protestant
extremists of carrying out a random sectarian attack.
   The killings followed a series of IRA bombings and shootings in
Northern Ireland, Britain and West Germany which left six dead and
37 injured.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule
in Northern Ireland and unite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
