<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Bomb     08-08 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Bomb,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Found Under U.S. Officer's Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A housekeeper found a homemade bomb
that failed to explode under the car of a U.S. Air Force sergeant
near his home outside Clark Air Base, a base spokeswoman said today.
   Explosive experts defused the bomb after it was found early
Sunday under the car of Master Sgt. Francisco S. Calabia, Capt.
Maryellen Jadick said.
   A Filipino police officer, Cpl. Danilo Maniti, said the fuse of
the bomb apparently had been lit since it was partially burned, but
it ``must have been snuffed out by rain.''
   No suspect or motive have been found in the attempted bombing,
according to a statement issued by the base.
   The statement said Calabia told investigators he parked his
station wagon at 6:30 a.m. Saturday under a car port in an off-base
housing area.
   Calabia, whose hometown was not given, said he had not received
any warnings or threats, the statement added.
   The incident occurred at a time of heightened security near the
base.
   Communist rebels in October killed three Americans and a
Filipino outside Clark, which is located in Angeles city, about 50
miles north of Manila.
   More than 40 people have been killed in Angeles since May in
murders that police blame mostly on the rebels.
   An American soldier was shot and killed while jogging near his
home on July 25, but police said the airman's estranged Filipino
wife admitted plotting the killing to collect insurance.
</TEXT>
