<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-T-Shirt     08-08 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-T-Shirt,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Return Confiscated T-Shirt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today returned, with apologies, a
T-shirt they confiscated from a teen-ager because it criticized
military censorship in Israel and angered a crowd of Israelis in a
bus station.
   Tamar Forman, 14, a daughter of U.S. immigrants, said she
planned to continue wearing the white shirt emblazoned in red with
``Freedom of the Press'' in Hebrew, Arabic and English, despite the
controversy it stirred.
   The shirt also bears a mock military censor's stamp and a
picture of a soldier gagging a man, whose hands are tied.
   A policewoman took the shirt from Miss Forman last month after
forcing her to remove it at Jerusalem's central bus station when an
angry crowd of 50 surrounded the girl, cursing her.
   Left-wing legislators said the incident underscored anti-press
feeling in Israel that has intensified during the 8-month-old
Palestinian uprising, in which 237 Arabs and four Israelis have
been killed.
   Miss Forman, who complained to police about the incident last
week, was questioned for 30 minutes today at Jerusalem police
headquarters.
   A policewoman then apologized for the confiscation and returned
the shirt.
   ``The lady said she was sorry and gave me the shirt,'' Miss
Forman said. ``I feel it's good something was done about this, and
I hope this means it won't happen to somebody else.''
   Her mother, Judy Forman, from Trenton, N.J., hugged her daughter
as they left the station and said she was shocked ``that such a
thing could happen to my daughter and in my country, the state of
Israel.''
   Miss Forman said she had worn the shirt several times to school
before the incident. ``I plan to wear it again,'' she added.
   But her father, David, an immigrant from Boston, interrupted to
say: ``Not in the central bus station.''
</TEXT>
