<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalStrike     08-08 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Strike,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement at Public Hospitals May Lead to Private
Sector Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative agreement aimed at averting a
strike by 1,600 nurses at two public hospitals could lead to
settlements in three strikes involving nearly 4,000 private-sector
nurses, Mayor Art Agnos said.
   Local 790 of United Public Employees announced the tentative
agreement Sunday. Ratification would prevent 1,600 nurses from
striking San Francisco General, which handles the poorest and
sickest people in the city, and Laguna Honda Hospital, which cares
for elderly patients, and a half-dozen city clinics, including one
at a jail.
   ``We reached this settlement on time because none of the parties
wanted to add to the health care fears that have permeated this
city'' since the labor disputes began last month, Agnos said.
   ``I call on all the parties in the private-sector disputes to
take a lesson from the public sector here,'' the mayor said.
   Talks with Local 790 continued round-the-clock throughout the
weekend; the settlement was reached at 4:20 a.m. Sunday.
   Details of the pact were not released. The public-sector
division of Service Employees International Union sought to reduce
nurse-patient ratios and improve measures to retain and recruit
nurses.
   Pay was not an issue with the municipal nurses, but
private-sector nurses say increased pay is the main issue in their
strike.
   Agnos said he told his staff last week to try and settle the
dispute before Tuesday's strike deadline in order to prevent adding
to a labor crisis that so far involves eight private hospitals.
Nine hospitals have not been struck.
   Agnos also called for an immediate resumption of bargaining in
the strikes, in which no new talks have been scheduled. He said he
planned to ``very actively, very aggressively'' involve himself and
other city officials in the disputes.
   About 1,700 licensed vocational nurses and hospital workers in
Local 250 of the Hospital and Health Care Workers Union went on
strike July 26 against seven hospitals. More than 2,100 registered
nurses represented by the California Nurses Association struck at
six of those facilities on Aug. 2.
   On Saturday, 130 nurses represented by the CNA and an
undetermined number of service workers represented by Local 250
also went on strike at French Hospital.
   The struck hospitals have remained open.
   The strike by Local 250 is mainly over health benefits and sick
leave. The CNA wants an 11 percent raise for the first year and a
10 percent raise in the second year of a two-year contract.
   The hospitals are negotiating as a group called Affiliated
Hospitals and have offered 18 percent raises over 31 months, which
would cost the affected six hospitals $40 million. Talks with
French Hospital employees are separate from the other negotiations.
 
</TEXT>
