<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RegattaAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0479 08-08 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Regatta Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Racing Boat Crashes Into Crowd, Injures 23</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to reduce injury count from 24 to 23,
three still critical, add description of injuries, picking up 5th
graf pvs, `Wood, 23 ....' SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Surovchak was ...,'
to edit.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos PG1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A racing boat apparently snagged debris during
a race before it flew out of control into a crowd of spectators
along the Allegheny River, injuring 23, authorities said.
   The 1,100-pound, 16-foot boat driven by Robert Wood suddenly
became airborne, veered sharply to the right and slammed into the
crowd near Three Rivers Stadium during Sunday's 11th annual Three
Rivers Regatta, which drew 100,000 people.
   Eleven of the injured were children.
   This morning, hospitals treating the victims reported three
people still in critical condition. One person originally counted
among the race accident victims was injured separately while diving
in the river, said a spokeswoman for one of the five hospitals that
treated the injured.
   Police spokeswoman Margaret Rizza said the injuries included
open fractures, abrasions and severe blunt injuries to the chest,
stomach and head.
   Wood, 23, of North Peterborough, Ontario, suffered minor
injuries and shock, said the race medical director, Barry Carras.
   The accident occurred in choppy water during the seventh lap of
the 50-lap Champion Spark Plug Grand Prix race.
   The 15-boat race, sponsored by the U.S. Formula One Racing
Association Inc., was the highlight of the regatta.
   Spectators lining the 1.2-mile course said the accident happened
so quickly they didn't immediately figure out what had happened.
   ``I was watching the lead boats going around, and I looked up
and saw (Wood's boat) headed right at us about 50 feet out,'' said
Patrick Heyden of Butler County.
   ``The front end lifted and it started coming toward us,'' said
Robert Surovchak, 21, of suburban Bethel Park. ``We had about 10 or
15 seconds to get out of the way, but some of the people didn't
realize what was going on and they got hit.''
   Surovchak was not hurt, but his girlfriend, Julie Saver, 19, of
Pittsburgh, who had been standing beside him, was hospitalized in
serious condition at Allegheny General.
   The race was restarted two hours later, after paramedics
transported the injured from Roberto Clemente Park to five
hospitals. The rest of the race was limited to 20 laps.
   Race officials said Wood's propeller apparently snagged some
debris and came off, causing the boat to lose control and spin
wildly into the crowd at a 90-degree angle. The boat landed on its
side with the engine toward the spectators.
   Another driver in the race, John Provich, 44, of Ambridge, said
authorities recovered a railroad tie from the river with propeller
marks on it. He speculated that Woods' boat hit the railroad tie.
   Police Lt. Leo O'Neill described the wood as ``a rather large
log.''
   ``It was just one of the pieces of debris that was pulled from
the river in that vicinity,'' O'Neill said. ``At this point the
investigation is very broad and we're looking into all aspects.''
   Police said they didn't know how long it would take detectives
and officials of the U.S. Coast Guard to complete the investigation.
   Witnesses said the boat's engines were off when it hit the
riverbank at about 40 mph. But race officials said they did not
know the boat's speed.
   Formula One boats, which have eight- and six-cylinder engines
and weigh up to 1,000 pounds, are the fastest outboard powered race
boats. Drivers can reach more than 140 mph on straightaways and 90
mph on turns.
</TEXT>
