<HEAD>Residents Return Home After Accident, Gas Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELSBERRY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 600 evacuees have returned home and
cleanup has begun in the aftermath of a train derailment in which
14 cars crashed into a diesel fuel tank that exploded and burned
for nine hours.
   A tank storing anhydrous ammonia was punctured in the Saturday
accident and leaked dangerous fumes, said Troy Fire Chief Gerald
Cherry.
   Several firefighters suffered minor injuries, but no injuries
were reported by residents or the train's crew.
   A preliminary investigation indicated a bearing apparently
burned off a wheel on one car, causing the derailment, said Brian
Sweeney, a spokesman for Burlington Northern Railroad.
   People who were forced to spend Saturday night in a church and
school near this eastern Missouri town were allowed back into their
homes about 11 a.m. Sunday.
   ``I'm worn out,'' said Virginia Metts, 77, who spent Saturday
night at a motel. ``If I'd known how long it would be, I would have
taken some needlepoint or something.''
   The train was traveling from Galesburg, Ill., to St. Louis.
