<HEAD>Ortega Heads To Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega left today on
a surprise visit to Panama for talks with officials of that
country's military-dominated regime, the newspaper Barricada said.
   Barricada, which is run by Ortega's leftist Sandinista National
Liberation Front, cited sources at the Information and Press
Ministry as saying that Ortega ``will hold talks at the highest
level with representatives of the Panamanian government.''
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, chief of Panama's Defense Force,
currently holds power in Panama. The United States has indicted him
on drug smuggling and money laundering charges and has imposed
economic sanctions on the country in an effort to oust Noriega.
   Barricada gave no details, but sources in Panama, who insisted
on anonymity, said Ortega was scheduled to arrive in Panama City at
midday.
   For security reasons, Nicaraguan government officials did not
disclose the Sandinista leader's schedule, saying only that Ortega
will travel to Ecuador on Wednesday to attend the inauguration of
President Rodrigo Borja.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who is on a South
American tour, also is scheduled to attend the inauguration. State
Department officials said there were no plans for any meeting
between the two men.
   In Ecuador, the newspaper said, Ortega will ``officially
re-establish diplomatic relations between the two countries.''
Outgoing President Leon Febres Cordero of Ecuador broke diplomatic
ties in 1985, saying a statement Ortega had made was offensive.
   Borja invited Ortega to the inauguration and said one of his
first acts in office will be to re-establish relations with
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
