<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WesternFires     08-08 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Western Fires,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Fire Grows Overnight, Authorities Considering Evacuations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast-moving forest fire in Oregon grew by more than half
overnight to 11,000 acres, while cooler temperatures and higher
humidity helped firefighters in Yellowstone National Park halt the
spread of wildfires there.
   Authorities were considering whether to evacuate a popular
tourist area 25 miles southeast of Bend, Ore., because of the fire
in Deschutes National Forest. The fire continued to burn out of
control this morning despite the efforts of more than 1,000
firefighters.
   The Paulina fire, pushed by winds and low humidity, consumed
4,000 acres of mostly dead lodgepole pine overnight, officials said.
   Laurie Johnson, a U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman, said it was
possible the fire could reach the rim of Newberry Crater today.
   ``If this should happen, spot fires might start within the
crater near East and Paulina lakes,'' Johnson said. ``There's no
reason to panic. The fire is still a ways away.''
   Smoke from the human-caused blaze could be seen as far away as
Idaho.
   ``We've had columns (of smoke) up to three miles high,'' Johnson
said.
   At Yellowstone, some 1,000 firefighters halted the movement of a
19,600-acre blaze toward a religious settlement.
   ``The fires have slowed down,'' park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo
said this morning. ``I know we did not see significant increase in
acreage (overnight), and all the fires continue to be contained
within the park boundaries.''
   Much of the smoke that has billowed from the fires since late
June has begun to lift, unveiling acres and acres of green trees
that somehow managed to survive flames, she said.
   While some 180,000 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park have been
affected by the fires, Anzelmo said once all the smoke clears, the
stands of untouched trees will reduce the number of acres actually
charred.
   On the Fan fire burning in Yellowstone's northwestern corner,
firefighters managed to stop the northern movement of the fire and
keep it out of southern Montana property owned by the Church
Universal and Triumphant.
   Church officials have threatened to sue the National Park
Service if the blaze, which has stalled for several days at about a
quarter-mile from the Yellowstone border, crosses onto their land.
Last week, week church members stood before the flames and prayed
in an attempt to redirect the fire.
   In Idaho, crews continued to mop up the hot spots inside the
fire line on the 1,500-acre Spring Canyon II fire.
   ``We're hoping the weather will stay cool and humidity will stay
up for the next few days,'' spokeman Gary Cornell said.
   Firefighters contained the blaze, which is burning in the
Targhee National Forest near the Wyoming border, Saturday evening.
Officials said they hope to have the fire under control by tonight.
</TEXT>
