<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0535,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Announces Cease-Fire in Angolan War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with detail, background. No pickup. Adds
byline. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today declared an
immediate cease-fire in the 13-year Angolan war and set Nov. 1 as
the date it plans to begin pulling out of neighboring South-West
Africa.
   However, Foreign Minister Pik Botha said further negotiations
are necessary to determine a timetable for withdrawal of Cuban
troops from Angola and the granting of independence to South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia.
   ``This is the first step of a very long, arduous road to
peace,'' Botha told a news conference.
   Cuba, Angola and the United States also were expected to issue
statements today following last week's fifth round of U.S.-mediated
peace talks.
   Botha said South Africa planned to pull its estimated 3,000
troops out of Angola by Sept. 1.
   South Africa, along with the United States, backs the UNITA
rebel movement in its 13-year-old fight against the Angolan
government. Angola is backed by an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops.
   South Africa has an estimated 50,000 troops in Namibia, and
Botha said withdrawal would begin Nov. 1. But he said the countries
involved must first agree on a single date for the total withdrawal
of Cuban troops from Angola and independence for Namibia.
   The parties plan a sixth round of talks the week of Aug. 22 to
try to resolve the matter. The site of the talks was not announced.
   South Africa has said it will grant Namibia independence next
June 1 if all Cuban forces have left Angola by that date. Cuba,
however, has offered in previous talks to withdraw over four years.
   Today's announcement suggested the two sides were closer to
agreeing on a mutual date than at any time previously.
   Botha said South Africa had invited U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar to South Africa to discuss Namibian
independence.
   ``It's imperative that the secretary general visit South Africa
urgently,'' Botha said.
   The peace talks began in London in May. In the fifth round, held
last week in Geneva, negotiators reportedly agreed on a cease-fire
between South African and Cuban-Angolan forces as well as a mutual
pullback of troops. Details of the agreement were withheld.
   The parties have reached no public agreement on the role of
UNITA, SWAPO or the African National Congress, the main black group
fighting white rule in South Africa. South Africa has called for
the dismantling of seven guerrilla camps it says are operated in
Angola by the outlawed ANC.
   South Africa's mandate over Namibia was terminated by the United
Nations in 1966, but it has retained control over the territory in
defiance of several Security Council resolutions.
   The state-run South African Broadcasting Corp., in a commentary
today, described the current diplomatic climate as ``one that would
hardly have been conceivable just a few months ago.''
   However, it said major problems remained unresolved in regard to
implementation of the U.N. plan for elections in Namibia.
   ``The very substantial costs associated with the plan have
caught some of the parties unawares,'' the report said. ``Apart
from the $600 million needed for organizing U.N.-sponsored
elections, guarantees will have to be found for replacing the $120
million (in) annual economic aid ... that South Africa has borne
until now.''
</TEXT>
