<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0412 08-08 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0412,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Blasts Democrats, Suggests Reagan May Appear With Him at
Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comments, prepared remarks in top 12 grafs,
picking up in 5th graf pvs, The Bush; cuts last 6 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLELANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush criticized the Democrats'
platform as ``a document of deceit'' today and suggested there
still may be a chance that he and President Reagan will appear
together at the Republican National Convention next week.
   Initial plans called for Reagan to leave New Orleans before Bush
returns next Tuesday. However, the vice president told reporters on
Air Force II that he would view such a joint appearance as a plus
for his campaign.
   Bush, trying to put his stamp on the GOP platform, flew to the
Republicans' convention city today to call for ``a statement of
solutions'' that he said would cotrast with the invisible policies
of rival Michael Dukakis.
   ``He's the stealth candidate,'' the vice president said in
prepared remarks. ``For while he can't decide about the stealth
bomber, he favors instead stealth policies _ they can be neither
seen nor heard.''
   ``His campaign jets from place to place, but no issues show up
on the radar screen.''
   Besides testifying before the platform committee, Bush was also
to tour the Superdome, where he will be formally nominated next
week as his party's presidential candidate.
   ``Their nominee spoke for 50 minutes in Atlanta and failed to
mention the most important issue of our time: how to make the world
a safer place,'' Bush said.
   ``We need to make this campaign a plan for the future, a
statement of solutions, not an exercise in evasion,'' he said. ``We
should make our principles and our policies crystal clear to the
American people.''
   Bush ran through a litany of positions he had espoused during
his campaign, suggesting their inclusion in the platform.
   These ranged from tax credits for child care to a ban on
offshore dumping, a reduction in the capital gains tax and
imposition of the death penalty for drug kingpins.
   ``If we want to stop our kids from putting drugs in their veins,
they must first have good ideas in their heads and moral character
in their hearts,'' he said.
   On Sunday, Bush spoke with reporters on the grounds of St. Ann's
Episcopal Church in Kennebunkport, Maine, after attending services
with 22 members of his family: his wife, Barbara; his 87-year-old
mother, Dorothy; his five adult children, their spouses and his 10
grandchildren.
   The Bush clan, which occupied the two front pews of the small
oceanfront church, later posed for family photographs outside and
taped television commercials for the fall campaign.
   Bush denied accusations from the Dukakis campaign that he was
shying away from debates.
   ``Not only do I want debates, but I have to because I've got to
get him to stand by his record,'' Bush said.``We've got to spell
these differences out and debates are a good way to do it,'' he
said.
   But Bush was vague on when _ and how often _ he would be willing
to debate Dukakis.
   ``There'll be more than one debate, but how many ... has not
been sorted out yet,'' he said.
   Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich said Bush was only making
a display of bravado for the television cameras and should agree to
debate Sept. 14 in Annapolis, the first of three dates set by a
bipartisan commission.
   Dukakis campaign officials have criticized Bush for refusing to
commit himself to the schedule of debates set by the advisory
commission.
   ``It's time to dock the motorboat in Kennebunkport and launch
the debate in Annapolis,'' Estrich said Sunday.
   Meanwhile, Bush's designated campaign chairman, Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, suggested Bush might further distance
himself from positions embraced by the Reagan administration once
he is formally nominated.
   Baker, who is resigning his Cabinet post next week, said Bush
already has started to develop his ``own individual persona.''
   ``He will be seen in an entirely different light once he is his
party's nominee, a bit more free to speak out, speak his own mind,
and speak out on issues distinct and different from the
administration,'' Baker said on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press.''
   Baker also said he did not view Bush's campaign as troubled _
despite low ratings in recent public opinion polls.
   ``But I would agree there are a large number of unfavorables out
there,'' Baker said.
   He suggested the gap corresponded to the ``disapproval rating of
the administration, of the president'' and that it would narrow as
the election approaches.
</TEXT>
