<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--WasteShip     08-08 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Waste Ship,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team Begins Unloading Toxic Waste From Syrian Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENOA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts began work Monday to unload from a
Syrian ship 12,000 drums of a toxic substance that shippers have
been trying to dispose of for more than a year.
   Several rusty, leaking drums from the freighter Zanoobia were
being put into larger containers while experts began tests on the
waste, said Giuseppe Francese, head of the Genoa port.
   Unloading the drums will take from two to three months, he said.
   The Zanoobia brought the waste back to Italy two months ago
after foreign countries refused to accept it.
   The Italian state-controlled company Castalia, which won a $6
million contract to dispose of the waste, did not make public the
final destination of the unidentified toxic material, although port
sources said the material may be sent abroad to be incinerated.
   The waste, produced by Italian firms, was returned to Italy
after unsuccessful attempts to dump it in Djibouti, Venezuela and
Syria.
</TEXT>
