<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TropicalWeather 4thLd-Writethru a0524 08-08 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0524,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecasters Eyeing Tropical Depression Over Southeast Louisiana</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with noon EDT position on Beryl, Alberto
dissolving off the Canadian coast.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Beryl, the second named storm of the
Atlantic hurricane season, hugged the Louisiana coast today,
forcing evacuations from oil rigs in the Gulf of Mexico, while the
season's first tropical storm fizzled out near the Canadian coast.
   Beryl was upgraded today from a tropical depression after its
winds strengthened, reaching close to 45 mph with gusts up to 55
mph. The storm strengthened as it drifted closer to the warm waters
of the Gulf of Mexico. Oil companies evacuated more than 2,000
workers from oil rigs in southern Louisiana and the Gulf.
   The tropical storm had a center near latitude 29.5 north and
longitude 89.3 west. It was drifting southeastward at less than 5
mph, and its movement was expected to be slow and erratic through
Tuesday. The storm's center was about 50 miles southeast of New
Orleans.
   ``There is some likelihood it could strengthen,'' said Mark
Zimmer of the National Hurricane Center in Miami. ``It's not
drifting inland, it's drifting away from land, but very slowly.''
   Zimmer said the immediate danger from Beryl was to shipping and
oil rigs along the Gulf coast. People on the coast, he said, should
watch for tides of up to three feet above normal.
   Tropical storm warnings were in effect from Morgan City, La., to
Pensacola, Fla., and small craft from Port O'Connor, Texas,
eastward to Appalachicola, Fla., should remain in port, the center
said.
   ``Right now we're advising people to listen to their radios and
watch television,'' said Andy Valence, mayor of Grand Isle, La.,
about 40 miles south of New Orleans in the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``It's highly unusual for depressions to form over land. Most of
the time they get their start way out in the middle of the ocean,''
said Jim Gross, a forecaster at the National Hurricane Center in
Miami. ``We don't have a lot of experience with systems that form
this way.''
   A tropical weather system becomes a named storm when its winds
hit 39 mph, and a hurricane when wind velocity reaches 74 mph.
   The storm chiefly affected those out on oil rigs in the Gulf,
the weather service said.
   Chevron spokesman Jonathan Lifa said about 2,000 workers were
being evacuated early today. All employees at facilities at Venice
and Leesville in Plaquemines Parish were evacuated by boat and
helicopter, while non-essential personnel were removed from a
facility at Morgan City.
   Lifa said the storm became more threatening as it neared the
gulf.
   ``News reports (over the weekend) were that the center was
partially onshore and partially offshore, so we didn't have high
winds to worry about,'' Lifa said. ``The concern is that the more
it gets into the gulf, the more winds pick up. It is something we
are very concerned about.''
   Texaco spokesman Max Hebert said an unknown number of workers
were taken off Texaco rigs in the Gulf of Mexico today.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer First Class Bob Morehead said the
Coast Guard has not carried out any evacuations, but the storm's
winds buffeted helicopters and created choppy seas for its ships.
   The storm didn't appear to affect Republicans gathering in New
Orleans for their national convention next week; about 2 percent,
or 105, of the delegates have arrived to serve on various
pre-convention panels and committees, said Connie Thumma,
co-director of media operations for the convention.
   ``Better this week than next week,'' said Bill Phillips, the
convention manager.
   The storm was unlikely to have any effect on today's visit by
Vice President George Bush, who landed in New Orleans this morning
for an appearance at GOP platform sessions, said Phillips. Bush
also planned a stop at the Superdome, site of the convention.
   ``Right now New Orleans is mostly getting the weaker western
side of the storm. The folks that have been getting the worst of it
are those south of New Orleans,'' said meteorologist Mike Koziara.
   Meanwhile Alberto, the season's first named storm, fizzled out
today off the Canadian coast, Zimmer said.
   ``It's lost its tropical characteristics,'' he said. ``Now it's
just a storm.'' The center will no longer issue bulletins on it, he
said.
   Shortly after noon Sunday, the forecasters had issued a tropical
storm warning for Maine's coast from Bar Harbor to Eastport, but
they canceled it less than six hours later.
   The storm was most likely to make landfall at Yarmouth, Halifax
or Eddy Point, Nova Scotia, forecasters said.
   Typically, there are 10 named storms during the six-month
hurricane season, which begins June 1. Last year, there were only
three hurricanes and four tropical storms in the Atlantic.
</TEXT>
