<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Vincennes-Rescue     08-08 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes-Rescue,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship in Plane Shootdown Saves Stranded Iranian Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy cruiser that mistakenly shot
down an Iranian airliner last month rescued five Iranian fishermen
who had been adrift at sea for more than a week, the Pentagon said
Monday.
   The USS Vincennes spotted the five men drifting in a small
dinghy around 9 p.m. EDT Sunday in the Gulf of Oman, said Lt. Col.
Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman.
   At the time, the Vincennes was on a routine patrol in the Gulf
of Oman just below the entrance to the Persian Gulf at the Strait
of Hormuz, Schneider added.
   ``Their fishing boat had reportedly sunk eight days before and
they were afloat in a small dinghy,'' the spokesman said.
   ``The fishermen were dehydrated and suffered from hypothermia
and body rash. The USS Vincennes administered emergency medical
care and is currently holding them on board until arrangements can
be made for their safe return.''
   Schneider said the five men had in their possession ``a ship's
registration that provided certain information about the fishing
vessel and crew.''
   The spokesman declined to predict when the men would depart,
saying, ``Their return is being handled through diplomatic
channels.''
   The Vincennes took up patrol duties just outside the Persian
Gulf not long after it accidently shot down an Iranian Airbus on
July 3, killing all 290 aboard.
   The guided-missile cruiser had just emerged from a battle with
Iranian gunboats when its radar operators detected what they
thought was an Iranian F-14 fighter. According to a still-secret
Pentagon report, the stress of first-time combat contributed to
crew errors in tracking and targeting the airliner.
</TEXT>
