<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Vagrants     08-08 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Vagrants,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Vagrants Warned or Arrested in Byelorussia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in the Soviet republic of Byelorussia
have arrested or given official warnings for vagrancy to more than
40,000 people in the past four years, a newspaper report said.
   The report in Saturday's Sovietskaya Byelorussia, received
Monday in Moscow, said more than half of the people arrested for
vagrancy had held jobs but either were fired or quit voluntarily
when they started wandering.
   The newspaper added that many others had lost families and homes
while imprisoned and are faced with a suspicious society that does
not want to give them a second chance.
   ``Being isolated from society, many of them lose their families,
their residence permits, homes, and when they return work
collectives often do not wish to accept them and recognize them as
first-class citizens,'' the report said.
   Soviet media have begun paying more attention to social problems
such as homelessness and vagrancy in the more open atmosphere
created by Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost.
   The numbers cited by Sovietskaya Byelorussia _ 8,000 arrests and
35,000 warnings _ were surprisingly large for the republic of 10
million people. There was no indication how they might compare with
figures in other areas of the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union guarantees a job and a place to live for all of
its citizens, and proclaims that as one of the benefits of the
Soviet system.
   The newspaper said many of the vagrants turn to theft of
government or personal property.
   More than 80 percent of the vagrants are men, the newspaper
said. Three- quarters of the men and half of the women are under
30. Half have a high school education, but every sixth vagrant has
specialized high school or technical training, it said.
</TEXT>
