<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietInspectors     08-08 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors Check Cruise Missile Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors arrived Monday to
visit a cruise missile base and a repair shop to check compliance
with the superpower treaty to remove ground-launched medium-range
nuclear missiles from Europe.
   U.S. officials said the 20 Soviets on Tuesday will visit
Florennes air base, 40 miles south of here and a Belgian plant, 10
miles north of Florennes, which the United States uses as a repair
and maintenance shop for its European-based cruise missiles.
   U.S. officials said the United States has deployed 20 cruise
missiles at Florennes and 55 cruise missiles and their launch
canisters are at the plant at Gosselies which belongs to Sabca, an
aviation construction company.
   The Soviet inspectors, led by Viacheslav S. Lyebedev, arrived at
Brussels' Abelag airport and were welcomed by Belgian officials;
U.S. Air Force Col. John Fer, head of the On-Site Inspection
Agency's European field office at Rhein-Main Air Base in West
Germany; and his deputy, U.S. Army Lt. Col Scott G. Lang.
   Under the U.S.-Soviet accord, the United States and the Soviet
Union will remove all ground-launched nuclear missiles with a range
of between 300 and 3,400 miles.
   The treaty, which removes an entire class of nuclear arms, said
Lyebedev, ``marks the beginning of an unprecedented stage in the
history of mankind.''
   ``We will perform our duties in strict compliance with the
provisions of the treaty,'' said Lyebedev, speaking through an
interpreter.
   Fer said the inspections ``are serious business. It is a task we
accept with commitment.''
   In recent weeks, Soviet inspectors have visited U.S. missile
sites and related installations in Britain, West Germany, the
Netherlands and the United States. Italy is the only European
nation not yet visited by Soviet inspectors.
   U.S. inspectors have already visited sites in the Soviet Union,
East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   The Florennes air base houses the 485th U.S. Tactical Missile
Wing. Under NATO's 1979 decision to deploy 572 cruise and
Pershing-2 missiles in the five European nations, 48 cruise
missiles were to be based at Florennes.
   The repair plant at Gosselies belongs to the Belgian firm of
Sabca, a Belgiasn aviation construction firm, and does maintenance
and control checks on unarmed missiles from Belgium, West Germany,
Britain, Italy and the Netherlands.
   Under the treaty, the United States and the Soviet Union agreed
to remove hundreds of ground-launched medium- and shorter-range
missiles in a three-year period and not to produce or test such
weapons after that. The treaty also gives each party on-site
inspection rights for 13 years.
   The treaty covers U.S. cruise, Pershing-1A and Pershing-2
missiles and Soviet SS-20, SS-4, SS-5, SS-12 and SS-23 missiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0076 </DOCNO>
