<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Plot,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nephew of Late Kenyan President Jailed Over Plot to Topple
Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nephew of the late President Jomo
Kenyatta pleaded guilty Monday to plotting to overthrow the
government, and he was sentenced to six years in jail.
   Andrew Kibathi Muigai entered the plea before Chief Magistrate
Joseph Mango during a 20-minute proceeding.
   Muigai is the brother of former Assistant Minister of Health
Ngengi Muigai. Their father, James Muigai, was the brother of Jomo
Kenyatta, Kenya's first president who died in 1978.
   Andrew Muigai, 35, was accused of being a member of Mwakenya, a
Marxist underground group trying to bring down the government of
President Daniel arap Moi.
   More than 80 people, including journalists, civil servants and
university lecturers and students, have been jailed after admitting
links with the group. Human rights groups such as Amnesty
International claim the confessions are coerced.
   Mwakenya is a Swahili acronym for the Union of Nationalists to
Liberate Kenya. The group says in its literature that its aim is to
bring down Moi's capitalist government and to redistribute the
wealth.
   Muigai admitted he had held a secret meeting with exiled
politician Koigi wa Wamwere, a former member of Parliament who fled
Kenya for Norway in 1986 and is a frequent critic of the Moi
government. Muigai said his meeting with Wamwere occurred Jan. 25
at the town of Namanga on the Kenya-Tanzania border.
</TEXT>
