<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--SAfrica-University,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classes Suspended For a Week At Cape Town Campus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All classes at the University of
the Western Cape have been suspended this week following
confrontations linked to student demands for the ouster of a law
lecturer, a school official said.
   The step was announced Sunday night by Jakes Gerwel, chief
administrator of the predominantly mixed-race university, after
meetings with senior administrators and faculty.
   Last week, a group of students barged into the office of the law
school dean to demand the ouster of a junior lecturer who
purportedly was considered unhelpful to first-year students.
   Subsequently, students at a meeting voted to launch a
campus-wide class boycott, and there were reports that some
students disregarding the boycott call were assaulted.
   Gerwel said classes were being suspended this week ``to give the
university time to reflect.''
   Western Cape, with an enrollment of about 11,000, has evolved
into South Africa's most militant university. The administration
and faculty, as well as the student body, are active opponents of
apartheid, the government's policy of racial separation.
</TEXT>
