<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Ferry     08-08 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Ferry,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Currents Slow Search For Bodies After Ferry Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATIHAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong currents and muddy waters hampered
efforts Monday to find the bodies of more than 400 people missing
and presumed dead after a ferry capsized on the Ganges River, a
rescue official said.
   It was India's worst boat disaster, according to the United News
of India news agency.
   Only 23 bodies were found by Monday, officials and witnesses
said, including seven that were swept as far as 15 miles downstream
by the waters of the flood-swollen river at Katihar, about 650
miles east of New Delhi.
   About 100 people swam to safety or were rescued by villagers
after the 35-year-old ferry overturned Saturday when it hit a sand
bar while crossing the river.
   Most of the passengers were pilgrims crossing the river Hindus
consider sacred on their way to a shrine in the town of Deoghar.
   ``Now it is becoming clear that some 400 people must have died
in the accident,'' said Jyoti Prasad Mullick, vice chairman of the
local municipal board.
   Indian Navy divers Monday made their first attempt to reach the
boat, which is resting in water up to 30 feet deep. But the divers
were slowed by strong currents and muddy water, said H.S. Pathak,
head of the diving team.
   Katihar Commissioner Madan Mohan Singh said authorities plan to
break open the submerged two-deck ferry to retrieve the bodies.
   Soldiers on a boat used long bamboo poles to try to poke the
bodies out of the vessel.
   About 5,000 villagers and relatives of missing passengers Monday
gathered in drizzling rain on the banks of the Ganges to watch the
operation, according to Katihar Police Inspector N. Kumar.
   The ferry had a capacity to carry about 160 people, but 535
tickets were sold for the trip, according to dockworkers, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   ``It was badly overcrowded,'' said an official, who requested
anonymity. ``Many lives could have been saved if the ferry had
carried water safety equipment such as life jackets.''
   Survivors said they protested when 150 bags of wheat were loaded
on the vessel, which began wavering and capsized about 100 yards
from shore.
   Boat accidents are common in India during the annual monsoon
rains when major rivers overflow their banks.
   At least 150 people died on July 5, 1970, when a boat capsized
in Krishna River in eastern India.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
