<HEAD>East Germans, Soviets Begin Joint Maneuvers; NATO Games Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 14,500 Soviet and East German troops began
joint manuevers Monday in central East Germany, the state-run East
German ADN news agency reported.
   ADN said the joint exercise in the region of Burg, Jessen,
Luebbenau, Teupitz and Luckenwalde, south of Berlin, was under the
command of Soviet General Alexander Kozlov. It did not say how long
the war games would last.
   In Casteau, Belgium, meanwhile, NATO said about 250,000
soldiers, including 17,000 from the United States, will take part
in the 16-nation alliance's annual fall maneuvers in Europe.
   NATO's military wing, Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe,
said the soldiers will take part in 20 exercises as part of the
Autumn Forge series.
   The operations range from Bar Frost near the Arctic Circle to
maneuvers throughout the Mediterranean, it said.
   The statement said 17,000 troops from the United States' 1st
Infantry Division at Fort Riley, Kan., will take part in the annual
Reforger _ Return of Forces to Germany _ exercise.
   The U.S. soldiers, the statement said, will join nearly 100,000
troops in a field training maneuver called Certain Challenge in
southern Germany.
