<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chambers     08-08 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owner of Bar Sued in Jennifer Levin's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a young woman strangled in
Central Park charged in a $25 million lawsuit Monday that a tavern
owner used her killer to lure underage girls to his bar.
   Steven and Ellen Levin charged that Dorrian's Red Hand, owned by
Jack Dorrian, was a ``cesspool of corruption.''
   They alleged that Dorrian served Robert Chambers alcohol on Aug.
26, 1986, the morning he killed their daughter, Jennifer, even
though he was too young to drink.
   They charged that Dorrian served Chambers ``as part and parcel
of a scheme or plan ... to parade Chambers as a decoy and an
enticement for the patronage of his social group and those of
approximately similar age, and more particularly, of the feminine
portion thereof.''
   Chambers, 21, is serving a five- to 15-year sentence for killing
Miss Levin. He pleaded guilty March 25 to first-degree manslaughter
while a jury was deliberating murder charges against him following
his two-month murder trial.
   Chambers strangled Miss Levin, 18, and left her nearly naked and
battered body sprawled beneath a crabapple tree behind the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. A bicyclist discovered the body.
   During the trial, Dorrian put up his $700,000 home to secure a
total of $157,500 bail for Chambers. He said he did it because he
felt sorry for Chambers' mother, Phyllis.
   The Levins' suit, which names Dorrian, his wife Carol, and the
restaurant-bar, charges the defendants were ``negligent, careless
and reckless'' in ``making possible and causing'' the conduct that
led to Miss Levin's death.
   Dorrian called the Levin's allegations ``absolutely
ridiculous.'' He has said that recent legal action against him has
been vindictive because he helped the Chambers family after Miss
Levin was killed.
   Dorrian's liquor license was suspended for two 10-day periods in
1988 for serving alcohol to underage patrons.
   In July, the Levins filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against
Chambers for the wrongful death of their daughter. Their lawyer,
Harry Lipsig, said the lawsuit would hang like a ``Sword of
Damocles'' over Chambers if he should ever come into any money.
</TEXT>
