<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Republicans-Calero     08-08 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Republicans-Calero,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Leader Criticizes Dukakis; Ortega Feels the Opposite</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero, seeking a
renewed pledge of support from the Republican Party, said Monday
that Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis doesn't understand the
Nicaraguan Sandinistas and ``the threat they represent.''
   ``He doesn't understand that they are bent on not only
subjecting the Nicaraguan people but to expanding their revolution
throughout Central America. Otherwise he wouldn't be speaking the
way he has,'' the Nicaraguan rebel leader said after addressing the
Republican Platform Committee.
   On the other side, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega says he
found Dukakis' acceptance speech at the Democratic National
Convention inspiring and believes the Sandinista government ``can
trust Dukakis' administrative ability and the administrative
ability of a future Democratic administration to change U.S.
policy.''
   Ortega, quoted in the August issue of Forbes magazine, said, ``I
think that with Dukakis we could have better conditions to work for
a new dialogue. However, I think Mr. Dukakis will doubtless
encounter some serious obstacles; he will be subjected to
McCarthyist pressures from the die-hard conservatives.''
   In New Orleans today, Contra leader Calero made his negative
comments about Dukakis after asking a GOP platform committee to
renew the party's support of the Nicaraguan rebels.
   The platform, to be presented to the convention next week, is
expected to include language similar the party's 1984 statement of
support for the Contras.
   During his testimony, Calero avoided referring specifically to
Dukakis, saying only that many Americans seem to lack understanding
about the situation in his homeland.
   Questioned later by reporters, however, Calero said of Dukakis,
who opposes aid to the Contras, ``He doesn't understand the
Sandinistas apparently. He does not understand the threat they
represent.''
   Calero, one of seven directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance,
said if Congress would give ``proper support'' the Contras could
bring down the Sandinista government in a year. He said Sandinista
soldiers would defect and the Contras could not only revive their
dispersed forces of 17,000, but double their numbers in a few
months.
   Critics see that outlook as overly optimistic, not only because
of the uphill congressional battle for funds but in light of recent
in-fighting among the Contra factions and defection of the southern
fighting faction from the larger force.
   Calero said a repeat of the $100 million in military and
humanitarian aid approved in 1986 could turn the tide for the
weakened Contras and pressure the Sandinistas back to a serious
negotiating posture.
   Senate Republicans and Democrats are pondering a resumption of
military aid to the Contras, but the figures under consideration
generally are much lower.
   Without the aid, Calero told the platform hearing, ``the chances
are very dim'' for peace negotiations to resume.
   He told the platform committee that the Contras are committed to
peace through negotiation, although the rebel leaders have rejected
Sandinista proposals to resume peace talks that broke off June 9
without agreement. In late June, the Nicaraguan government offered
to have talks in Miami but the Contras said the talks should be in
a Central American country.
   In Congress, an aid package proposed by Senate Democratic leader
Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia, was considered Monday by Senate
Republicans.
   It would allow release of $16 million in military aid this fall
if President Reagan certified that the Nicaraguan government had
disrupted the peace and stability of Central America.
   Calero termed the $27 million humanitarian aid package currently
proposed by Senate leaders _ with the $16 million in stockpiled
military supplies releaseable by separate presidential and
congressional approval _ ``totally inadequate.''
</TEXT>
