<DOCNO> AP880808-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SpaceShuttle     08-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Test Firing Reset For Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA officials said Monday that a
new valve had tested out satisfactorily in the space shuttle
Discovery's engine compartment and they rescheduled the ship's
oft-postponed main engine test firing for Wednesday.
   The countdown for the test will begin at 6:10 p.m. EDT Tuesday.
The 22-second engine firing is set for 7:30 a.m.
   The engine test was halted Thursday in the last second when a
sensor reported that a valve had not closed as it was supposed to.
Engineers determined that the sensor, not the valve, was
malfunctioning but decided to replace both parts as a unit.
   That required erecting scaffolding, removing extensive plumbing
and wiring and gaining access to the crowded engine compartment.
The changeout was completed by midnight Saturday. The work of
reconnecting and testing all parts and removing the work platforms
was being completed Monday.
   ``Work on changing the hydrogen fuel bleed valve in Discovery's
number two main engine went better than expected over the
weekend,'' the space agency announced Monday, in setting the new
test date.
   ``The recovery from the problem on Thursday shows that the team
is working smoothly and I am expecting an on-time engine firing on
Wednesday morning,'' said Hugh Harris, a spokesman for NASA's
Kennedy Space Center.
   All three of Discovery's engines will be fired, using only a
portion of the half million gallons of fuel in the external tank,
while the shuttle remains bolted to the launch pad. The two solid
fuel rocket boosters flanking the shuttle tank will not be ignited.
   In the past, a flight readiness firing has been required only
for new shuttles, except for one time when a malfunction made a
retest necessary. But the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration is treating Discovery as an untried ship because of
the long time since the last flight and the many changes made since
the Challenger disaster.
   Challenger exploded 73 seconds after launch on Jan. 28, 1986,
with the loss of seven lives and there have been no American manned
missions since then. A leak in Challenger's right booster was
blamed for the accident. The boosters have been redesigned to
prevent a recurrence.
   Discovery's test-firing has been postponed five times for
various malfunctions, including leaks in ground equipment and last
wee's abort.
   No date has been set for Discovery's four-day flight with five
astronauts aboard, but the delays have made it all but certain that
NASA can't meet a late September target.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1517EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     08-08 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviets,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Soviet Jews Visiting Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Soviet Jews are getting a
first-hand look at Israel after a 21-year travel ban to the Jewish
state. Some say they don't like what they see, while others dream
of staying forever.
   About 2,000 Soviet Jews are in Israel visiting their immigrant
relatives, according to Foreign Minister Shimon Peres. Hundreds
more arrive each month.
   Until this year, relatives of the more than 200,000 Soviet Jews
who emigrated to Israel have been permitted only telephone or
letter contact, and family visits were forbidden.
   Although diplomatic ties cut by the Kremlin to protest Israel's
1967 seizure of the West Bank and Gaza Strip have not been renewed,
recent changes in the Soviet political climate have made tourism
possible for those Jews who have relatives in Israel.
   The visitors are permitted to stay up to two months and are
restricted to bringing about $10 a day out of the Soviet Union.
   Airfare and visa charges amount to about $3,000, a large sum for
Soviets who on average make about $285 a month.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the visits were ``a very
positive trend'' and were accompanied by the arrival of a Soviet
consular delegation in Israel last year and the departure of a
similar Israeli mission to Moscow last month.
   Israeli officials hope the visits will help boost Soviet Jewish
emigration to Israel, which reached a record low last month.
   While Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union attained an
eight-year high of 1,639 in July, during the first seven months of
1988 only about 12 percent of 16,178 emigrants decided to settle in
Israel.
   To boost emigration, the Jewish Agency's Russian Department has
begun organizing free promotional tours that include seminars on
Israel's history and culture. Officials say the funding is
unlimited.
   ``We've turned into a travel agency,'' one official said as he
added the name of another Soviet Jew requesting a tour to a long
list of visitors on his desk. ``The phones never stop ringing.''
   Mina Helman of Riga said the tour had given her a glimpse of
``the astonishing Jerusalem, the lively Tel Aviv and the beautiful
Negev desert.''
   But some Soviet Jews said their time in Israel had revealed
problems in finding jobs and housing, as well as a constant state
of tension with Israel's Arab neighbors.
   ``I have spent 10 days in Israel and now I don't know if I want
to settle here,'' said a middle-aged man who said he was a
``refusenik'' _ a Soviet Jew denied an emigration permit.
   Chaim Finkelstein, 60, a construction worker from Kishinev, said
his visit convinced him that ``Israeli politics are ugly.''
   ``You have too many (political) parties. There must be a limit
somewhere and too much democracy can be harmful,'' he told the
daily newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
   Some Soviet Jewish immigrants in Israel agreed their countrymen
would be better off settling elsewhere.
   ``It's a crime to encourage people to come here. The absorption
system is a disaster,'' said Vika Ladizhinsky, whose father, Yefim,
a well-known immigrant painter, hanged himself in 1982 because he
failed to get the reception in Israel he had expected.
   Some Soviet Jews said the visits had strengthened their desire
to live in Israel.
   Marina, a Moscow teacher in her 40s who declined to give her
last name, said the Israel she saw during a 40-day visit was
markedly different from the hostile picture portrayed in the
official Soviet media.
   ``I thought people were being killed in the streets of Israel,''
she said of Soviet coverage of the 8-month-old Palestinian
rebellion in the Israeli-occupied territories. ``I'll tell all my
friends to come to Israel immediately.''
   Berta, 66, a gynecologist on a two-week visit with her sister,
said she wanted to settle in Israel with her husband, and was using
the visit to find out about job opportunities and pensions.
   Most of the Soviet visitors praised Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms, saying they had greatly simplified the procedure for
getting exit visas.
   One middle-aged Leningrad woman, her relatives said, was
``reborn,'' by her trip. The woman sat on a bench, silently
embracing her mother and sister.
   ``She cannot talk,'' the mother said. ``She is too distressed.
She goes back in two days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
