<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Softball enthusiasts Howard Schnurnberger
and Esther Fitzgerald opted to forgo a big church wedding and have
nice ceremony at home.
   So with a backstop as their backdrop, the couple married at home
plate in Block Park.
   Flanked by members of the groom's softball team, the couple
braved a possible rain delay and finished the ceremony in time for
the team to prepare for their late-afternoon game.
   ``We just decided it would be fun,'' Fitzgerald said. ``We
didn't want to make a big deal about the day. At the same time, we
wanted to just enjoy the company of friends and have a good time.''
   Following the exchange of vows, the team took the field to warm
up and the newlyweds took a short honeymoon trip _ around the bases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MCFARLAND, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents made a big stink when the
machine Wisconsin Power and Light Co. uses to add odor to natural
gas broke.
   The utility was flooded with hundreds of telephone calls Sunday
from customers who thought there had been a gas leak.
   Natural gas has no odor and one is regularly added so that a
leak, which can result in an explosion if gas builds up, can be
detected.
   WPL spokesman Don Piepenburg said the machine, which normally
adds the odor a little at a time, dumped it all at once.
   He said the machine was shut down and utility representatives
went door-to-door to assure residents there was no leak or danger.
</TEXT>
