<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NightOut     08-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Night Out,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Will Turns On The Lights In Philadelphia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans in more than 7,200 towns were set
to turn on porch and house lights Tuesday night in the fifth annual
``National Night Out Against Crime.''
   Vice President George Bush will switch on a giant light bulb in
downtown Philadelphia at 8 p.m. to kick off the symbolic message to
criminals that people intend to fight for safe neighborhoods.
   The annual anti-crime effort is organized each year by the
Pennsylvania-based National Town Watch Association. Its goals are
to heighten crime prevention awareness, generate support for local
anti-crime efforts, strengthen neighborhood spirit and promote
cooperation with law enforcement agencies.
   ``The event turns the clock back about 30 years to a time when
neighbors routinely kept an eye out for each other, kids played
outside until well after sunset and people knew the cop on the
beat,'' said Matt Peskin of Wynnewood, national project coordinator.
   Organizers of the national effort said lights will go on this
year in all 50 states, in all the U.S. terrorities, and in hundreds
of U.S. military bases around the world.
   After people join in the turn-on, also depicted this year as a
turn-off on drugs, they can go outside to visit with neighbors and
police as well as participate in block parties, cookouts, parades
and other activities.
   Electric industry officials estimate that leaving a couple of
lights on all night for a year would cost the average homeowner
about $30.
   Among events Tuesday night:
   In Dayton, Ohio, the world's largest banner will be unfurled,
24,000 square foot, bearing the message: ``Dayton's National Night
Out Against Crime-Drugs.''
   Residents of Chesapeake, Va., plan a ``Dunk the Criminal''
booth. An 88-minute police-civilian softball game is scheduled at
Ashland, Ky.
   Police in Anaheim, Calif., plan to distribute free light bulbs
at a senior citizen center, and in Chicago seniors will launch that
city's campaign by distributing blue ribbons. Mayor Edward Koch of
New York also will hand out ribbons.
   Joining in will be U.S. military installations in West Germany,
England, South Korea, the Netherlands, Iceland, Belgium, Cuba and
Japan. And in Canada, neighborhoods in Edmonton and Burlington
planned to turn out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
