<DOCNO> AP880808-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RegattaAccident     08-08 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Regatta Accident,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railroad Tie Eliminated As Cause, Wake Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities investigating a boat racing
accident that injured 23 spectators eliminated a floating railroad
tie as the cause Monday, leaving the wake from other boats as the
prime explanation.
   Early reports suggested the boat driven by 1987 Canadian
National Champion Robert Wood struck the railroad tie.
   ``There's no connection,'' said Public Safety Director Glenn
Cannon. ``There are no marks on it at all to indicate that it was
struck by anything, and we have a witness who places it near the
shore before the impact occurred.''
   Wood's boat, which was clocked at more than 116 mph during time
trials for the Champion Spark Plug Grand Prix event, catapulted out
of the Allegheny River, veered right and crashed into the bank,
where spectators were watching the 11th annual Three Rivers Regatta.
   ``It just seems he hit a wake,'' Cannon said. ``It lifted him up
in the air. When it came down it didn't come down in the manner it
should have. He tried to steer the boat to the left.''
   Wood, who suffered minor injuries and shock, told police he
believed his boat was buffeted by air from the boats he was
following.
   Investigators hoped to determine the speed by studying videotape
of the scene shot from a blimp for Secaucus, N.J., television
station WWOR. The station was covering the New York Mets-Pittsburgh
Pirates baseball game nearby at Three Rivers stadium.
   The boat appeared to slow after it veered toward shore,
apparently no longer under power.
   ``Not only that, but as he hit, the bottom of the engine would
have begun striking the bottom of the river,'' Cannon said. ``And
there's a man-made edge, called riprap, stones together with
cement, that slowed the boat tremendously.''
   Divers continued looking Monday for the last missing piece of
the boat, a piece of metal that was located below the propeller.
The part could confirm whether debris in the river contributed to
the accident, Cannon said.
   Meanwhile, city officials started reviewing crowd control
measures.
   The Parks Department previously used fence to keep spectators
from the river's edge, but ``for some reason ... that was
discontinued,'' Cannon said.
   The fence will probably be back next year, putting an additional
15 to 20 feet of concrete walkway between the water and spectators,
he said.
   Only one of the injured remained in critical condition Monday,
said Allegheny General Hospital spokeswoman Karen Long. Two others
improved to serious, seven remained hospitalized in serious to good
condition, and 13 others were released.
</TEXT>
