<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Governors-Reagan Bjt   08-08 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors-Reagan, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Applaud Vintage Reagan Speech on Big Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors warmly applauded
President Reagan on Monday for a vintage attack on Washington and a
tribute to their initiatives in dealing with national issues such
as welfare and job creation.
   ``He was talking language we understand,'' Republican Gov.
Thomas Kean of New Jersey said of Reagan's address to the National
Governors Association.
   Democratic Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas replied,
``Absolutely,'' when asked if he thought it was a political speech
designed to help Vice President George Bush in the presidential
campaign.
   ``But it was one that was appropriate within the limits of the
association,'' Clinton added. ``I think it was as political as he
could be without stepping out of line.''
   Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the association's most
prominent current member, was not present for the president's
speech.
   The Democratic presidential candidate planned to attend the
closing session of the NGA meeting on Tuesday and then have a
closed strategy session with Democratic governors.
   Reagan never mentioned Bush, Dukakis or the presidential
campaign, but he touted the economic statistics certain to be a key
part of the Bush campaign.
   ``Our states, like our citizens, have known the blessings of the
longest peacetime economic expansion on record,'' he told the
governors, citing the creation of more than 17 million jobs during
his two terms as well as a current unemployment rate that is the
lowest in 14 years.
   The largest part of the president's speech was devoted to citing
the virtues of states as opposed to the federal government _ a
familiar theme of the Reagan presidency.
   ``In the last seven and one-half years we have broken the
federal government of its compulsion to control every breath the
states take,'' Reagan said.
   He said that ``too often in the past when Washington listened to
the states, it heard only what it wanted to hear. Today, things are
different. When governors talk, we not only listen, but we hear.''
   Praising state initiatives, Reagan said that ``from education,
to transportation, to helping America's poor and homeless, you have
led. While Washington has been caught up in partisan intrigue,
you've gone out and done the job.''
   The governors were meeting between the two national political
conventions, but they studiously avoided allowing the campaign to
intrude on their meeting.
   Reagan held to that non-partisan approach. But he was far more
partisan during a stop at U.S. Precision Lens, a firm located a few
miles from the governors meeting.
   Still avoiding mentioning Dukakis by name, the president said,
``I've heard some people bad mouthing our economy recently. I think
they must have stopped reading the newspaper that day in 1981 when
they handed over the lease to the White House.''
   He said ``some people are telling you to take for granted the
economic growth of today and of the last seven years.''
   He characterized that message as telling people ``you can take
prosperity for granted, it's time for a change, take a chance on
us.''
   Reagan said that was ``sort of like someone telling you that
you've stored up all the cold beer you could want, so now you can
unplug the refrigerator. ... You can't unplug our pro-growth
economic policies and expect things to stay the same.''
   Democratic Gov. Richard Celeste of Ohio retorted that ``the
issue is bread and butter, not cold beer.''
   Celeste called Reagan's speech to the governors ``a wonderful
trip down memory lane. ... All of us would agree on the importance
of initiatives on the state level.''
   Kean said Reagan would be a help to Bush, but ``anybody, no
matter how good they are, is a marginal help. It's up to the
candidate who's running.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
