<HEAD>Felix Leclerc Dies At 74</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix Leclerc, a singer, poet and playwright, died
Monday at his home of a heart attack, a family spokesman said. He
was 74.
   Leclerc had been ill for some time, said his secretary, Pierre
Jobin.
   Born in La Tuque, Quebec, Leclerc was best known for writing
nationalist songs that influenced such Quebec singers as Gilles
Vigneault, Robert Charlebois and Pauline Julien.
   Leclerc lived on the Ile-d'Orleans, an island in the St.
Lawrence River near Quebec City. Survivors include his wife and two
children.
