<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-American     08-08 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-American,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines To Pay $70,000 To Settle Discrimination
Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines will pay $70,000 to resolve
a government complaint that it discriminated against flight
attendant applicants based on their citizenship status, the Justice
Department said Monday.
   The settlement will cost the air carrier $53,000 in back pay and
$17,000 in federal civil penalties.
   The agreement will affect 33 applicants who qualified as
``intending citizens,'' but whom American refused to consider for
employment _ either because they could not produce an alien
registration card or because their cards had expiration dates.
   ``Intending citizens'' under the 1986 immigration law are
permanent and temporary residents admitted under the new
legalization program, and refugees and those who have sought asylum
who intend to become citizens. The act prohibits employers from
discriminating against them.
   ``We hope this settlement will put others in the airline
industry on notice that the challenged practices are proscribed by
the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986,'' said Lawrence J.
Siskind, the special counsel named under the statute.
   Siskind's office enforces prohibitions against employment
discrimination based on national origin and citizenship status.
   The agreement settles a complaint filed April 12 and cannot be
construed as an admission of liability by American, the department
said.
</TEXT>
