<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Eikenberry     08-08 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Eikenberry,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`L.A. Law' Star Reveals Breast Cancer; Will Do NBC Documentary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jill Eikenberry revealed Monday that she was
undergoing treatment for breast cancer while filming the first six
episodes of the hit NBC series ``L.A. Law'' two years ago.
   Eikenberry made a surprise appearance at a news conference held
by NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff to announce she
will help produce with NBC News a documentary about breast cancer
survivors, ``Destined to Survive: 100 Roads to Recovery,'' to air
Oct. 12.
   ``I was one of the lucky ones. I didn't have to lose a breast,''
said Eikenberry, who said the cancer was discovered between filming
of the pilot and beginning of production of the series. ``I had to
undergo radiation therapy during the first six episodes of `L.A.
Law.' It was not an easy time,'' she said.
   Eikenberry plays attorney Ann Kelsey on the series. She and
co-star Michael Tucker are married in real life as well as on the
series.
   ``Between the period of my treatment and diagnosis, I underwent
a tremendous amount of soul-searching and terror, despite the
incredible support of my husband, my family and my friends,'' said
Eikenberry. ``The only real rays of hope came from the women who
had been through these things and survived. They were the ones who
made me feel I wasn't alone.''
   The documentary will profile 100 survivors of breast cancer,
some famous, such as first lady Nancy Reagan, and others not. The
aim is to encourage other women to carefully check themselves for
signs of the disease.
   ``We brought this project to Brandon because we felt, I felt he
would be sympathetic because of his history with Hodgkin's disease,
because he's also destined to live,'' Eikenberry said.
   Tartikoff said he underwent successful treatment of Hodgkin's
disease, a form of cancer, several years ago before he went on to
huge success programming NBC's prime-time lineup.
   ``When Jill brought this to me it honestly did touch a chord,''
he said. ``I do think that what this will say to people who face
any form of cancer, particularly breast cancer, is that you cannot
only survive, you can triumph, flourish and lead meaningful,
productive lives.''
</TEXT>
