<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike Bjt   08-08 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Goes Back To Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Months behind in an industry where everything
is due last week, producers and scriptwriters scrambled Monday to
regroup after a 22-week strike that idled thousands and devastated
the fall television schedule.
   The Writers Guild of America membership Sunday voted 2,111 to
412, or by 83.7 percent, in favor of the pact with the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   ``I would say nobody's in fighting form,'' NBC Entertainment
President Brandon Tartikoff said.
   The walkout crippled Hollywood and left the upcoming TV season
in shambles. The season's start will be delayed, perhaps until
mid-October or later, despite the anticipated glut of written
material.
   The production season for prime-time television usually begins
in late June and early July.
   ``What we are going to do this morning is what we normally do in
May. We have two writers' meetings today and three tomorrow,''
producer Tony Thomas said in a telephone interview as he drove to
work. ``We are starting from scratch, which is what everyone in
town is doing.''
   Thomas, producer of TV's ``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``The Golden
Girls,'' ``It's A Living'' and ``Empty Nest,'' said the networks
have not reduced their orders, and he expects to produce 22 shows
for ``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``The Golden Girls.''
   ``Probably around the production of the fourth and fifth episode
we will start to feel the crunch because of lack of planning and
have to start spending more money,'' Thomas said. ``You're always
behind in TV, and that will just happen sooner.''
   The ratification came in the 154th day of one of the longest and
most painful strikes in modern Hollywood history, eclipsing by one
day the WGA's 1960 walkout that lasted 153 days.
   ``There have been hardships,'' said Al Di Tolla, president of
the International Association of Theatrical and Stage Employees,
which is holding its annual conference in Reno, Nev., this week.
   Di Tolla said the five-month strike resulted in the worst
unemployment rate in the history of his union, which covers
carpenters, electricians, set decorators, costumers and other
crafts.
   Of the 75,000-member union, up to 60 percent were unemployed, Di
Tolla said. One-third of the union's members are based in Los
Angeles.
   Timothy Wurtz and his writing partner, Glenn Benest, have two
television movies for CBS and two feature films for 20th Century
Fox that will all be due in coming weeks. ``Today, we're starting
on the second draft of one of the TV movies,'' Wurtz said. ``And we
have to deliver a second draft on one of the features within six
weeks.''
   Wurtz said he typically writes four to five hours in the morning
and devotes afternoons to business. ``Now, I might be working eight
to 10 hours a day writing, and I may be working more than five days
a week.''
   At restaurants and messenger services, two peripheral businesses
affected by the strike, managers noted an upswing in business as
early as last week, when a tentative agreement was reached
following several days of rumor.
   ``Thursday and Friday we had a little burst of business,'' said
Frank Casado, who with his wife Lucy owns the El Adobe Mexican
restaurant on Melrose Avenue across the street from Paramount
Studios.
   ``I look forward to things improving. Beside the writers, you
have all the extras. And the carpenters and electricians, those
guys eat pretty good too,'' Casado said. ``It may take awhile. They
may need a few checks to get back ahead of things.''
   Jim Burke, manager of the LA Express messenger service, also
said business had picked up Thursday and Friday. Before the strike,
Burke said, LA Express dealt almost exclusively with entertainment
industry clients and suffered a 50 percent loss in business.
   He said he pushed for new, non-entertainment clients and
recouped about 90 percent of his regular business
   ``Now we hope to go through the roof,'' he said.
   The WGA has 9,000 members, most living and working in Southern
California. The alliance has 217 member companies, responsible for
85 percent of network prime-time television and 90 percent of
feature film production and distribution.
</TEXT>
