<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EasterTrial     08-08 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Easter Trial,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easter, Sons Convicted of Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman and her three sons were convicted Monday
of murder in the deaths of three police officers whose
bullet-riddled bodies lay in a motel room from which the family
held police at bay for 10 hours.
   A Wayne County Circuit Court jury deliberated for 17 hours over
four days in convicting Alberta Easter, 70, and her sons, William
Lemons, 44, Roy Lemons, 48, and George Lemons, 46, of three counts
of first-degree murder each.
   Murder convictions carry mandatory life prison terms.
   They were charged in the deaths of Inkster Officers Daniel
Dubiel, 36, and Clay Hoover, 24, and Sgt. Ira Parker, 41.
   The jury, which heard 13 weeks of testimony, also found the sons
also were found guilty of felony firearms and felonious assault
charges.
   There were many trial delays because George Lemons must have
dialysis treatments.
   The police officers had been trying to serve a bad check warrant
on Easter and one of the Lemons when they were shot. Easter and her
sons then negotiated with police for the release of the officers,
who medical witnesses testified were dead during the siege at the
Bungalow Motel.
   Police and the Easter family exchanged gunfire during much of
the night of July 9, 1987, before the family gave up early the next
day. They have been jailed ever since.
   Easter had claimed both that the officers shot each other while
exchanging gunfire with the family inside the room, and that they
were shot during exchanges between the family and officers outside.
   But autopsy reports said the officers were killed within minutes
of entering the motel room. Hoover and Dubiel were shot 29 times
each, one report said.
   Dubiel and Hoover initially tried to serve the warrant and
called for help from Parker when Easter asked for a delay in her
arrest, saying she wanted to try to straighten the matter out
without going to jail.
</TEXT>
