<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NuclearLiability     08-08 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Liability,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan May Sign Bill Increasing Industry Liability in Nuke
Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is expected to sign
legislation to require nuclear power companies to take a bigger
financial responsibility for damages arising from a reactor
accident, an administration official said Monday.
   ``We have strongly supported this bill,'' the official said of
the proposed 15-year renewal of the 1957 Price-Anderson Act that
won final congressional approval on a voice vote Friday in the
Senate.
   ``It is likely that he will sign it,'' said the Office of
Management and Budget official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Price-Anderson Act is unique because it is the only federal
statute that sets a limit on how much a company or an entire
industry can be forced to pay to victims of an industrial accident.
   The bill would set the liability limit for the nuclear
generating industry at $7.1 billion for all damages from a single
accident. That is 10 times the amount the industry was responsible
for under the previous law, which expired a year ago.
   If damage awards exceeded the limit, Congress would have to come
up with a legislative plan to supply the rest of the money.
   The $7.1 billion limit walks a line between the nuclear
industry, which sought a lower figure, and interest groups like
Public Citizen, the Ralph Nader-founded organization which pushed
for a higher limit or none at all.
   Public Citizen has pointed to government studies suggesting that
a catastrophic nuclear accident could cause $100 billion or more in
damages. Critics say the Treasury could end up providing most of
the compensation.
   David Hamilton, national field director of U.S. Public Interest
Research Group, said that ``while the (new) cap is a net
improvement over current law, the revision does little more than
current law to encourage corporate responsibility, to protect
taxpayers from having to pay for a nuclear accident or to ensure
that all legitimate victims of an accident are compensated.''
   Steve Unglesbee, director of legislative communications for the
American Nuclear Energy Council, an industry group, called the
legislation ``a big step forward in compensation'' for victims.
   Renewal of the Price-Anderson Act is not expected to spur
construction of new nuclear power plants. Unglesbee says that to
revive the industry, the federal licensing procedure needs to be
streamlined and a standardized plant design must be established.
   And barring an accident requiring large payments to victims, the
higher liability limit is not expected to have any major impact on
electricity rates charged by utilities with nuclear plants,
according to congressional aides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
