<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PrimaryRdp     08-08 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Actor Seeks House Nomination; Illinoisans To Pick Successor
to Price</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA W. BARNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former actor Ben Jones of ``Dukes of Hazzard'' fame tries again
for Congress in Tuesday's Georgia primary, while voters in southern
Illinois chose a successor to the late Rep. Mel Price and Colorado
voters also pick House nominees.
   Also at stake as Georgians settle on nominees in 10 House
districts is the Democratic nod for the seat held by Republican
Rep. Newt Gingrich. Gingrich, who is unopposed for his party's
nomination, has been in the forefront of efforts to force an
investigation of House Speaker Jim Wright.
   In the Atlanta area's 4th congressional district, Jones, who
played the rustic mechanic ``Cooter'' on the comedy series, is
regarded as the front-runner for the Democratic nomination to face
Republican Rep. Pat Swindall in the fall.
   Swindall, a two-term congressman whose views appeal to the
religious right, is considered vulnerable as a result of his
admission that he considered accepting laundered drug money during
a home loan transaction.
   The congressman, videotaped by government investigators, said he
was ashamed he considered the deal but insisted he broke no law
because he ultimately rejected it. He has no primary opposition.
   Jones, who won 47 percent of the vote in his race against
Swindall in 1986, faces attorney Nick Moraitakis and theater
operator John Stembler.
   In the 6th District, which runs south and west of Atlanta, David
Worley, a 30-year-old attorney, and businessman Clyde Eugene Owens,
51, are competing for the chance to face Gingrich, a five-term
congressman, in November.
   In Illinois, the election to fill the unexpired term of Price is
a dress rehearsal for the Nov. 8 general election, when the same
candidates vie for a full two-year term in the 21st district.
Price, a Democrat who had held the seat for nearly 44 years, died
April 22 at 83.
   Democrat Jerry Costello, 38, is the St. Clair County board
chairman and one of southern Illinois' most powerful party leaders.
His opponent, Republican Robert Gaffner, 55, an administrator at
St. Louis Community College, came within 843 votes of defeating
Price in 1986.
   The two men had emerged as their parties' November nominees
after Price announced he would not run for another term.
   In Colorado, the action in determining nominees for the six
House seats was on the Republican side, with primary contests to
determine opponents to Democratic congressmen David Skaggs of the
2nd District and Ben Nighthorse Campbell in the 3rd.
   State Rep. David Bath of Arvada and former Secretary of State
Mary Estill Buchanan face off to oppose Skaggs in the Boulder
County district, which includes the northwest fringes of the Denver
area.
   Buchanan was Colorado's first woman secretary of state. In 1980,
she won the GOP nomination for U.S. Senate and lost to Democrat
Gary Hart in a close race.
   In the 3rd District, which spans much of western and southern
Colorado, one of the two GOP candidates, Montrose County
Commissioner Ken Neesham, has suspended his campaign. He is
embroiled in a criminal investigation of alleged illegal use of
county road equipment.
   The other, real estate agent Jim Zartman, has been traveling
1,000 miles a week throughout the district to gain name recognition
in hopes of unseating Campbell.
   And in Lyons, Ga., Annie Laurie Hussey, who has been Toombs
County probate judge since 1945, is seeking her 12th four-year term
in office at the age of 91.
   ``My doctor says I'm healthy and all the lawyers in Toombs
County are behind me,'' said the judge, a great-grandmother.
   Jackie Driskell, a legal secretary, is running against Mrs.
Hussey.
</TEXT>
