<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HelenaShultz-Profile     08-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helena Shultz-Profile,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State's Wife a Frequent Traveling Companion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helena M. O'Brien was an Army nurse in Hawaii
during World War II when she met her future husband.
   Five months after the war's end, she and George P. Shultz, a
Marine officer at the time, were married. They celebrated their
42nd wedding anniversary last February.
   ``O'Bie'' Shultz, as she is known to friends, is a frequent
traveling companion of her husband, the secretary of state, and was
a passenger in Shultz's motorcade Monday in La Paz, Bolivia, when a
terrorist bomb went off.
   The car in which she was riding was slightly damaged but she and
others in the caravan escaped injury.
   The Shultzes have remained a very close couple over the years, a
fact amply demonstrated at the time of his appointment to the State
Department in July 1982.
   On arrival in Washington after being summoned from London,
Shultz found two limousines awaiting him at the airport.
   One, he was told, was for him, the other for his wife to take
her anywhere she wanted to go while Shultz had his interview with
President Reagan.
   Shultz waved off the second car. ``No,'' he said, ``she'll come
with me. We're a package deal.''
   Mrs. Shultz, who does not tell her age, lists her special
interests and hobbies as handicapped children, gardening, golf,
traveling and ``taking care of and keeping up with George.''
   She looks forward to the time next January when Shultz returns
to private life after six years at the State Department. They have
homes in Stanford, Calif., and Cummington, Mass., and have five
children and five grandchildren.
   The last was born after the Moscow summit. Afterward, Mrs.
Shultz scrapped plans to accompany her husband to Spain and the
Middle East, going instead to California to help with her new
grandchild.
</TEXT>
