<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TomahawkTest     08-08 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tomahawk Test,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Successfully Tests `Capsule Launch' Cruise Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy said Monday it had successfully
demonstrated a submarine ``capsule launch'' system for a Tomahawk
cruise missile during a test in the Gulf of Mexico.
   The test firing was performed by the nuclear-powered USS
Providence on Sunday and involved a conventional land-attack
version of the Tomahawk fitted into a specially added ``capsule''
in the bow of the submarine.
   The cruise missile _ carrying an inert warhead for the test _
was launched from the submerged submarine and then ``flew a fully
guided land-attack mission of approximately 450 miles to a recovery
area on the Eglin Air Force Base, Fla., range,'' the Navy said.
   The test was important because it demonstrated that land-attack
cruise missiles can be carried and stored aboard a submarine in the
bow, outside the pressure hull, and fired from that position, said
Bob Holsapple, a spokesman.
   Without such a capsule launch system in the bow, a submarine
cannot be armed with cruise missiles without reducing its arsenal
of on-board torpedoes, he added.
</TEXT>
