<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Gilmore     08-08 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Gilmore,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran Journalist, War Hero, Dead At 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel F. Gilmore, a veteran foreign
correspondent who covered Europe, Asia and the Middle East for
United Press International during more than 40 years with the wire
service, died Sunday of emphysema. He was 66.
   At the time of his death, Gilmore was senior correspondent for
Maturity News Service, a nationally syndicated wire service
covering issues affecting older Americans.
   Gilmore, a native New Yorker, began his journalism career as a
copy boy for The Associated Press and Time magazine. He joined
United Press, as the agency was then known, in 1941 but left to
join the Army Air Force in 1942.
   He saw action in the European theater during World War II, and
received the Purple Heart and air medal with three clusters.
   Gilmore was the lead radio operator-gunner with the Hell's
Angels B-17 bomber squadron that operated out of England. In March
1944, Gilmore's plane was shot down over Europe and he was rescued
by French Resistance forces, who hid him for two months. German
border guards captured him in the Pyrenees Mountains as he was
attempting to reach Spain. He was freed in May 1945 by British
forces six days before Germany surrendered.
   After rejoining United Press, Gilmore served in bureaus in
London, Rome, Vienna, Frankfurt and Hong Kong. Assignments also
took him to the Soviet Union, the Middle East, Africa and Indochina.
   While in Rome, he met and married Clare Lorene Brubaker, of
Johnstown, Pa., a State Department employee at the U.S. Embassy.
   Gilmore was UPI European news editor from 1962 to 1972. He was
the service's Asian division chief, directing the coverage of the
Vietnam War, from 1972 to 1973. From 1973 until his retirement in
1987, he worked in Washington as head of UPI's national security
affairs team.
   He is survived by his wife Clare; mother, Elizabeth; sister,
Margaret Calkin; and brother, Patrick. Burial will be in Arlington
National Cemetery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
