<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FoodAid     08-08 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Aid,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Extends Funds For Emergency Hunger Relief Through Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday passed an emergency hunger
relief bill that extends a temporary food program for a year and
requires the government to buy an extra $110 million in surplus
commodities for the needy.
   The bill, similar to one passed last month by the Senate, also
makes small increases in food stamp benefits and makes it easier
for farmers, the disabled and the elderly to qualify for food
stamps.
   The measure goes to a conference committee to be reconciled with
the Senate bill.
   The House bill, passed by voice vote, extends through fiscal
1989 the Temporary Emergency Food Assistance Program which
distributes surplus agricultural commodities to the needy.
   The bill earmarks an extra $70 million for TEFAP and the
remaining $40 million for commodities to be distributed by soup
kitchens and food banks.
   Including the food stamp changes, the Congressional Budget
Office has estimated the bill will cost $306 million in fiscal
1989, rising gradually to $671 million in 1993.
   The Reagan administration has said it opposes the bill for
budget and policy reasons.
</TEXT>
