<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Governors-Drought     08-08 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors-Drought,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Commend Drought Relief Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Relief, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm state governors Monday approved a
resolution commending the Reagan administration and Congress for
quick action on an aid package for farmers hit hard by the drought.
   The governors, in a report from a task force chaired by Iowa
Gov. Terry Branstad, also urged continued federal and state
attention to the problems of farmers struggling to cope with
today's economics and international trade imbalances.
   The Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development of the
National Governors' Association unanimously approved a resolution
praising Washington for quick action on a $3.9 billion bill to
provide emergency help to farmers whose crops and livestock are
suffering because of this year's drought.
   ``The legislation that Congress is set to pass is excellent,
far-reaching legislation that provides assistance to livestock and
crop producers,'' the committee, chaired by North Dakota Gov.
George A. Sinner, a Democrat, said in its resolution.
   A House-Senate conference committee approved a compromise
version of the bill Thursday, and the Senate approved it Monday.
The legislation was expected to receive final legislative approval
in the House as early as Tuesday. President Reagan is expected to
sign it into law within days of receiving it.
   Governors at the National Governors' Association annual meeting
this week in Cincinnati said U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng has been particularly cooperative in aiding the drought relief
effort.
   ``I've been in this business a long time, folks, and I've never
seen this kind of response from the Department of Agriculture,''
said Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, a member of the governors'
agriculture committee.
   The committee approved the 67-page report from Branstad's task
force. The report urges federal and state governments to give
continuing attention and support to rural America as it fights to
cope with depressed farm prices and declining value of farm land.
   The task force's report said the average price of farm land per
acre went from $219 in 1972 to $823 in 1982, then back down to $547
in 1987.
   It urged states to help rural communities prepare for the future
by creating special offices for rural affairs, providing tailored
development information for rural areas and helping rural
industries develop new products and find new markets.
   The report also urged Washington to shape federal policies with
more sensivitity to their impact on rural America.
</TEXT>
