<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Iran     08-08 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Iran,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Calls for Vigilance, But People Seem Ready for Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leaders issued new calls for
vigilance Monday, the day the U.N. secretary-general announced a
cease-fire in the long war with Iraq, but people in the Iranian
capital seemed ready for peace.
   Newspapers carried reports on a Cabinet meeting in which members
stressed the need ``for complete readiness and presence of
combatants'' and more military volunteers. State television said
the Iraqis shelled a village, wounding three civilians, and Tehran
radio reported several violations of Iranian air space by Iraqi
fighters.
   Residents of Tehran appeared convinced the end to the fighting
was at hand. Even President Ali Khamenei, who expressed serious
doubts about the truce prospects a few days ago, told an
international conference the 8-year-old war ``is apparently coming
to a close.''
   He told a conference of Islamic scholars, however, that Iraq's
conduct during negotiations at the United Nations in New York
``gives us the right to have doubts about their real aims.''
   Kayhan, one of the main afternoon papers, carried the headline
``Cease-fire to be announced tonight.'' Inside were photographs and
brief biographies of ``martyrs'' _ Iranians killed in action.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general, announced
Monday in New York that the truce will begin Aug. 20 and peace
negotiations between Iran and Iraq will open five days later in
Geneva.
   A driver who spoke English and said he formerly held a well-paid
job in construction, told a visitor: ``My son, Romin, has sent a
message that he is coming home in four weeks now that the fighting
ends. He has been in the army for two years and eight months.
Luckily he has not been wounded. The place where is he is now is
pretty quiet.''
   A 25-year-old named Fahrad said he was excused from military
service because of injuries he suffered in a car accident while
studying petrochemical engineering in Los Angeles.
   ``Many of my generation are dead,'' he said. ``In a way I was
lucky to have been in that accident.''
   An Associated Press reporter requested permission to visit
front-line troops preparing for the truce, but a Ministry of
Islamic Guidance official said it was not possible. A request to
visit Tehran's war cemetery brought the same answer.
   The English-language Tehran Times carried comments from Iranians
on Monday about the government's acceptance of a U.N. Security
Council's cease-fire resolution a year after it was passed.
   Brig. Gen. Morteza Mohammadi, described as commander of
``Division 81 in Khoramabad'' gave what seemed a typical answer:
   ``Being a follower of the imam (Ayatollah Ruhollah Kkhomeini),
we obey his decree whatever it is.
   ``In fact, there are three major reasons for our compliance:
First, being Moslems, Imam Khomeini is our religious leader.
Second, being Iranians, Imam Khomeini is the leader of the leader
of the Islamic revolution. Thirdly, we are the army, and Imam
Khomeini is the supreme commander of the armed forces.''
   Private Khazrullah Panah said:: ``Although I enjoy war, the
imam's order is the ultimate order for us.''
   Habibullah Nasrullah Tabar, a 20-year-old Basij (volunteer)
said: ``If the imam tells us to fight for a hundred years we will.
If he deems it right to negotiate with the enemy, we will too.''
</TEXT>
