<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Crash     08-08 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bulgaria-Crash,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises To 27 After Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more people have died of injuries
suffered in the crash of a Bulgarian airliner last week, bringing
the death toll to 27, the state news agency BTA reported Monday.
   The Soviet-designed Yak-40 jetliner, with 33 passengers and four
crew members on board, crashed into a river bed Tuesday after
failing to take off from Sofia airport. The cause of the accident
has not been determined.
   The latest casualties were a 29-year-old Yugoslav and the flight
engineer, the agency said.
   Twenty-three people died at the time of the crash, and two more
died a day later.
   Nine passengers remain hospitalized, all of them Bulgarians.
   The plane was scheduled to fly from the Bulgarian capital to the
city of Varna on the Black Sea.
