<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--India-Cholera     08-08 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--India-Cholera,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Epidemic Reaches 858</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water-borne diseases have claimed 30
more lives in India, raising to at least 858 the number of people
killed by the epidemic, according to media reports.
   Cholera and gastroenteritis have claimed 11 more lives in New
Delhi, the United News of India and Press Trust of India reported
Sunday. At least 260 people in the capital have died of the
diseases, the reports said.
   More than 6,000 people in New Delhi were admitted to hospitals
with symptoms of the diseases, the reports said. They said 818 of
the cases were diagnosed as cholera.
   Health clinics have inoculated more than 28 million Indians
again cholera, United News said. India's population is 800 million.
   Health officials blame the epidemic, which began in early July,
on flood waters washing through sewage and uncollected garbage and
seeping into drinking water supplies.
   The slums of New Delhi, where the garbage has not been collected
in months, is hardest-hit by the epidemic.
</TEXT>
