<DOCNO> AP880808-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     08-08 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Studying Status of Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet commission studying conditions in a
disputed southern region may recommend giving it more autonomy to
help end a standoff between two ethnic groups, a prominent
historian said Monday.
   The commission's work on the status of Nagorno-Karabakh is
connected with preparations for a long-promised plenum of the
Communist Party Central Committee on ethnic relations, said Yevgeny
Ambartsumov.
   Among the compromise solutions the commission is considering is
upgrading the enclave's status from an autonomous region within the
Azerbaijani republic to that of an autonomous republic, which has
its own constitution and laws, he said.
   ``We must find a realistic compromise that would take into
account the aspirations of Armenian people, and the people of
Nagorno-Karabakh, and contribute to better ethnic relations,'' he
said at a government-sponsored news conference.
   He said he did not know when the commission would issue its
report.
   Ambartsumov, a department head at the Soviet Academy of
Sciences' Institute of Economics of the World Socialist System, is
half Armenian. He appeared at a news conference sponsored by the
government news agency Novosti with Azerbaijani writer Chengiz
Guseinov.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is dominated by ethnic Armenians, who have been
agitating since February to have their region taken from Azerbaijan
and annexed to Armenia.
   Demonstrations of hundreds of thousands of people have been held
in Yerevan, the Armenian capital. There have been general strikes
in Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia. Ethnic rioting broke out in the
Azerbaijani city Sumgait in early March, killing 32 people, 26 of
them Armenians.
   On July 18, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's
highest executive body, rejected demands to unite Nagorno-Karabakh
with Armenia.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said that the
policy-making Central Committee should hold a meeting on ethnic
relations, but there has been no indication when it will be.
   Ambartsumov said poor reporting by Soviet media contributed to
the tension in Armenia, portraying Armenians mourning those killed
in Sumgait as extremists and nationalists.
   He called for ``full information, correct information,'' under
Gorbachev's policy of glasnost.
   The situation was quieter but still tense in the southern
republics.
   ``The situation is not very good, but it is more or less quiet
and we have time to start a more profound analysis,'' he said.
   Ambartsumov said Armenians have gained more involvement in the
life of Nagorno-Karabakh. ``In sharp contrast to past developments,
Armenia today is engaged in discussion and solution of the problems
of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is part of Azerbaijan,'' he said.
   Armenian construction workers are building roads and improving
the airport, and food deliveries are being made from Yerevan, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ArmsControl     08-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Arms Control,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Still Seeks Dismantlement Of Soviet Radar Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has directed federal agencies
to develop responses in the event the Soviet Union refuses to tear
down a radar installation considered by the United States to be in
violation of an arms-control treaty.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Monday that a
third, five-year review of compliance by the superpowers to the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty will be held in Geneva beginning Aug.
24.
   He said the principal objective of the United States at the
review session is to ``obtain the Soviet Union's agreement to
correct its violations of the ABM treaty and to satisfy other U.S.
concerns regarding Soviet non-compliance with its obligations under
the treaty.''
   Fitzwater, repeating a stand that Reagan and other top officials
have stated in the past, said the Soviet Union's large,
``phased-array radar'' station at Krasnoyarsk, Siberia, ``is a
significant violation'' of a central element of the ABM treaty of
1972.
   ``In preparation for the upcoming review,'' Fitzwater's
statement said, ``the president has issued guidance that the U.S.
delegation should continue to make it clear that the existence of
the Krasnoyarsk radar violation calls into question the viability
of the ABM treaty. ... ''
   ``It should be dismantled without further delay and without
condition,'' the statement said. ``Unless resolved, the Krasnoyarsk
radar violation will force the United States to consider the
exercise of its rights under international law to take appropriate
and proportionate responses.''
   The statement did not define what those responses might entail.
   But it did say that among the options would be for the United
States to declare the Krasnoyarsk radar ``to be a material breach
of the ABM treaty.''
   ``The president also has directed that the Department of
Defense, working with other executive branch agencies and the
Congress, take the lead in developing a range of appropriate and
proportionate responses for consideration if the Soviet Union
continues to refuse to correct the Krasnoyarsk violation,'' the
statement said.
   ``After hearing what the Soviet Union has to say at the
five-year ABM Treaty Review,'' it said, ``should the situation
remain unresolved, the president will consult with the Congress and
our allies concerning next steps.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
