<HEAD>Quebec Poet and Songwriter, 74</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix Leclerc, a Quebec songwriter, poet and
playwright, died of a heart attack Monday at his home, a family
spokesman said. He was 74.
   Leclerc had been ill for some time, according to his secretary,
Pierre Jobin.
   Leclerk was born in La Tuque, Quebec, and wrote nationalist
songs that had an influence in the 1960s on such Quebec singers as
Gilles Vigneault, Robert Charlebois and Pauline Julien.
   Leclerc lived on Ile-d'Orleans, an island in the St. Lawrence
River near Quebec City.
   He is survived by his wife and two children.
</TEXT>
