<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-8-8-88     08-08 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-8-8-88,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Married On 8-8-88 But Astrologist Warns Of Unlucky Stars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-88 Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Israeli couples were married
Monday on the eighth day of the eighth month of 1988, but some
astrologists said the position of the stars was not lucky for
matrimonial bliss.
   ``We are happy to get married on this date, 8-8-88, because we
become a part of history,'' one bride, identified only as Ayelet,
told Israel radio.
   Her fiance, Shmuel, whose family name was not given, said he
heard ``a lot of astrological talk about this date. If this is
really true, we may be lucky.''
   Another couple, Sarah and Moshe, said they would celebrate by
``having everything in eight: Lighting eight candles and arranging
eight flowers. We shall be happy after getting married on the 8th
day of the eight month, '88.''
   Ayelet and Shmuel had a difficult time reserving a wedding hall,
even for a fee of $9,375 that included the cost of the wedding
dresses, recorded music and fried chicken for the guests, the Al
Hamishmar newspaper reported.
   Reservations for wedding halls, where most Israeli marriage
services are performed, had been streaming in.
   ``Halls throughout the country were booked solid months ago by
couples seeking to take advantage,'' of what the Chinese consider
to be a lucky number, the Jerusalem Post reported.
   Many astrologists said Monday was lucky for marriage.
   ``The convergence of eight, a number that is suffused with life,
creates circumstances ... especially favorable for romantic love by
catalyzing a release of dormant positive energy forces,'' Madame
Sheli, an astrologist told the Jerusalem Post.
   And there were astrologists who said the position of the stars
and the number eight may carry unpleasant surprises.
   ``There's a difficult position of the stars,'' said astrologist
Miriam Binyamini. ``The whole year 1988 is thought to be a hard one
because of the number eight. It's a difficult number. I wouldn't
get married on that day.''
   ``Such a day is good for business, money, sex ... sex by itself,
not accompanied by romantics,'' she told Israel radio. She added:
   ``These couples would have money. But they will have to invest a
great effort in building a happy marriage. I assume today's
marriages would not turn that happy, especially in the area of
simple family relations.''
   One Israeli couple, Yochi and Erez, told Israel radio they
decided to marry on 8-8-88 because ``otherwise we would have to
wait 11 years, till the 9-9-99.''
   ``God forbid!,'' Ms. Binyamini said. ``Then the stars are even
worse.''
</TEXT>
