<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Personnel,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Names Replacement For Pendleton At Civil Rights Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to elevate William
Barclay Allen to be chairman of the Commission on Civil Rights,
succeeding the late Clarence M. Pendleton Jr., the White House said
Monday.
   Allen has been a member of the commission since 1987 and was a
member of the panel's California Advisory Committee for two years
prior to that.
   He has been a professor of government for the Claremont Graduate
School at Harvey Mudd College in California and is a graduate of
Pepperdine University and Claremont Graduate School.
   Ralph Neas, executive director of the Leadership Conference on
Civil Rights, criticized the selection of Allen.
   ``Regrettably the president has named another right-wing
idealogue as chairman of the civil rights commission,'' Neas said.
``His decision continues to ensure that the commission will lack
any credibility and will remain a joke.''
   The White House also announced that Reagan intends to nominate
Thomas C. Griscom, who recently resigned as White House
communications director, to be a member of the board of the
Communications Satellite Corp., succeeding Neal B. Freeman.
   Griscom would serve on the board of directors until the date of
the annual meeting of Comsat, if confirmed for the position by the
Senate.
   From April 1987 through July of this year, Griscom was assistant
to the president for communications and planning. Before that, he
was president and chief operating officer of Ogilvy and Mather
Public Affairs.
</TEXT>
