<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VincennesReport     08-08 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Report,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>JCS Chairman Gets Report on Shootdown Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official investigation report on last
month's shootdown of an Iranian airliner by a Navy cruiser was
delivered Monday to the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm.
William J. Crowe, defense officials said.
   The report by a military board of inquiry was forwarded to Crowe
by Gen. George Crist, the head of the U.S. Central Command, which
is responsible for all U.S. military forces in the Mideast.
   Last week, sources disclosed that investigators had concluded
the USS Vincennes attacked and destroyed an Iranian airliner on
July 3 because of human mistakes made under the stress of combat.
   Because of the mistakes, the captain of the Vincennes believed
his ship had survived its first combat only to confront an
approaching, ``hostile'' Iranian jet fighter, said the sources. In
reality, the radar contact was a civilian airliner with 290 people
aboard that had just taken off from a large military base at Bandar
Abbas, Iran.
   The defense officials said Monday that Crist ``had made some
changes'' and inserted some of his own observations and
recommendations in the inquiry report, which was prepared by Rear
Adm. William Fogarty.
   ``But he made no bottom-line changes,'' added one official, who
like the others demanded anonymity.
   It was not known how long Crowe would take to review the report
and forward it to Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci. The Pentagon
has said it will release an unclassified version of the report
after it reaches Carlucci.
</TEXT>
