<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-O'Hare-Problems     08-08 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Hare-Problems,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Safety Investigators Call For More Controller Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety investigators called Monday for
a ``back-to-basics'' training program for air traffic controllers
at Chicago's busy O'Hare International Airport because of an
unusually high number of controller errors.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said that a majority of
the controller errors recorded at O'Hare's radar control facility
during the first six months of the year involved a ``breakdown in
basic (controller) skills.''
   But the safety board said problems at O'Hare, the second busiest
airport in the world with an average of nearly 2,200 takeoffs and
landings a day, go beyond controller skills.
   It called on the FAA to take immediate actions to provide
controllers at O'Hare with newer and better radar and computer
equipment, find ways to increase controller staffing, reduce peak
traffic loads, improve controller training and develop better
quality assurance.
   The FAA declined to comment directly on the NTSB
recommendations, which came out of a special safety board
investigation of O'Hare's air traffic operations because of a
sudden increase in controller errors earlier this year.
   The FAA, however, announced that it planned a special
broad-ranging review of O'Hare by a team of agency and aviation
industry experts with a report to be submitted to FAA Administrator
Allan McArtor by Sept. 20.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said the review will go beyond air
traffic control questions and include an examination of the
airport's overall operation. Participants in the review will
include representatives from the airlines, pilots union, various
aviation organizations and the City of Chicago, Farrar said.
   ``Overall more than 50 organizations have been invited to
participate in the review,'' said Farrar.
   O'Hare Airport is the second busiest in the world with 796,939
arrivals and departures last year, second only to Atlanta's
Hartsfield International. Last year O'Hare handled more than 56
million passengers, more than any other airport.
   It also has been the subject of numerous investigations by the
FAA, the NTSB and congressional committees because of safety
concerns. The latest investigation by the NTSB was prompted by
reports in June that controllers had committed 19 operational
errors where aircraft had been allowed to fly dangerously close to
one another, seven more than during all of 1987.
   After examining these incidents, NTSB investigators concluded
that in many cases ``controllers failed to follow the procedures''
and in a majority of the cases the errors involved a ``breakdown in
basic (air traffic control) skills.''
   The safety board said that in many cases the controllers'
performance was affected by ``excessive workload, lack of
attentiveness, foregetting, perceptual problems, fatigue, and
excessive time on position without a break.''
   But the board said it was ``concerned that these controllers,
working at one of the nation's busiest terminal radar facilities
failed to act in accordance with basic controller standards and
principles'' and questioned the effectiveness of the FAA's overall
quality control program.
   Other areas of NTSB concern at O'Hare were:
   _ Continuing excessive overtime with many controllers saying
they are required to work six-day weeks.
   _ Shortages in the number of controllers. While the FAA has
authorized additional controllers at O'Hare's radar facility, the
number of controllers there actually has increased by only five in
the last two years, investigators said.
   _ The need for newer and better computer, radar and
communications equipment. Some of the equipment has been in use at
other facilities for years, the safety board said. It said that 26
other FAA facilities are currently scheduled to received the FAA's
most advanced terminal radar system before it is scheduled to come
to O'Hare.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
