<1ST_LINE>u a AM-88Rdp     08-08 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-88 Rdp,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Day Comes Up Eights For Births, Banks And Sports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eight Eight, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight-pound, eight-ounce babies were born Monday, the date of
8-8-88, a bank offered an 88-day certificate of deposit,
mathematicians declaimed on eights and gamblers went eight-ball
wild.
   Kelli-Lee O'Brien was born at 8:08 a.m. Monday in Hackensack,
N.J., at a weight of 8 pounds, 8{ ounces. Her mother's
obstetrician, who was making his eighth delivery in his
two-week-old private practice, has eight children.
   ``It's been hysterical around here all morning,'' said Jean
Werner, head nurse in the labor and delivery unit of Hackensack
Medical Center. ``Everybody can't believe it. Everybody thought
they were joking with all the eights coming up,'' she said.
   Kelli-Lee's parents, Kirsten, 23, and James, 25, of Vernon,
coincidentally gave their daughter a name with eight letters.
   Not to be out-done, William Royal Crowder Jr. weighed 8 pounds,
8 ounces at birth Monday at Richmond, Va. His parents are William
R. and Karen Crowder of Virginia's Dinwiddie County.
   Prince Andrew and the Duchess of York, both 28, had a baby girl
Monday at 8:18 p.m. London time. The child's great-grandmother,
Elizabeth the Queen Mother, last week celebrated her 88th birthday.
   In Roanoke, Va., Helen Canary turned 88 on the day of eights.
``I've seen a whole lot in 88 years, yes,'' Ms. Canary said.
   Tourists descended on tiny Eighty Eight, Ky., and radio stations
called from around the world called residents for interviews.
   Tascosa National Bank in Amarillo, Texas, offered 88-day
personal certificates of deposit at 8[ percent interest. Minimum
deposit? You guessed it: $8,888.
   The eighth day of the eighth month of the 88th year also was the
kick-off day for the centennial anniversary of the American
Mathematical Society based in Providence, R.I.
   In a press release for the weeklong conference, Martin Gardner,
a former columnist for Scientific American magazine, wrote:
   ``Eight is, from a standpoint of pure arithmetic, the second
cube, the sixth Fibonacci number, and the sum of the first three
digits of pi.
   ``Applied to the outside world, eight takes on more glamour as
the notes of an octave, the arms of an octopus, the eight-cylinder
motor, stock market eighths, the figure-8 knot, the skater's figure
8, the eight-hour work day, behind the eight ball, old Spanish
pieces of eight, and the eighth wonder of the world.''
   Monday was the eighth birthday of Stephan Lollar of Burlington,
Vt., so his grandmother, Connie Lollar of Springfield, Mo., sent
him a special eight ball.
   Her late husband, White Sox player Sherm Lollar, hit his 1,000th
major league hit in the eighth inning of a game in 1958 against Red
Sox pitcher Tommy Brewer, then took the ball and painted it black
with a white 8.
   Mrs. Lollar also painted an oversized card for her grandson with
images of crazy eights, arachnids, the semiphore signal for 8 and
an octillion _ a 1 followed by 27 zeros. She also wrote an 88-line
poem in which each line ended with a word rhyming with ``eight.''
   Michigan gamblers also noted the date, triggered higher than
usual sales in both the three-digit and four-digit daily numbers
games, said Bureau of State Lottery spokeswoman Laurie Kipp-Klecha.
By mid-afternoon, more than 10,520 four-digit tickets with the 8888
combination had been sold, she said.
   Connecticut's state lottery sold out the numbers 8888 early
Monday after about 1,600 tickets were sold. ``The computer realized
we had reached $8 million (in potential liability) and sales were
stopped,'' said Ed Harrigan, a spokesman for the state Division of
Special Revenue. That $8 million limit was set earlier and had
nothing to do with the date.
   ``When you get that many numbers, it's a powerful manifestation
... because it's 11 years before it shows up again,'' said Joanne
Benedetto, a numerologist at the Chrystal Cave Bookstore in Orange,
Calif.
   In Europe, throngs of young West German couples rushed to city
registry offices to get married, hoping the date would bring them
luck. Many ceremonies were not preregistered and appeared to be
spur-of-the-moment, including 58 such weddings in Duesseldorf.
   More than 10,000 Germans stormed the northern Bavarian town of
Blindheim to buy stamps bearing the village's postal code: 8888.
   Thousands of Israelis also filled wedding halls. A couple
identified only as Ayelet and Shmuel said they would celebrate
their anniversary by ``having everything in eight: lighting eight
candles and arranging eight flowers.''
</TEXT>
