<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-08 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Warnings Expand Over Parts of the Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the Southeast on
Monday, with locally heavy rain associated with tropical storm
Beryl, and rain also developed along a line from the Great Lakes to
the Texas Panhandle.
   Tropical storm warnings were expanded to cover the Gulf Coast
from Morgan City, La., to Pensacola, Fla. It had sustained wind
blowing at 45 mph with gusts to 55 mph in squalls over the Gulf of
Mexico.
   Locally heavy rain soaked the central Gulf Coast in association
with Beryl. Valparaiso, Fa., got 2.20 inches of rain in the morning
and Mary Esther, Fla., got 1.45 inches.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed during the middle of
the day across the southern third of Florida. And showers and
thunderstorms were scattered along the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along a slowly moving cold
front that extended from the north-central Great Lakes through the
lower Missouri Valley into the Texas Panhandle. The front's forward
motion was resisted by very warm, humid air dominating the middle
Mississippi Valley and the southern Plains.
   The cold front helped produce showers and thunderstorms that
brought locally heavy rain to parts of the upper Mississippi
Valley. Eau Claire, Wis., got 1.81 inches of rain from
thunderstorms during the morning and parts of northern Iowa got 1
to 3 inches during the night. Decorah, Iowa, got 2.72 inches and
Rowan, Iowa, got 2.66 inches.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over the northern third of New
England during the afternoon. And scattered showers and
thunderstorms developed over the southern high Plains into parts of
central Colorado.
   It was a hot day across parts of the southern Plains and lower
Missouri Valley, with temperatures above 100 degrees from central
Texas through central Oklahoma and across parts of northwestern and
north-central Missouri.
   Kansas City, Mo., hit a record high of 104. In Texas, Dallas and
Fort Worth tied their record of 106 and Corpus Christi tied its
record of 99.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 106 in Texas at Waco and Dallas-Fort
Worth. The low for Monday morning was 36 at Butte, Mont., and
Truckee, Calif.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the lower Mississippi Valley across the Gulf Coast to the
southern Atlantic Coast and Florida. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms also were forecast from New England through the lower
Great Lakes and middle Mississippi Valley into eastern Kansas.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the central and northern
Pacific Coast region and across the upper Great Lakes; from the
upper 90s to 105 from southern Oklahoma through central Texas into
the Rio Grande Valley; between 100 and 110 across the desert
Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across much of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
