<DOCNO> AP880808-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Pilots     08-08 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Pilots,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Afghan Airmen Defect To Pakistan in Fighter Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Afghan airmen in a Soviet-built
MiG-19 abandoned a bombing mission over Afghanistan on Monday and
flew their fighter jet to Pakistan, where they asked for political
asylum, authorities said.
   Pakistan officials meanwhile refused to confirm or deny
newspaper accounts that the Islamabad government was holding a
Soviet pilot shot down last week.
   Authorities at the northwest border village of Parachinar said
the two Afghan fliers landed their fully armed plane, handed over
sidearms and asked for asylum.
   They said the men told Parachinar airport security that they,
along with another two fighters, had been sent from Kabul to bomb
Moslem guerrilla positions in eastern Paktia province. While the
others attacked Paktia, the pilot swerved his aircraft toward
Pakistan, they said.
   Airport security fired on the MiG, fearing it was coming in to
bomb the airport although the pilot, identified as Maj. Munir, and
the other airman, Capt. Wazir, advised the control tower they
wanted to defect.
   They circled the airport four times before they were allowed to
land, local authorities said. The fighter was loaded with rockets
and bombs.
   Newspaper reports said a Soviet airman was flown to Islamabad,
the Pakistani capital, after surviving the downing of his Su-20
ground attack fighter by a U.S.-built Pakistan air force F-16 last
Thursday. The plane reportedly was shot down near the border
village of Miranshah.
   Over the course of the 10-year war in neighboring Afghanistan, a
half-dozen Afghan pilots have defected to Pakistan with their
aircraft. This was the first defection reported since the Soviets
began their withdrawal from Afghanistan on May 15.
   Cross-border incursions in Pakistani airspace have occurred
frequently during the long conflict between the Marxist government
in Kabul and Islamic guerrillas.
   An air force official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
``there has been some increase'' since the signing of an April 14
agreement providing for the phased withdrawal of more than 100,000
Soviet soldiers from Afghanistan.
   Guerrilla reports from North Waziristan, where Miranshah is
located, said four Afghan refugees were killed last Wednesday when
a Soviet or Afghan fighter jet bombed Pakistani territory.
</TEXT>
