<DOCNO> AP880808-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PerezdeCuellar     08-08 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Perez de Cuellar,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low-Key UN Chief Having Success with Peace and Truce Accords</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Javier Perez de Cuellar is mild of manner
and would not boast of his diplomatic skill, but he had reason for
pride Monday when he announced a cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war.
   The Iran-Iraq war is the latest in several seemingly intractable
conflicts for which the United Nations has been asked to help find
a solution.
   The Soviet Union is withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers
from a 10-year-old civil war in Afghanistan under a U.N.-mediated
agreement signed April 14.
   Combatants in Cambodia, southwestern Africa and the Western
Sahara have asked the world organization to find ways of ending
their wars without a defeat for any party.
   Perez de Cuellar's diplomatic successes in Afghanistan and the
gulf contrast with his early disappointment in the 74-day Falkland
Islands war between Argentina and Britain. It was fought in 1982,
the year after he became U.N. chief executive.
   The soft-spoken diplomat from Peru, now 68, is known for
discretion and diligence. He likes to quote the French aphorism
``Le ton fait la chanson,'' which means the melody makes the song,
not a loud voice.
   The secretary-general tried to create harmony between Britain
and Argentina as London's fleet of warships steamed toward the
Falklands, but both sides hardened their positions after two weeks
of talks. Argentina also claims the islands, which it calls the
Malvinas.
   Before the Falklands conflict ended, Israel invaded Lebanon. The
Israelis defied Security Council demands for a cease-fire and
withdrawal, and bypassed the 7,000-member U.N. peacekeeping force
in southern Lebanon.
   With infinite patience, Perez de Cuellar insists it is ``much
easier for a government to make concessions to the United Nations
than to make concessions to one another or to a big power.''
   That theory bore fruit in the past week, when Iraq abandoned its
demand for direct talks with Iran as a first step toward peace,
accepting Perez de Cuellar's compromise suggestion for direct talks
immediately after a cease-fire takes effect.
   He announced Monday that the truce would begin Aug. 20 and the
peace talks Aug. 25.
   After he became secretary-general, Perez de Cuellar said he
would not seek a second five-year term because the U.N. chief must
remain independent and not curry favor with the five permanent
Security Council members. He relented, however, and was re-elected
in 1986 with no serious opposition.
   A career diplomat, he was Peru's ambassador to the United
Nations from 1971-75 and served on the Security Council in 1973-74.
   He was U.N. special representative to Cyprus in 1975-77 and, in
1979, was appointed undersecretary-general for political affairs.
He held that post until becoming secretary-general and also was
special representative to Afghanistan in 1981.
</TEXT>
