<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NBCSchedule     08-08 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC Schedule,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Sees Little Effect Of Strike On Fall Scheduling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Writers Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five-month writers strike that just ended
will push back NBC's mid-season replacements a month or so, but
otherwise the network is in good shape for the fall, NBC
Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff said Monday.
   NBC will have two weeks of prime-time coverage of the Summer
Olympics beginning Sept. 15. That made the network less vulnerable
to delays in the new season of entertainment shows caused by the
strike, but had threatened to devalue the promotional platform
afforded by the multimillion-dollar Olympics coverage.
   ``We've had a lot of time to sort of digest what was happening
and prepare for the day when it (the strike) would be over,''
Tartikoff told a news conference, though he added, ``I would say
nobody's in fighting form.''
   Most of NBC's schedule will premiere in October. Three shows
that make up the Tuesday lineup, ``Matlock,'' ``In the Heat of the
Night'' and ``Midnight Caller,'' will be delayed until the end of
November because of ABC's airing of its miniseries ``War and
Remembrance'' that month, not directly because of the strike,
Tartikoff said.
   Premiering the week of Oct. 3 will be ``ALF,'' ``The Hogan
Family,'' ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' ``Highway to Heaven,'' ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World,'' ``Dear John,'' ``Sonny
Spoon,'' ``227,'' ``Amen,'' ``Golden Girls,'' ``Empty Nest'' and
``The Magical World of Disney.''
   The week of Oct. 24 will have ``Tattinger's,'' ``Something Is
Out There,'' ``Hunter,'' ``Family Ties'' and ``Day by Day.'' The
next week, NBC will add ``Baby Boom,'' ``Night Court,'' ``Cheers,''
``L.A. Law'' and ``Miami Vice.''
   ``It's not going to be our tack to rush shows on the air,
particularly the new ones, and diminish the possibility for
long-term success to get on one week early,'' Tartikoff said.
   ``We were prepared and we did give script orders early enough so
they could be meaningful at this time. I think that's why we're
getting on sooner'' than the other two networks, he said.
   Besides the Olympics, NBC also had several series, including its
top-rated ``The Cosby Show,'' that were able to stay in production
under independent contracts with the Writers Guild.
   ``Mid-season might come after the February sweeps,'' a delay of
about a month, Tartikoff said.
   ``Hardy Boys,'' a remake considered during the strike, will be
made as a two-hour movie, but NBC has no series commitment.
   The extensive research the network did in looking for old shows
to re-shoot was not an exercise in futility, Tartikoff said.
   ``We did the entire history of television in a seven-week
period,'' he said. ``The one thing you realize when you go back is
that television at one time was a much more varied marketplace, and
there were a lot more interesting ideas out there than are the
tableaux today. Out of that there have been some ideas and
offshoots'' that could become the germs of new series ideas.
   Tartikoff also announced that NBC has struck a deal with the
network's former president, Grant Tinker, who now heads GTG
Entertainment, for a two-hour pilot called ``Bay Watch.'' It would
hit the air in the fall of 1989.
   Tinker currently is producing two shows for CBS.
</TEXT>
