<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Napier     08-08 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Napier,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Actor Alan Napier Of `Batman' Fame Dead At 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British actor Alan Napier, whose
butler character tidied up the Bat Cave but never divulged his
master's identity in the 1960s ``Batman'' television series, died
Monday at the age of 85.
   Napier died at the Berkley East Convalescent Hospital in Santa
Monica, where he had been living since June, said nursing
supervisor Naseem Chunara. He suffered a stroke last year and had
been ill for several days, she said.
   In a career that spanned four decades, the tall, elegant
Englishman appeared in more than 50 films, including ``My Fair
Lady,'' ``Tender is the Night,'' and ``Journey to the Center of the
Earth.''
   His best-remembered role, however, was Alfred Pennyworth,
Batman's trusted servant in the television series.
   The ``Batman'' series, based on the comic strip, achieved
enormous popularity during its short run from January 1966 to March
1968 with its campy dialogue and celebrity villains.
   Adam West played the Caped Crusader and Burt Ward was his
sidekick Robin, the Boy Wonder. Guest villains included Burgess
Meredith as the Penquin, Cesar Romero as the Joker, Vincent Price
as Egghead and the late Victor Buono as King Tut.
   Batman's cover identity was that of millionaire Bruce Wayne.
Pennyworth worked in both the above-ground Wayne mansion and in the
Bat Cave crime lab, where his duties included dusting the Bat
Computer.
   Born Alan Napier-Clavering in Birmingham, England, his other
films included ``We Are Not Alone,'' 1939; ``The Invisible Man
Returns,'' 1940; ``The House of the Seven Gables,'' 1940; ``The
Song of Bernadette,'' 1943; ``Cat People,'' 1942; ``Lassie Come
Home,'' 1943; ``Forever Amber,'' 1947.
   He also appeared as the Earl of Warwick in ``Joan of Arc'' in
1948 and portrayed Cicero in ``Julius Caesar'' in 1953.
   Funeral arrangements are pending at Pierce Brothers Mortuary in
Westwood Village.
</TEXT>
