<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleTest     08-08 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Test,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Qualifying Test Of Redesigned Shuttle Booster Set For Aug.
18</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last of five full-scale
test-firings required to qualify the redesigned space shuttle
booster rocket for flight is scheduled for Aug. 18, Morton Thiokol
Inc. announced Monday.
   A successful test of the 126-foot-long rocket at the aerospace
company's northern Utah plant 25 miles west of here would clear the
way for resumption of shuttle flights, on hold since the Jan. 28,
1986, Challenger disaster.
   A faulty seal between sections of one of Challenger's two
boosters was blamed by a presidential commission for the explosion
that destroyed the spacecraft shortly after launch.
   Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab said next week's test,
following the successful fourth firing on June 14, will incorporate
several intentional flaws to test backup systems to their limits.
   ``It's severely flawed. It has flaws in every joint but one. Two
of the three field joints and the case-to-nozzle joint are
flawed,'' he said.
   ``We have already tested full-sized motors in short duration
tests with these same types of flaws. This test will allow us to
demonstrate that with a full-duration test, further adding to the
confidence in the redesign,'' Raab added.
   The two-minute test will burn approximately 1.1 million pounds
of solid fuel propellant, sending a cloud of smoke and flame
thousands of feet into the sky.
   The redesigned rocket developed by Morton Thiokol to replace
Challenger-era boosters incorporates new and additional O-ring
seals made of cold-resistant materials, as well as improved
insulation intended to further reduce the possibility of flaming
exhaust gases leaking through a joint rather than the rocket motor.
   Such a leak ignited Challenger's exterior liquid fuel tank.
</TEXT>
