<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     08-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preschool Molest,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three More Children Won't Testify In McMartin Pre-School Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three children have refused to testify in the
McMartin Pre-School molestation trial, a prosecutor said Monday,
placing in jeopardy 27 of the 99 molestation charges against the
school's operators.
   Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin said outside court that the
prosecution might try to prove the charges without the three
children, ``but it's an extraordinarily difficult thing to do.''
   She said the children have refused to testify because they don't
want to revive painful memories and because they remain
traumatized. Two boys, she said, continue to have ``strong
nightmares,'' and one girl has lost her memory of all events prior
to a year ago _ a sign of ``massive depression.''
   ``While we have a responsiblity to present all of the evidence,
we also have a responsiblity not to increase trauma to kids,'' Ms.
Rubin told reporters of the decision not to force the children into
court.
   Another child refused to testify last month, and the judge
refused a prosecution bid to use her videotaped preliminary hearing
testimony from 1985. Three charges were based on her allegations.
   Raymond Buckey, 30, and Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61, are charged
with 99 molestations and one joint count of conspiracy with 82 of
the counts naming only Buckey. The molestations allegedly took
place at their now-defunct McMartin Pre-School in suburban
Manhattan Beach.
   The case has been in Los Angeles courts for five years, and the
trial has been under way for more than a year. Nine children have
testified so far in the case, which once focused on 41 youngsters.
   With 30 charges resting on four children who will not testify,
the prosecution stands to lose nearly a third of the charges to
dismissal if the judge finds insufficient evidence to support them.
   Buckey's attorney, Danny Davis, said outside court he was not
surprised at the development and had suspected earlier that the
prosecution would drop some of the child witnesses.
   ``The remaining three witnesses had more contradictions and
unbelievable accounts (in their testimony),'' he said. ``They were
a liablity (to the prosecution.)
   ``I think the prosecution case is falling of its own weight.''
   Davis said he would vigorously oppose any effort to have the
children's parents testify instead of the alleged victims.
   Prosecutors dropped charges against five other teachers at the
school in 1986.
</TEXT>
