<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0685,1020</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Announces Date of Iran-Iraq Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with reaction,
other. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
announced Monday that Iran and Iraq will begin a cease-fire in
their 8-year-old war on Aug. 20 and will open peace negotitions
five days later in Geneva.
   ``The restoration of peace will bring to the peoples of both
countries victories far greater than those of war,'' he said in a
statement, capping a full year of U.N. peace efforts and three
weeks of intense, delicate diplomacy.
   The Persian Gulf war killed or wounded more than 1 million
people and cost hundreds of billions of dollars.
   The U.N. chief told the 15-nation Security Council the two sides
would begin direct talks on a comprehensive peace settlement Aug.
25 in Geneva. He said he would preside and the level of the talks
was to be decided.
   ``I now call upon the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Republic
of Iraq to observe a cease-fire and to discontinue all military
action on land, at sea and in the air as of 0300 GMT on 20 August
1988,'' he said in his statement.
   The starting time of 3 a.m. Greenwich Mean Time Aug. 20 is 11
p.m. EDT Aug. 19.
   ``I have been assured by the two parties to the conflict that
they will observe this cease-fire in the context of the full
implementation of Resolution 598,'' a peace plan adopted by the
Security Council more than a year ago.
   As he spoke, the envoys of Iran and Iraq were both present in
the Security Council for the first time since the war started. But
Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati and Iraqi Ambassador
Ismat Kittani did not acknowledge each other's presence.
   The council will meet Tuesday to authorize a 350-man unarmed
U.N. peace-keeping force, including a naval contingent, to monitor
the cease-fire and troop withdrawal.
   Perez de Cuellar did not announce dates for all peace plan
elements, including troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange, direct
peace talks and an investigation into which side started the war.
   The agreement is the second U.N. negotiating success this year.
Moscow is withdrawing Soviet soldiers from Afghanistan under a
U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14.
   ``This is not a personal success for me,'' Perez de Cuellar said
later in answer to reporters' questions. ``It is a success for the
two parties, for the Security Council, for the U.N. organization.''
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, later told a news
conference:
   ``I wish to declare my government is prepared to accept the
demand of the secretary-general and that of the entire world
community to refrain from any military action on land, sea and air,
starting today.''
   ``Let me express my sincere hope that today's historic
announcement will be the first step in the implementation of all
provisions of Resolution 598, and the achievement of a just,
comprehensive and honorable setttlement, returning peace and
stability to all the region.'' .
   Asked if Iran was ready to make peace with Iraq, he said: ``Of
course, there is no question about it.''
   Iraq's Kittani told reporters: ``This is a happy day. I don't
think anyone is unhappy. We in Iraq have been waiting for this day
...
   ``Now we begin the arduous but happy march that begins from
here. I am sure it will not be a smooth road, but it will be much
more pleasant than fighting and bloodshed.''
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters told reporters: ``This is a
historic date for the participating countries, a historic day for
the United States which has pressed so hard to bring this war to
and end, and a truly historic day for the United Nations.''
   Iraq had foreign exchange reserves of $35 billion when the war
began and now owes an estimated $60 billion. Iran has not borrowed,
but its foreign exchange reserves have declined to a few billion
dollars.
   A financial journal published in Paris, La Tribune, estimates
Iran needs $80 billion and Iraq $30 billion to rebuild
transportation, oil installations, housing, factories, schools and
hospitals.
   U.N. negotiations had been deadlocked over Iraq's demand for
direct talks with Iran before a cease-fire. Iran had rejected that
demand, saying it wanted a truce first, then direct talks. Perez de
Cuellar proposed a compromise formula that includes direct talks
immediately after a cease-fire.
   People in Tehran seemed convinced Monday the fighting would end.
   A 25-year-old man named Fahrad said he was excused from military
service because of injuries suffered in a car crash while studying
petrochemical engineering in Los Angeles.
   He told an Associated Press reporter: ``Many of my generation
are dead. In a way I was lucky to have been in that accident.''
   Diplomats in Baghdad said efforts to keep the guns silent may
continue for years because of border and other issues.
   Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after border skirmishes.
   President Reagan said: ``We may finally see an end to that long
and bloody war. ... I applaud and encourage the efforts of
Secretary-General Perez de Cuellar.''
   About two weeks will be needed to deploy the peacekeepers and
their operation will cost $74 million for the six months
authorized. They will be drawn from about 25 nations, each paying
for the soldiers it sends.
   A report by Perez de Cuellar said the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military
Observer Group will:
   _Establish agreed cease-fire lines on the basis of forward
defended areas existing when the truce begins, with adjustments
when the sides are too close.
   _Monitor compliance with the cease-fire.
   _Investigate alleged violations and restore the situation in
each case.
   _Use negotiations to prevent changes in the status quo pending
withdrawal to internationally recognized boundaries.
   _Supervise, verify and confirm withdrawal.
   _Obtain agreement on other arrangements, such as weapons
limitations near the border and patrolling of sensitive areas by
U.N. naval personnel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
