<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GalaxySighted 1stLd-Writethru a0659 08-08 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Galaxy Sighted, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,440</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 1st graf to insert dropped word ``light'' and 8th graf,
``The red xxx to CORRECT years to miles.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Announce Discovery of Most Distant Galaxy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronomers on Monday announced the discovery
of the most distant galaxy known, a cluster of stars 15 billion
light years away that formed long before the Earth and the sun.
   ``This is very unusual and very rare,'' said Ken Chambers of
Johns Hopkins University, one of the co-discovers. ``We're seeing
something from before the Earth formed, possibly before our own
galaxy, and when the universe was very different than today.''
   The distant galaxy, known as 4C41.17, is far too faint to be
seen by the eye, but it emits a radio signal a billion times more
powerful than the sun's radio signal.
   ``It is one of the most powerful radio galaxies we know of,''
said Chambers.
   Though the galaxy was located by radio signals, its distance
from Earth was established by analyzing the optical spectrum, or
type of light, put out by the galaxy.
   Chambers said the galaxy puts out a sharp optical signal of the
type characteristic of hydrogen and carbon. The wavelength of the
emission, however, is stretched by movement away from the observer.
   This stretch causes the light color to shift toward red, the
so-called ``red shift.'' By measuring this shift, the astronomers
could calculate the distance of the galaxy.
   A red shift of 3.8 found for 4C41.17 shows that it is about 15
billion light years away. A light year is the distance light
travels in a year, about 5.8 trillion miles.
   Chambers said at 15 billion light years, the galaxy is about 90
percent of the distance to what is thought to be the edge of the
universe. He said it also gives a view back in time and the galaxy
as seen now is only few billion years after the Big Bang, the
massive explosion that is thought to have started the universe
expanding outward.
   The galaxy is thought to be ``primitive,'' or in an early stage
of formation, Chambers said.
   ``To be able to study the dynamics as it is forming will tell us
a lot of how galaxies are formed,'' he said.
   The Earth and sun are thought to have formed about 4.6 billion
years ago.
   The study of the distant galaxy was announced at the 20th
assembly of the International Astronomical Union. Chambers'
co-discovers were George Miley, a European Space Agency
representative at the Space Telescope Science Institute, and Wil
van Bruegel, an astronomer at the University of California,
Berkeley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     08-08 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet, U.S. Diplomats Discuss Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said
Monday that Pakistan is continuing ``destructive actions'' in
violation of the pact intended to end the war in Afghanisan.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said Shevardnadze made
the comment during a meeting at the Foreign Ministry with U.S.
Ambassador Jack Matlock.
   Shevardnadze returned Sunday from a four-day visit to
Afghanistan and Tass said Matlock requested the meeting.
   While in Kabul, the Afghan capital, Shevardnadze and Afghan
officials said Pakistan was continuing to supply weapons to the
rebels fighting Afghanistan's Marxist government.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979
to help the government fight the anti-communist rebels. Under
Geneva accords signed April 14 by Pakistan and Afghanistan, with
the Soviet Union and the United States as guarantors, the Soviets
are to withdraw all of their military units by Feb. 15.
   It was estimated that the Soviets had about 120,000 military
personnel in Afghanistan when the withdrawal began May 15. The pact
called for half the Soviet forces to be out of the country by Aug.
15
   Tass reported that Shevardnadze, in his talks with Matlock,
``corroborated the viewpoint that an obvious imbalance emerged in
the Afghan settlement.''
   It quoted him as saying, ``At a time when the Afghan government
and the Soviet Union consistently adhered to the course toward
implementing in full the Geneva agreements, Pakistan continued
destructive actions.''
   Shevardnadze also said the United States, as a guarantor, has an
obligation to ensure ``the letter and the spirit'' of the pact,
according to Tass.
   It said Matlock delivered a letter to the foreign minister from
Secretary of State George P. Shultz, but said nothing about the
contents.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert declined to comment about
the letter.
   Shevardnadze told reporters in Kabul Sunday that the Soviet
withdrawal would would proceed on schedule despite the Pakistani
``infractions.''
   He said the Soviet troops would be out of 25 of Afghanistan's 30
provinces soon, and half of the force would be out as promised by
Aug. 15.
   Shevardnadze did not specify the five provinces where Soviet
troops would remain for some time. Afghan officials earlier this
year announced formation of a special northern zone, where the bulk
of the nation's natural resources are located, and it is believed
the government is establishing a stronghold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
