<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Elephants     08-08 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elephants,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Bill To Combat Illegal Ivory Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday passed legislation to
combat illegal trafficking in African elephant ivory.
   Sent to the Senate by voice vote, the measure would prohibit
imports into this country of any ivory taken in violation of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.
   That worldwide agreement uses a system of quotas and ivory
markings in an effort to regulate the international trade in ivory
from African elephants, whose numbers have fallen to an estimated
700,000 from 1.5 million in 1979.
   The bill would ban importation of raw ivory from any nation
without a native elephant population and would prohibit exportation
of raw ivory from the United States.
   The legislation would require the Interior Department to license
all U.S. commercial importers and exporters of ivory and to declare
moratoria on ivory imports from nations lacking adequate elephant
protection programs.
   The department would have to do a country-by-country review of
the programs and decide by Dec. 31, 1989, whether a particular
nation's preservation efforts are adequate.
   Violations of the proposed law would carry a maximum civil
penalty of $5,000 and a maximum criminal penalty of a $200,000 fine
and a year in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
