<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ContraAid 3rdLd-Writethru a0717 08-08 1049</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0717,1010</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senators Attack Democratic Contra Aid Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after pvs 14th graf to add comment from
Contra leader; picks up pvs 15th graf bgng ``Virtually all ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican support for a Democratic Contra aid
plan collapsed Monday after GOP senators and leaders of the
Nicaraguan rebels denounced it and White House officials said it
might prove impossible to implement.
   Following an hour-long private meeting to discuss the Democratic
attempt to forge a bipartisan Contra-aid policy, many Republicans
emerged to criticize the effort, some calling it an attempt to
provide political cover for opponents of Contra aid.
   ``The Democratic plan is unsatisfactory,'' said Sen. Strom
Thurmond, R-S.C. ``I hope they will change their minds and do what
has to be done.''
   ``They know that it won't work or they wouldn't be supporting
it,'' Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said of the Democrats. He
complained that many of the Democrats who have added their support
to the compromise effort are long-time opponents of arming the
Contra rebels to fight Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who took part in the initial
negotiations last week, told reporters: ``Negotiations are over
with. I don't think there is any more room. We've gone as far as we
can go.''
   He predicted Democrats will hold together on the issue, and he
dismissed the GOP complaints, saying `` They really don't have a
leg to stand on, substantively.''
   Despite the rancor, Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas
said he would take ``one last shot'' at meeting his colleagues'
objections to the proposal.
   And Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the chief architect
of the Democratic Contra-aid package, said discussions had resumed
between the White House and Dole's office and told his colleagues:
``I still hope that we can have the co-sponsorship of my amendment
by Mr. Dole and others on the Republican side. I would like to have
an action by the Senate that is strongly bipartisan.''
   Dole said that in the hours after the breakup of the GOP
senators' meeting some progress at compromise had been made.
   But he added: ``I wouldn't want to be overly optimistic.''
   Sources inside the meeting said Colin Powell, President Reagan's
national security adviser, reported that representatives of the
government agencies that would have to implement the plan told him
it does not provide sufficient funds to do the job.
   Powell told reporters on Friday that he thought progress had
been made in working out an acceptable package but a source quoted
him as telling the GOP senators that the White House now has
serious reservations about it.
   ``He said, ``We cannot implement it. We've talked with the
people who would have to implement it and it cannot be done,'''
according to the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They also said Contra leaders contacted the White House and
several GOP senators Monday morning to declare their unanimous
opposition to the plan. They quoted them as saying they would
rather risk getting no aid at all than to accept restrictions
drafted by the Democrats.
   Bosco Matamoros, a spokesman for the Contra resistance forces,
told the Associated Press that Contra leaders see the Democratic
plan as unacceptable and resulting from ``internal politics in the
United States which basically seek to reward (Nicaraguan President)
Daniel Ortega for not complying with the commitments of the peace
process.''
   ``This new legislation will only increase the pressures on the
resistance which brought the Sandinistas to the negotiating
table,'' Matamoros said. ``It will place the option on us to
surrender or become refugees.''
   Virtually all Senate Democrats had endorsed the compromise
drafted late last week by Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., Dole and a handful of other leaders of both parties.
   The Democratic plan would permit $27.1 million in immediate
non-lethal ``humanitarian'' logistical aid to the Contras.
   But it also would give Reagan an opportunity to ask Congress in
September or October to release some $16.3 million in previously
purchased arms, ammunition and other military supplies now stored
in warehouses in Central America.
   Byrd and House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, promised Republican
leaders last week that they would bring a military aid proposal to
a prompt vote in both houses of Congress if Reagan certifies that
Nicaragua has disrupted the ``peace and stability'' of Central
America by taking two of three possible actions.
   The three include: an unprovoked military attack on the Contras;
continued ``blatant violations'' of the regional peace plan; and
continued ``unacceptable levels of military assistance by
Soviet-bloc countries, including Cuba.''
   But several Republicans emerging from the meeting, most of them
Contra supporters, said the plan is fatally flawed.
   Stevens said a chief objection is that there is no effective
method of getting the military supplies to the Contras inside
Nicaragua from the warehouses in Honduras.
   ``They would have to come out of Nicaragua to pick it up in
Honduras,'' Stevens said. ``That won't work.''
   Some senators also complained that the Democratic plan bars U.S.
intelligence agencies and the Pentagon from delivering military aid
to the Contras, saying that because deliveries must be made in the
face of the Sandinista armed forces, those are the only agencies
equipped to do the job.
   Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, said the Democratic plan is intended
merely to provide political insurance for Contra-aid opponents.
   ``We shouldn't give cover to the people who have been trying to
destroy the freedom fighters for their entire careers in the
Senate,'' Symms said. ``It's just a political cover for people to
use so they can say they are for Contra aid when in reality it's a
death knell for the Contras.''
   He said there was an apparent consensus inside the meeting that
Republicans should seek a vote on a proposal drafted earlier by
Dole that would not only provide ``humanitarian'' aid for the
Contras and a vote on releasing the stored arms already approved
but would provide $20 million in new military aid as well.
   If the Byrd plan were adopted it could defuse a potential
embarrassment for the Democrats whose presidential candidate,
Michael Dukakis, has opposed military aid to the Contras while his
running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, has voted for it in the
past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
