<2ND_LINE>AM-Sea Turtles,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Scorecard: Shrimp 1, Sea Turtles 0</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved legislation Monday to
temporarily bar the Reagan administration from carrying out a plan
to require shrimp fishermen to use devices to protect endangered
and threatened sea turtles.
   The bill, sent to the Senate by voice vote, would prohibit
making the devices mandatory before Sept. 30, a month after such
regulations are slated to take effect.
   The delay is to allow House and Senate negotiators time to work
out differences in their versions of legislation to reauthorize the
Endangered Species Act.
   Both bills would prohibit requiring the devices in inshore
waters until May 1990. The Senate bill also would ban device
regulations for offshore waters until next May.
   Turtles often drown when snared in shrimp nets.
</TEXT>
