<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Frenay     08-08 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Frenay,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henri Frenay, Major Figure In French Resistance, 82</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henri Frenay, a professional soldier who became a
major figure in the French Resistance during the Nazi occupation of
France in World War II, died at the age of 82, family members said
Monday.
   Frenay died Saturday in Porte-Vecchio on the French
Mediterranean island of Corsica, the home of his wife, Chilina, and
was buried there Sunday, Le Monde newspaper reported. Cause of
death was not given.
   His only child, Henri, said in a statement that a Mass would be
celebrated in Paris at a date to be announced later. On Monday
night, the presidential palace said in a statement that President
Francois Mitterrand would attend the ceremony and ``would hope the
nation renders a solemn homage to Henri Frenay.''
   Last March, Mitterrand, himself a Resistance figure, awarded
Frenay the Grand Cross of the Legion of Honor, calling him ``the
incarnation of the young, interior Resistance.''
   Frenay _ known by the pseudonym Charvet _ founded the Secret
Army during the occupation, the Resistance group Combat, and the
underground Resistance newspaper of the same name.
   Born Nov. 19, 1905 in Lyon, Frenay was educated at France's
military academy, St. Cyr. A captain when Germany invaded France in
May 1940, Frenay was captured the following month, but escaped. He
returned to Lyon where he at once began organizing resistance
against the Germans.
   After the Liberation, he served in the provisional governments
of 1944 and 1945 as minister for prisoners, deportees and refugees.
   He was promoted to colonel in 1945.
   Frenay wrote several books on the Resistance, including ``La
Nuit Finira'' (The Night Will End), published in 1974;
``Volontaires de la Nuit'' (Volunteers of the Night) 1975, and
``L'Enigme Jean Moulin'' (The Jean Moulin Riddle) 1977.
   His vision of his mission differed from that of Gen. Charles de
Gaulle, who wanted all resistance groups to work under the umbrella
of his London-based leadership.
   ``Well, Charvet, France will choose between you and me,''
Frenay, quoting de Gaulle, recounted in his book ``La Nuit Finira.''
   In the 1965 presidential election, Frenay called for a vote
against de Gaulle, who he said represented a ``haughty and obsolete
nationalism.''
   After the war, Frenay became administrator of a toy company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0150 </DOCNO>
