<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FloridaEnglish     08-08 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida English,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Language Question To Go To Voters In November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proponents of making English the
state's official language got enough signatures with one day to
spare to put their proposed constitutional amendment before the
voters.
   The group, Florida English, thought it had enough signatures to
get the issue on the November ballot, but last Tuesday learned it
was 930 short.
   ``They have made it,'' Ethel Baxter, assistant director of the
division of elections, said Monday afteroon.
   The deadline was Tuesday at 5 p.m.
   ``Now that it's on the ballot, we think it will pass
overwhelmingly,'' said Pat Fulton, a spokeswoman for Florida
English.
   ``We still have more work ahead of us,'' Fulton said in a
telephone interview from Miami. ``We overcame some odds _ you know,
the last minute numbers problem.''
   The referendum would ask voters to designate English as the
official language, but would leave it up to the state Legislature
to decide what, if any, government practices would be changed.
   In June, a group called English Plus, launched a campaign
against the constitutional amendment, saying the law is
discriminatory and could cripple business and tourism in a state
with strong ties to Latin America.
   Signatures of 8 percent of the Floridians who voted in the last
general election are needed to get an amendment on the ballot by
initiative. Besides that statewide requirement of 342,939 names,
the 8 percent minimum must be met in 10 of the state's 19
congressional districts, which was what gave Florida English some
trouble.
   The group collected 5,273 signatures to make up for the
signature shortage in three days, Fulton said.
</TEXT>
