<2ND_LINE>AM-Retirement Home Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Employee Turned Off Alarm in Retirement Home Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with identity of victim. Picks
up 3rd graf, `The fire...'. SUBS last graf to conform.
^By WILL LESTER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLANTATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire alarm went off when a fatal blaze
broke out at a retirement home, but an employee turned it off
because residents previously had activated the alarm as a prank,
police said Monday.
   One resident, Howard Sheder, 74, died in Sunday's fire at the
Golden Age Retirement Home and 17 other residents were taken to
hospitals, mainly for treatment of smoke inhalation. Four rescue
workers and a man who aided them also were treated for smoke
inhalation and exhaustion.
   The fire may have been caused by someone smoking in a room, said
Cherian Samuel, owner of the 23-resident home in this Fort
Lauderdale suburb. The official cause of the fire was still
uncertain, police spokesman Ed Plaisted said, however.
   The facility has smoke detectors and passed a fire department
inspection in March 1988, Plaisted said.
   But when a detector went off, the employee ``turned it off
thinking (the residents) were playing with it. Some people in the
neighborhood spotted the fire and called it in,'' Plaisted said.
   The quick work of two police officers in the area when the call
came in and a civilian who aided them saved lives in the nursing
home as thick, black smoke swept through it, the spokesman said.
   ``They went in there with reckless abandon, kicking open bedroom
doors,'' he said.
   Damage to the one-story structure was not heavy; no official
damage estimate was released.
   ``I think it's a tragedy because one loss of life occurred,''
Fire Chief Robert Pudney said, ``but it could have been worse.''
   The blaze was put out within 11 minutes, he said.
   Samuel said the fire began in Sheder's room. He said Sheder had
been warned not to smoke in his room.
</TEXT>
