<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Nicaragua     08-08 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Nicaragua,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Leader Visits Noriega, Criticizes `Imperialist
Policies'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua
and Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the boss of Panama, declared
Monday that both their countries are victims of U.S. imperialist
policies.
   Noriega, who is under federal U.S. indictment on drug
trafficking charges, welcomed Ortega personally when the Nicaraguan
leader arrived at a military air base for an unannounced three-day
official visit.
   Ortega said his trip was a gesture of solidarity with Panama.
   ``We are here to emphasize the gratitude of the Nicaraguan
people to the people of Panama, who like the Nicaraguan people are
under attack by imperialist policies'' of the United States, Ortega
said in a brief statement to reporters.
   ``We are also here to ratify the friendly relations existing
between the people and government of Nicaragua and the people and
government of Panama.'' Noriega said Ortega's visit ``shows the
points of agreement that exist among peoples who are the object of
aggression.''
   When pressed to explain, Noriega replied: ``Those of the empire
against the weak ones.''
   The Reagan administration supports rebels who have fought since
1981 to overthrow Ortega's leftist Sandinista government.
Washington also has tried economic and diplomatic means in the past
year to force Noriega out as head of the 15,000-member Panamanian
Defense Forces, the position from which he runs the country.
   A federal grand jury in Florida indicted Noriega last February
on drug smuggling charges. Noriega has denied the accusations.
   Last week Secretary of State George P. Shultz tried
unsuccessfully to get the foreign ministers of El Salvador,
Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala to issue a joint declaration
accusing Nicaragua of not living up to a Central American peace
agreement signed Aug. 7, 1987.
   Nicaragua was not invited to the Aug. 1 meeting of Shultz and
the Central American foreign ministers in Guatemala City. Shultz
now is on a Latin American tour and has scheduled meetings Tuesday
with the chief executives of Honduras, Costa Rica and El Salvador.
   He then will travel to the inauguration Wednesday of Ecuador's
left-leaning President-elect Rodrigo Borja, which President Fidel
Castro of Cuba also plans to attend.
   Ortega also had planned to attend Borja's inauguration but then
postponed his trip to Ecuador by one day.
   Nicaraguan officials in Panama said he plans to arrive in Quito,
capital of Ecuador, on Thursday. They did not explain the change in
plans.
   Borja's predecessor, President Leon Febres Cordero, broke
diplomatic relations with Nicaragua in 1985 after Ortega made a
remark Febres considered offensive. Borja promised he would
re-establish relations with the Sandinistas the day after he was
sworn in.
   Asked by reporters to comment on Shultz's activities in Central
America, Ortega said it was the secretary's purpose ``to weaken the
unity so necessary among Latin American nations to defend their
common interests.''
</TEXT>
