<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParkRiot 1stLd-Writethru a0615 08-08 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Park Riot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0615,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Riot, City Drops Park Curfew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf `I don't' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with more
brutality complaints, details, additional quote from police
commissioner. Picks up 9th graf pvs `Koch aides...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city will not enforce a 1 a.m. curfew at
most parks this summer to prevent violence similar to a weekend
riot that left 38 people injured, officials said Monday.
   ``The weather is very hot. The beaches are closed. People are
really angry about (the curfew),'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said of the
confrontation early Sunday in Tompkins Square Park on Manhattan's
Lower East Side.
   Koch also blamed ``provocateurs,'' saying they incited the
violence by throwing bottles and fireworks at police.
   ``There are people looking for confrontation. ... And if they
take on a cop, it's at their peril,'' he said.
   Four hundred fifty police officers tangled with 250
demonstrators who gathered in the street outside Tompkins Square
Park to protest its closing. Witnesses charged that protesters and
bystanders were beaten without cause.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said police tried to close the
park at the request of residents who complained of loud music and
drug dealing.
   Neither Koch nor Ward would say if officers used undue force.
Ward said news footage of officers beating people had to be viewed
in context.
   ``I don't know of any extreme use of force,'' Ward said. But the
Civilain Complaint Review Board said it had received 23 complaints
about police conduct at the riot.
   One alleged victim had a broken finger, three had cuts that
needed stitches, 14 had bruises they said were caused by
nightsticks and five said they were shoved or pushed, said Sandra
Marsh, the board's executive director. ``If there was extreme use
of force, I urge those people to come forward, and their complaints
will be investigated,'' Ward said. Even if officers were attacked,
he said, ``provocation is not a defense to the illegal use of
force.''
   Koch aides distributed photocopies of flyers at a news
conference said to have been handed out by demonstrators. One
warned landlords around Tompkins Square that if the curfew were
enforced ``our organization will destroy your homes''; another was
bordered with drawings of guns and explosives. Koch called them the
work of ``provocateurs,'' and Ward said ``professional
demonstrators'' were involved.
   Curfews at two parks, one in Greenwich Village and one on
Manhattan's East Side, will still be enforced to combat drug
dealing, Koch said.
</TEXT>
