<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irag-Victory     08-08 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irag-Victory,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Celebrate `Great Victory' Over Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fireworks exploded in the night sky over
Baghdad early Tuesday and jubilant Iraqis fired thousands of
bullets into the air to celebrate ``the great victory'' over Iran.
   The celebration came after U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar announced in New York on Monday that Iran and Iraq had
agreed to a cease-fire in their eight-year-old war.
   Perez de Cuellar said the cease-fire would start Aug. 20 and
peace negotiations would take place five days later.
   Shortly after midnight, government television called on Iraqis
``to celebrate the great victory achieved by Iraq'' on ``the
greatest day of all.''
   It announced a tree-day period of celebration.
   The war has killed or wounded about 1 million people and cost
both countries billions of dollars.
   Iraqis danced on pickup trucks and waved palm leaves from the
windows of cars driving through Baghdad as tracer bullets and
flares flashed overhead.
   ``The war is over. Victory for Iraq,'' said a man at the
entrance to the Al-Rashid hotel as he looked up at the fireworks.
   ``The war is over, praise be to God,'' said a woman beside him.
   ``Here, take this'' a security man said, offering a reporter an
automatic rifle.
   The guard then fired the rifle into the sky, laughing with other
security men across the street who unleashed scores of rounds from
a machine gun.
   Not all of the bullets went skyward. A car in the Al-Rashid
parking lot had a bullet hole in the hood.
   Children scampered through the streets collecting cartridges.
</TEXT>
