<DOCNO> AP880808-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-O'NeillHouse     08-08 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Neill House,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Commission Given Option Of Moving O'Neill House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a boarding house where
Eugene O'Neill wrote his first plays agreed Monday to give
preservationists a chance to save the building by moving it to
another location.
   The owners wanted to raze the house, built around 1860, to make
way for a summer home, but the state won a temporary injunction
blocking the demolition.
   The agreement, which still must be formally presented to the
court, ``gives everybody at least something of what they want,''
said state Assistant Attorney General Lawrence Russ, representing
the state Historical Commission.
   The owners gave the state until January to decide whether the
1{-story building can be moved, and until March 1, 1989 to remove
the building from its site on a sandy stretch of the Thames River
in southeastern Connecticut.
   Edward Moukawsher, attorney for the four owners, said the house
is run-down and that it would have been too much of a burden to
restore it. Moukawsher had argued that the house, built in
Carpenter Gothic style, was only of minor historical significance
and that its importance had been exaggerated.
   The O'Neill family's summer home, Monte Cristo Cottage, is
located only a block away from the boarding house and is listed as
a National Historic Landmark.
   The boarding house could not receive that designation because of
its historical similarity to the cottage, Russ said.
   O'Neill was convalescing from tuberculosis when he was taken on
as a winter guest at the boarding house in 1913-14, while the rest
of his family traveled on a theater tour.
   During that time, he produced four one-act plays that were
incorporated into his first published work, ``Thirst and Other One
Act Plays,'' and his first full-length play, ``Bread and Butter,''
said historic preservationists.
   While moving the house would strip it of some of its historical
significance, it still would be the building where O'Neill began
his career as a dramatist, Russ said.
   O'Neill, who died in 1953, won four Pulitzer Prizes for his
plays and the Nobel Prize in literature.
   The agreement was reached on the same day a Superior Court
hearing was set on whether the injunction should remain in effect
pending a trial. Russ conceded that the state would not have been
able to prevent the home's ultimate destruction if a trial had been
held.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
