<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Airbus     08-08 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Airbus,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Waning for Flight Recorder From Downed Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran is returning equipment it rented to
search for the still-missing flight recorder from the Iran Air
jetliner shot down by the U.S. Navy, the official Islamic Republic
News Agency said Monday.
   IRNA quoted an unidentified airport official in Iran's southern
port city of Bandar Abbas as saying electronic beeps given off by
the flight recorder had almost stopped.
   Iran said an oil-exploration ship equipped with exploratory
devices will continue the search after engine repair work.
   The report quoted another unidentified source as saying the
intensive search, using equipment rented from Britain, was not
really needed as the Navy admitted it shot down the plane.
   The Iran Air Airbus was shot down July 3 by the missile cruiser
USS Vincennes while on a flight over the southern Persian Gulf from
Bandar Abbas to Dubai in the United Arab Emirates. All 290 people
on board were killed.
   U.S. Navy officials said the Vincennes mistook the passenger
plane for an F-14 jet fighter planning to attack.
</TEXT>
