<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For eight years, Iran and Iraq sent their
youth to slaughter, squandered their wealth and mortaged their
futures in a war that gained nothing for either side.
   Children as young as 13, eagerly seeking a martyr's death,
perished as sacrificial mine sweepers. Children, parents and
grandparents were blown to bits or crippled by bombs, shells and
missiles in the cities of both sides. Soldiers and civilians were
maimed by poison warfare.
   In all, more than 1 million people were killed or wounded. The
war cost hundreds of billions of dollars and caused measureless
agony and grief.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, the U.N. secretary-general, announced
Monday in New York that the two enemies had agreed to end the war
with a cease-fire Aug. 20 and to begin peace negotiations Aug. 25
in Geneva.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Monday voted overwhelming
approval of a $3.9 billion drought-relief bill designed to aid
hundreds of thousands of farmers and ranchers battered by one of
the driest growing seasons on record.
   ``This bill is a message of hope to the American farmer,'' Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee,
said shortly before the 92-0 vote. ``Help is on the way.''
   The politically popular legislation, the most expensive disaster
relief measure ever enacted for agriculture, was expected to
receive final legislative approval in the House as early as
Tuesday. President Reagan is expected to sign it into law within
days of receiving it.
   Agriculture Department officials have said the assistance could
begin reaching farmers about 60 days after enactment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors warmly applauded
President Reagan on Monday for a vintage attack on Washington and a
tribute to their initiatives in dealing with national issues such
as welfare and job creation.
   ``He was talking language we understand,'' Republican Gov.
Thomas Kean of New Jersey said of Reagan's address to the National
Governors Association.
   Democratic Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas replied,
``Absolutely,'' when asked if he thought it was a political speech
designed to help Vice President George Bush in the presidential
campaign.
   ``But it was one that was appropriate within the limits of the
association,'' Clinton added. ``I think it was as political as he
could be without stepping out of line.''
   Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the association's most
prominent current member, was not present for the president's
speech.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EIGHTY EIGHT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This tiny town's number came up Monday
_ 8-8-88 _ and visitors crowded in from around the country, calls
came in from around the world and the post office was besieged with
thousands and thousands of letters.
   ``You've got to think of your eight lingo on a day like today,''
said Mike Carroll of nearby Bowling Green, whose favorite number is
eight. ``I bought an eight-pack of beer, and I'm having a great
time, g-r-e-i-g-h-t.''
   Visitors to the southwestern Kentucky town 8.8 miles southeast
of Glasgow could buy sandwiches or an RC Cola-moon pie combination
for 88 cents at the 88 Market under a banner that read ``Happy
Birthday Eighty Eight, Ky.''
   One of the most talked-about parts of the celebration was the
marriage of Tom Accardo and Deborah Muhlbeier of Casper, Wyo.,
planned for 8:08 p.m. on 8-8-88 in Eighty-Eight, on the eighth step
of the church.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of new planets and of complex
organic chemicals in comets is encouraging astronomers to intensify
their search of the universe for intelligent life beyond the Earth.
   ``The circumstantial evidence is mounting every day'' that
intelligent life could have developed elsewhere in the universe,
Michael J. Klein, manager of NASA's radio search for life, said
Monday. ``It is encouraging.''
   Klein said discoveries announced last week that planet-like
objects have been found orbiting distant stars, and that organic
chemicals thought to be the precursors to life exist in comets
support fundamental theories about life evolving from cosmic
chemistry.
   ``That is the circumstantial evidence that life exists
elsewhere,'' Klein said. ``We know now that the materials are
there. It gives us a good feeling that we are on the right track.''
   He commented at the 20th assembly of the International
Astronomical Union, which is meeting in Baltimore.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Months behind in an industry where everything
is due last week, producers and scriptwriters scrambled Monday to
regroup after a 22-week strike that idled thousands and devastated
the fall television schedule.
   The Writers Guild of America membership Sunday voted 2,111 to
412, or by 83.7 percent, in favor of the pact with the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   ``I would say nobody's in fighting form,'' NBC Entertainment
President Brandon Tartikoff said.
   The walkout crippled Hollywood and left the upcoming TV season
in shambles. The season's start will be delayed, perhaps until
mid-October or later, despite the anticipated glut of written
material.
   The production season for prime-time television usually begins
in late June and early July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insider trading on stolen Business Week stock
tip columns has alarmed the magazine's rivals, compelling some to
review their own security and recheck back issues to make sure they
haven't been victimized, too.
   ``We don't take any pleasure in what happened to Business Week,
but we're in the enviable position of bolting the barn door before
the horse escapes, or at least checking the locks,'' said Gary
Belis, spokesman for Fortune, which has a biweekly circulation of
755,000. ``We're checking the locks.''
   Belis said a spot check of Fortune's ``Companies to Watch''
column going back several months showed no unusual prepublication
activity in any stocks mentioned.
   Senior editorial officials at Forbes and Money, two other widely
read business magazines, also said they were reassessing protection
of market-sensitive material in the aftermath of the scandal at
Business Week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press will
be allowed to merge their business and production operations
because the smaller Free Press was in danger of financial failure
stemming from years of steady and apparently irreversible losses,
Attorney General Edwin Meese III said Monday.
   In approving the application for a joint operating agreement,
Meese rejected the recommendation of a Justice Department
administrative law judge who said the two newspapers' pricing
policies were unrealistic.
   Meese, however, said there was little prospect for the Free
Press to return to profitability in Detroit's highly competitive
market.
   ``For me, the continuing and persistent operating losses
suffered by the Free Press over the course of nearly a decade, with
no prospect of unilaterally reversing that economic condition in
the foreseeable future, describes a newspaper `in danger of
financial failure','' Meese said in his opinion.
   Meese told reporters that the Free Press' losses were not
manipulated but came ``from intense competition.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after Love Canal was
declared a national disaster area because buried chemicals were
oozing to the surface, the largely abandoned neighborhood remains
at the center of environmental debate.
   The former chemical dump that forced hundreds of families from
their homes has been fenced off and surrounded with clay and
plastic liners to prevent chemicals from leaking into groundwater.
   Corroding drums of chemicals have been separated and complex
runoff monitoring and collection systems have been built.
   But even though the contamination has been largely contained and
state officials have begun to talk about restoring the neighborhood
to residential use, critics think Love Canal and hundreds of
similar sites throughout the nation will remain potential disasters
until a safe disposal method is found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Nikos Kazantzakis, who created
joy of life with ``Zorba the Greek'' and a religious storm with
``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' remains popular in his native
land 30 years after his death.
   His novels sell thousands of copies every year, mainly in Greek
but also in English, French, German and Japanese. He is believed to
be the most-read writer in modern Greek.
   ``We have a huge turnover in the half-dozen major Kazantzakis
novels. ... In Greek he's mostly bought by young people, and then
the tourists pick up the foreign language copies,'' said Byron
Dokimakis. He owns a leading bookstore in Heraklion, capital of
Crete, the island where Kazantzakis was born.
   Dokimakis said the two most popular novels are ``Zorba,'' an
exuberant portrayal set on Crete of a man with a huge zest for
life, and ``Last Temptation,'' which presents Jesus as a weak,
unstable man who doubts his divinity and dreams of making love to
Mary Magdalene, the reformed sinner.
</TEXT>
