<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv14   08-08 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv14,0443</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Aug. 14, the 227th day of 1988. There are 139
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 14, 1945, President Harry S. Truman announced that Japan
had unconditionally surrendered, ending the hostilities of World
War II. Capitulation came several days after the atomic bombings of
Hiroshima and Nagasaki, and after Emperor Hirohito called on
Japan's war council to give up.
   On this date:
   In 1848, the Oregon Territory was established.
   In 1900, international forces _ including U.S. Marines _ entered
Beijing to put down the Boxer Rebellion, which was aimed at ridding
China of foreigners.
   In 1917, China declared war on Germany and Austria at the start
of World War I.
   In 1935, the Social Security Act became law, creating
unemployment insurance and pension plans for the elderly.
   In 1941, President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime
Minister Winston S. Churchill signed the Atlantic Charter.
   In 1947, Pakistan became independent of British rule.
   In 1951, newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst died in
Beverly Hills, Calif.
   In 1962, robbers held up a U.S. mail truck in Plymouth, Mass.,
making off with more than $1.5 million.
   In 1969, British troops intervened militarily in Northern
Ireland as sectarian violence between Protestant and Roman
Catholics increased.
   In 1973, the U.S. bombing of Cambodia came to a halt, marking
the official end to 12 years of American combat in Indochina.
   In 1980, President Jimmy Carter and Vice President Walter
Mondale were nominated for a second term in office at the
Democratic National Convention in New York.
   Ten years ago: Israel's Cabinet, concerned about upcoming
Mideast peace talks in the U.S., shelved a plan to build five new
Jewish settlements in the occupied West Bank at least until after
the summit.
   Five years ago: President Reagan met with Mexican President
Miguel de la Madrid in La Paz, where the two leaders failed to
resolve their disagreement over policies for Central America.
   One year ago: The government reported that America's merchandise
trade deficit had soared to $15.7 billion in June 1987 as Americans
stepped up a buying spree of imported goods.
   Today's birthdays: Newspaper columnist Russell Baker is 63.
Singer Buddy Greco is 62. Actress Alice Ghostley is 62. Rock singer
David Crosby is 47. Actress Susan Saint James is 42.
   Thought for today: ``God made everything out of nothing. But the
nothingness shows through.'' _ Paul Valery, French poet and critic
(1871-1945).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0167 </DOCNO>
