<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv15   08-08 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv15,0480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Aug. 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Aug. 15, the 228th day of 1988. There are 138
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on Aug. 15th, 1888, T.E. Lawrence, the
British soldier who gained fame as Lawrence of Arabia, was born in
Tremadoc, Wales. Lawrence played a leading role in the Arabs'
revolt against Turkish Ottoman rule during World War I. He died in
1935 as the result of a motorcycle accident.
   On this date:
   In 1057, Macbeth, the King of Scotland, was slain by the son of
King Duncan.
   In 1769, Napoleon Bonaparte was born on the island of Corsica.
   In 1914, the Panama Canal opened to traffic.
   In 1918, the United States and Russia severed diplomatic ties.
   In 1935, humorist Will Rogers and aviator Wiley Post were killed
when their airplane crashed near Point Barrow, Ala.
   In 1939, ``The Wizard of Oz,'' MGM's musical version of the L.
Frank Baum fantasy, premiered at Grauman's Chinese Theater in
Hollywood.
   In 1945, U.S. wartime rationing of gasoline and fuel oil ended.
   In 1947, India became independent after some 200 years of
British rule. Jawaharlal Nehru became India's first prime minister.
   In 1948, the Republic of Korea was proclaimed.
   In 1961, East German workers began building the Berlin Wall.
   In 1969, the Woodstock Music and Art Fair opened in New York
state.
   In 1971, President Richard M. Nixon announced a 90-day freeze on
wages, prices and rents.
   In 1974, South Korean President Park Chung-hee escaped an
assassination attempt, but his wife was killed.
   Ten years ago: The U.S. House of Representatives approved, by a
vote of 233-169, a 39-month extension of time for ratification of
the proposed Equal Rights Amendment to the Constitution, and sent
it to the Senate.
   Five years ago: President Reagan, speaking in New Orleans,
likened his Central America policy to the citizens' crime-fighting
program ``Neighborhood Watch,'' saying that ``outside troublemakers
and bullies will think twice.''
   One year ago: Thousands of Elvis Presley faithful marched past
the grave of the ``king'' of rock and roll in Memphis, Tenn., as
they began an all-night vigil marking the 10th anniversary of his
death.
   Today's birthdays: Cooking expert Julia Child is 76. Actress
Wendy Hiller is 76. Eagle Forum president Phyllis Schlafly is 64.
Playwright Robert Bolt is 64. Actress Rose Marie is 63. Actor Mike
Connors is 63. Actress Janice Rule is 57. Civil rights activist
Vernon Jordan is 53. Actor Jim Dale is 53. Broadcast journalist and
author Linda Ellerbee is 44. Britain's Princess Anne is 38.
   Thought for today: ``Why would anybody lie? The truth is always
more colorful.'' _ Jerry Hall, American model.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
