<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv16,0512</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Aug. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Aug. 16, the 229th day of 1988. There are 137
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 16, 1977, the ``king of rock 'n' roll,'' Elvis Presley,
died of a heart ailment at Graceland Mansion in Memphis, Tenn., at
the age of 42.
   On this date:
   In 1777, American forces won an important victory of the
Revolutionary War at the Battle of Bennington, Vt.
   In 1812, Detroit fell to British and Indian forces in the War of
1812.
   In 1829, Siamese twins Chang and Eng Bunker arrived in Boston
aboard the ship Sachem to be exhibited to the Western world.
   In 1858, a telegraphed message from Britain's Queen Victoria to
U.S. President James Buchanan was transmitted over the recently
laid trans-Atlantic cable.
   In 1861, President Abraham Lincoln prohibited the states of the
Union from trading with the seceding states of the Confederacy.
   In 1894, labor leader George Meany was born in New York City.
   In 1896, gold was found at Bonanza Creek, Ala.
   In 1948, baseball legend Babe Ruth died in New York at the age
of 53.
   In 1956, Adlai E. Stevenson was nominated for president at the
Democratic convention in Chicago.
   In 1960, Britain granted independence to the crown colony of
Cyprus.
   In 1984, a federal jury in Los Angeles acquitted former
automaker John Z. DeLorean of all eight counts in a $24 million
cocaine conspiracy indictment.
   Ten years ago: James Earl Ray, convicted of assassinating Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. in 1968, repeated his assertion at a Capitol
Hill hearing that he did not commit the crime, saying he'd been set
up to take the blame by a mysterious man called Raoul.
   Five years ago: The United States admitted that Army
intelligence officers had helped former Nazi official Klaus Barbie
flee to Bolivia and escape prosecution following World War II after
he'd been recruited as an anti-communist spy.
   One year ago: 156 people were killed when Northwest Airlines
Flight 255 crashed while trying to take off from a Detroit airport;
the sole survivor was four-year-old Cecelia Cichan. Thousands of
people worldwide began a two-day celebration of the ``harmonic
convergence,'' which heralded what believers called the start of a
new, purer age of humankind.
   Today's birthdays: Former Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin
is 75. Actor Fess Parker is 63. Actress Ann Blyth is 60. Actor
Robert Culp is 58. Sportscaster Frank Gifford is 58. Singer Eydie
Gorme is 56. Actress Julie Newmar is 53. Actress Anita Gillette is
52. Actress Carole Shelley is 49. Actress Lesley Ann Warren is 42.
Singer Madonna is 30. Actor Timothy Hutton is 28.
   Thought for today: ``Life is not lost by dying! Life is lost
minute by minute, day by dragging day, in all the thousand, small,
uncaring ways.'' _ Stephen Vincent Benet, American author and poet
(1898-1943).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
