<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--OtherFolks Adv21   08-08 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Other Folks, Adv 21,1054</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ColorFoto subscribers get 0 35mm slides.)
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Cloyce Webster is a pack rat. He's also a
handyman, storekeeper, cobbler, mechanic, storyteller, artist,
husband and father. In addition to running a cluttered general
store in rural Michigan, he has spent half a century collecting
derelict automobiles and other castoff items most people would call
junk.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You won't find Webster, Mich., on any map.
But you won't come across many in these parts who don't know of
Webster and its ``founder,'' Cloyce Webster.
   ``I guess everyone knows about me,'' Webster says, hands thrust
in the pockets of his worn overalls.
   Webster is proprietor of a ramshackle general store on a dirt
road 7 miles north of Fremont. A sign outside reads:
   WEBSTER MICHIGAN
   OPEN 7.A.M. TO 10 P.M.
   CLOSED SUNDAYS
   He has no post office in his store, but he's so well-known
locally that mail addressed to Webster, Mich., reaches him.
   Since first setting up shop here in 1932, Webster has been
collecting derelict automobiles and gadgets, pop bottles and
hubcaps, batteries and milk jugs, toasters and sewing machines, all
kinds of litter that together comprise something of a scrapbook of
the 20th century. Indeed, a trip to Webster throws the visitor into
a time warp, back to the days of Coca-Cola thermometers and 5-cent
soda pop.
   Cloyce Webster, a youthful-looking 70-year-old pack rat,
storekeeper, cobbler, mechanic, storyteller, artist, husband and
father.
   Surrounded by dairy farms that dot the rolling hills of
west-central Michigan, some might call Webster's 27 acres a
junkyard. But among the rusting hulks of 1930s and '40s automobiles
are some treasures.
   ``Sure, I know some of these things are worth a lot,'' he says.
``And I sell some of 'em.''
   He rummages through a box full of antique bottles. ``Here's one
of them old Dr Pepper bottles. Betcha never seen one of them
before.''
   Webster will sell you anything you want. But if you can't pay,
he's been known to make a deal. Cut him some wood, and he'll fix a
battery free of charge.
   Batteries are his specialty. But, he says, he can fix just about
anything ``if I can get the part.''
   Chances are, he has it already.
   Even more remarkably, he knows where it is.
   ``Inventory? I keep it all up here,'' Webster says, pointing to
his soiled, green cap.
   Indeed, there is a touch of organization amid the apparent chaos.
   ``See that '36 Hudson?'' Webster asks, pointing to the
moss-covered automobile partially imbedded in the ground outside
the back of his shop. ``It's filled with table-model radios. That
'35 Chevy over there? Filled with gaskets. Only gaskets.''
   Webster bought most of the old cars and bicycles, although some
were abandoned after being dropped off for repairs. ``I used to buy
everything that came along,'' he says.
   All are for sale.
   ``I can make any one of 'em run,'' Webster insists.
   Entangled in vines and weeds, are probably 500 bicycles and
cars, Webster estimates, not including all the ones in hundreds of
pieces. About 2{ tons of hubcaps are piled up, reaching the
branches of the trees.
   ``I'd clean it all out, but even if I took 10 tons a day out it
would still take seven or eight years to get rid of it all,''
Webster says.
   Inside the weathered building is a cluttered maze of spare parts
and cases of soda bottles stacked to the ceiling, dark and narrow
aisles leading to several rooms. There's a grocery section and a
shoe repair section, where Webster uses car tires to make rubber
soles _ ``guaranteed not to wear out.''
   ``This is where I do my painting,'' Webster says, indicating a
cramped area by a window. There are enamel paints on a cluttered,
flat surface, but no room to sit down.
   It is here that Webster gets away from it all, painting wildlife
scenes on aluminum printing plates.
   ``Ten dollars apiece. I sell lots of 'em,'' Webster says,
pointing to the hundreds of finished products piled in his ``art
department.''
   His subjects come from postcards, photographs, other paintings
or from memory.
   ``I start about 30 of 'em at a time,'' he says proudly,
displaying his favorite nature scenes.
   ``I started drawing on little scraps of paper when I was in the
Air Force so I'd remember what everything looked like,'' Webster
says, taking out a pile of the aging pencil drawings on a shelf.
   An 11th-grade dropout, Webster spent four years in the Air
Force, from 1942 to '46, closing the shop while he was gone.
   When he returned, he married, and he and his wife, Elaine, have
been running the store ever since, living in a rickety house next
door. Webster's 94-year-old father, a former farmer, lives down the
road.
   The Websters have three grown children, one of whom lives nearby
and sometimes helps out at the store, and eight grandchildren.
   Asked if any of his children might take over the business after
he retires, Webster hesitates, as though it was the first time he's
thought about it.
   ``I don't know,'' he says. ``But I'm not retiring any time
soon.''
   That's good news to his regulars.
   ``I've been a regular for five or six years,'' says customer
Floyd Christner, who was here this time for a battery part.
``Whenever I get a flat tire, Cloyce always fixes them _ he fixes
everything.''
   And though some days are slower than others, Webster insists he
does a hearty business, especially considering he doesn't own a
telephone.
   ``If someone wants something, they'd better see me directly,''
he says.
   On Sundays, shaven and spruced up, Webster closes shop and heads
for the United Methodist Church of Hesperia, where he sings in the
choir.
   ``I think I'm pretty good,'' he says, smiling, exposing his two
teeth _ both on the bottom.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 21</NOTE>
