<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv21   08-08 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 21,0997</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scott Bakula took on a Broadway musical right
after he went into a prime-time television series, with the
understanding that it would be goodbye New York if the TV show
turned into a hit.
   Instead, ``Eisenhower & Lutz'' was canceled by CBS and ``Romance
Romance,'' a modest little musical that uses only four actors and
minimal scenery, has blossomed on Broadway.
   ``The timing was incredible,'' Bakula said the other day,
sitting in his dressing room at the Helen Hayes Theater. ``We
wrapped the series in mid-February and started rehearsals for
`Romance Romance' in March.
   ``I came into it saying, `I've got a TV series and may have to
go back in mid-June,''' he recalls. ``And the producers said,
`OK.'''
   ``Romance Romance,'' two separate one-act musicals, looks at
love in two very different places: turn-of-the-century Vienna and
trendy, modern-day East Hampton, Long Island.
   Bakula plays a rakish man about town in the first act and an
anguished yuppie contemplating an affair with a friend's wife in
the second.
   The show and Bakula were nominated for 1988 Tony awards. Neither
won, but the musical received national exposure on the Tony
telecast and has found a growing audience. A recording by MCA
Classics is scheduled for release in late summer.
   For Bakula, the recognition secured a stage reputation that
sprouted before he first went off to California to do television.
   The 33-year-old Bakula is one of those actors who looks at ease
in both mediums, although he says he is more comfortable on stage
than on television.
   ``I find the camera to be confining, but I've gotten over
that,'' he says. ``I tend to like to be physical on stage _ to move
and to do things.''
   Television requires a certain precision, he says _ hitting your
mark and then being still.
   ``How can you act?'' Bakula asks. ``But that's the trick of it
when you're coming from the theater. Now I'm used to it.''
   Bakula, who hails from St. Louis, found performing a part of his
life while growing up.
   ``I always sang and that led to doing theater,'' he says. He
went to the Univerity of Kansas to study business but later
switched to theater.
   ``I left school and came here to work in 1976, not study
theater,'' Bakula recalls. ``But I ended up studying my head off
all over town for years.''
   Still, Bakula had a job in show business the third day he was in
New York, although he had to leave town again to get it. The work
was in a dinner theater in North Carolina which was doing
``Shenandoah,'' a musical that supported him a lot during his first
years in New York.
   ``Whenever times got lean, it seemed like a company of
`Shenandoah' would come up,'' he says.
   The actor finally made it to Broadway in 1983, seven years after
arriving in New York. He survived ``Marilyn: an American Fable,'' a
short-lived and much-maligned musical based on the life of Marilyn
Monroe. In it, he played New York Yankee legend Joe DiMaggio, one
of Monroe's husbands.
   The troubled show, which had 13 producers listed above the
title, went through weeks of previews after the first director,
choreographer and leading lady were replaced.
   ``It was very frustrating,'' Bakula says now, ``but it was my
first Broadway show, so it also was very exciting.''
   The experience led Bakula almost immediately into a much happier
effort, ``3 Guys Naked from the Waist Down.'' The off-Broadway
musical, written by Michael Rupert and Jerry Colker, was a hip,
offbeat look at the world of stand-up comedians, one job in show
business Bakula had never tried.
   ``Now I know why people are stand-up comics,'' he says. ``When
you are really cooking, you feel like you can stay out there for
two hours, and they'll laugh at anything you say. It's a real heady
kind of feeling to be totally in control of an audience.''
   Bakula went west to appear in a Los Angeles production of the
off-Broadway musical ``Nite Club Confidential.'' He moved into
television with an occasional role on CBS' ``Designing Women'' as
Annie Potts' ex-husband and a major part in ABC's ``Gung Ho,''
which died quickly in a brutal time slot where it faced both
``Dallas'' and ``Miami Vice.''
   Bakula was cast as the fly-by-night lawyer in ``Eisenhower &
Lutz'' in July 1987 but the first episode wasn't filmed until
October. CBS didn't require a pilot because of the sterling
reputation of the show's producers, Alan Burns and MTM.
   The 13 episodes that eventually were made didn't set the
Nielsens afire, though the ratings had started to improve when the
show was canceled.
   ``I can't really explain what CBS did to the show,'' he says.
``We did everything they asked of us. We even got the 18- to
40-year-old audience that sponsors love.
   ``The network only has six half-hour shows on the schedule for
the fall,'' he adds. ``There were not that many slots to fill.''
   Fortunately, while in New York to publicize ``Eisenhower &
Lutz,'' Bakula did an informal audition for Keith Herrmann and
Barry Harman, the composer and director-lyricist of ``Romance
Romance.''
   ``I hadn't sung in a while and my voice was out of shape,'' he
says. But he got the job.
   ``It's kind of like a storybook ending,'' Bakula says ``We
survived opening night, which is a rarity these days, and then got
all those Tony nominations. And business has been getting better.
I'm not going anywhere else for a while.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 21</NOTE>
