<DOCNO> AP880808-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-SouthKorea-NorthKorea Adv14   08-08 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-North Korea, Adv 14,0392</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>North Korea _ A Stark Contrast To The South</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spotlight-South Korea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Part of a three-story package</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While South Korea has developed into
one of Asia's success stories, North Korea is one of the world's
most engimatic nations.
   The north, occupying the top half of the 600-mile long
peninsula, is feared for its often wild, irrational policies and
its willingness to use violence against its opponents.
   North Korean President Kim Il Sung, now 76, rules with a
monolithic personality cult that teaches North Koreans to idolize
him.
   Giant statues of Kim, called ``Great Leader,'' dot the country,
the state-run media are filled with slavish praise of the president
and North Koreans are taught that he is loved around the world.
North Koreans generally wear badges bearing Kim's picture.
   ``The centralized control which demands total loyalty to the
leader has produced a pervasive and almost suffocating cult of
personality,'' the Institute of International Affairs in London
said in a recent report.
   Kim is attempting to build the world's first communist dynasty;
his son, Kim Jung Il, has been designated to succeed him. A
personality cult is also being built around the son, who is called
``Dear Leader.''
   The ruling Korean Workers Party enforces rigid control over all
aspects of life. Independent political groups or other
organizations are not tolerated, religion is outlawed and dissent
or opposition is suppressed.
   But the north faces mounting problems. Chronic mismanagement,
rigid state planning and massive military spending have crippled
the economy and there are reports of food shortages.
   North Korea in 1987 because the first nation ever to be declared
in default on its foreign loans by international banks. North
Korean diplomats have been caught selling drugs, liquor and watches
in Western Europe in desperate schemes to raise hard currency.
   The north invaded the south in 1950 to trigger the bloody Korean
War. It maintains the world's sixth largest army and has repeatedly
carried out terrorist attacks against the south.
   The north was blamed for the bombing of a Korean Air Lines
commercial airliner that crashed near Burma last Nov. 29, killing
115 people. The North Koreans deny any involvement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-SouthKorea-Glance Adv14   08-08 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Glance, Adv 14,0371</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: South Korea-At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-South Korea-Spotlight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some basic facts about South
Korea.
   POPULATION _ 41 million people.
   GEOGRAPHY _ A small, mountainous country about the size of
Indiana or England, South Korea occupies the southern half of the
Korean Peninsula jutting into the Sea of Japan and the Yellow Sea.
Its only border is with North Korea, but it iarby
China, the Soviet Union and Japan. The country has hot, humid
summers and very cold winters.
   GOVERNMENT _ A republic with a strong presidential system under
which s neighbor to nethe presidency initiates most programs and the prime
minister
and cabinet ministers have little power. The unicameral National
Assembly is playing a growing role.
   The country, dominated by political strongmen for most of its
history, had never had a peaceful transfer of power until Roh
Tae-woo succeeded Chun Doo-hwan as president in February. Chun, a
former general, took power with military backing in 1980.
   HISTORY _ Korea's history can be traced to at least the 1st
century B.C. Small rival kingdoms fought for control of the Korean
peninsula over the centuries, with China often dominating the area.
Japan seized the country in 1910 and proclaimed it a province.
   U.S. and Soviet forces ended the harsh Japane            $895,000
