<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   08-08 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0545</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Vibes''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Raiders of the Lost Ark,'' the Steven Spielberg@George Lucas
homage to the Saturday matinee serial, spawned a host of films in
the same genre, ranging from the good (``Romancing the Stone'') to
the poor (``The Golden Child'').
   Now comes ``Vibes,'' which lands somewhere in between.
   The new Columbia Pictures release most resembles ``Romancing the
Stone'' in that an antagonistic couple are thrown into a fortune
quest in the South American wilderness, falling in love along the
way. ``Vibes'' has some other attributes as well, including
stunning Ecuadorian scenery and the movie debut of rock superstar
Cyndi Lauper.
   The story begins promisingly in a Manhattan psychic lab operated
by Julian Sands (``Room with a View''). Among his subjects is Jeff
Goldblum, a museum worker who can reveal people's secrets by
touching their personal possessions, and Miss Lauper, a blond bimbo
who can foretell the future with the help of a spirit companion
named Lucille.
   The pair take an instant dislike for each other, and their
feelings intensify when they arrive in Ecuador. What are they doing
in Ecuador? Well, it seems that a shady character resembling the TV
detective Columbo has enlisted them to help find his lost son. Why
they would trust such a person is one of the many mysteries
contained in the script.
   Expectably, Peter Falk's ruse is exposed. What he is really
after is Incan treasure hidden for centuries in the Andes. The
search has already claimed two lives, but the lure of fortune has
still attracted thugs and adventurers who will use any means to
snatch it first.
   Such goings-on provide a reasonable basis for a high-tech,
action-adventure. So what goes wrong? For one thing, the leading
characters sound like vintage Damon Runyon, and the script writers,
Lowell Ganz and Babaloo Mandel, have supplied one-liners that only
now and then zing.
   Ken Kwapis directed with a good eye for action, but his actors
seldom shine. Goldblum, who has created a number of memorable
characters, is strangely restrained. Falk veers from the amusing to
the annoying.
   That brings us to the celebrated Miss Lauper. She is typecast as
the wise-cracking babe in search of a man, and her role seems to
duplicate Judy Holliday's Billie Dawn in ``Born Yesterday.''
   Yet there are no false notes in the singer's portrayal, and at
times she can be quite touching. A film career could be assured if
_ a big if _ she can slip into roles that depart from her music
videos.
   Deborah Blum and Tony Ganz produced ``Vibes,'' which is rated PG
for language and excitement. Running time: 99 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
