<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--BirthDefects Adv11   08-08 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Birth Defects, Adv 11,0592</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 11, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ultrasound Can Serve As Baby's First Checkup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baby should have his first checkup,
some experts believe, about five months before birth.
   ``All women should have careful ultrasound in the fourth month
of pregnancy as though it is the baby's first physical exam,'' said
Dr. Judith G. Hall of the University of British Columbia.
   ``Most people think about prenatal diagnosis as preparatory to
early termination'' of the pregnancy, said Hall. ``But really it's
not. It allows us to begin early treatment.''
   Doctors may recommend abortion if ultrasound finds a severe
defect, but this isn't always the case.
   Ultrasound, in which the echoes of sound waves make pictures of
the fetus inside the womb, often is a routine part of prenatal
care, but Hall believes it can be employed much more effectively to
thoroughly examine a growing fetus.
   ``Some of us in the business of doing high-risk obstetrical
ultrasound can probably pick up most of the major congenital
abnormalities,'' agreed Dr. Beryl R. Benacerraf, a radiologist at
Harvard Medical School.
   About 5 percent of babies have significant congenital
malformations, physical defects present at birth that require
extensive treatment or change a child's life. While the newborn
death rate has fallen dramatically over the years, the liklihood of
serious birth defects has not changed.
   At a recent genetics conference at the Jackson Laboratory here,
Hall contended that at least half of all these birth defects could
be spotted before birth through ultrasound exams.
   Benacerraf has shown that doctors can accurately identify
fetuses with Down's syndrome by looking for thighbones that are
slightly shorter than usual and an extra roll of skin on the back
of the neck.
   Even though many women already have ultrasound during pregnancy,
Hall said it is not ordinarily used to take a careful look at the
unborn child's health. Instead, it is primarly intended to measure
the size of the baby's head and the length of his arms so
physicians can determine how old the fetus is.
   Among other things, she said, ultrasound can be used to check
the severity of osteogenesis imperfecta, a birth defect in which
the child suffers broken bones. The scan can help determine whether
the child would benefit from Caesarean section to avoid fractures
during birth.
   Ultrasound can also help spot fetal heart block, a condition in
which the fetus's heart fails to beat strongly enough. This
condition can be treated before birth by giving the mother
digitalis.
   Benacerraf said she believes all pregnant women should have
ultrasound, but she cautioned that many doctors are not trained to
spot birth defects.
   Physicians who have so-called level one training, she said,
``are just getting a couple of measurements and counting heads,''
while those with more sophisticated skills look for the often
subtle signs of abnormalities.
   Benacerraf said a major study, sponsored by the National
Institutes of Health, is trying to determine whether routinely
doing the more sophisticated ultrasound is worth the expense, which
is between $150 and $300. But even if it turns out to make economic
and medical sense on a large scale, it will not immediately be
available everywhere.
   ``There are not that many people trained in this field,'' she
said. ``If, all of a sudden, we decided to scan everybody who's
pregnant, we couldn't possibly handle the volume.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--BearResearch Adv11   08-08 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Bear Research, Adv 11,0557</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Aug. 11, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pen-Raised Bears Released To Test Survival Skills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mama bear is a crowd-pleaser,
especially with a roly-poly cub romping at her side. But what's a
zoo to do when baby grows up?
   Too often, surplus pen-reared black bears are sold, traded to
dubious buyers or killed, and the mother bred again so zoo visitors
won't be robbed of the baby bear experience, said Michael Pelton, a
wildlife science professor.
   Pelton, of the University of Tennessee, and Doug Scott of the
Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency are tracking radio-collared
bears released from zoo areas into the Cherokee National Forest.
   Pen-raised black bears have been used in research in Tennessee,
but ``this is the first time we've made a concerted effort to keep
track of them,'' Pelton said. ``We want to learn more about how
they react to a new environment after having been born in
captivity...''
   ``The main thrust of the study is to determine simply if these
animals will make it in the wild and if they're suitable for
release,'' Scott said. ``That's the big question. Should we even
take these bears off the hands of zoos, or should we just allow
them to be bought and sold?''
   Six bears, wearing radio collars, have been released, three each
from the Ober Gatlinburg and Grandfather Mountain resort zoos. One
bear grew dependent on area residents for ice cream and other food
handouts. When the zoo that had housed it declined to take it back,
the bear had to be killed. The resort later relented and took back
another bear after similar problems arose, Scott said.
   A third bear was found dead in the forest. Foul play is
suspected and an autopsy is pending. Radio contact has been lost
with a fourth bear.
   Despite the problems, neither Pelton nor Scott is ready to give
up.
   About 20 pen-raised black bears have been released into the wild
in Tennessee over the last 10 to 15 years, but without radio
collars there's no way of knowing their whereabouts, Pelton said.
   In the past, tattoos and ear tags were used on pen-raised bears.
At least three have turned up dead as the result of legal hunts,
which tells researchers they managed to adapt, at least to nature.
   The handling of bears in captivity has a lot to do with their
odds of making it in the wild, Pelton said. Often, they're fed
dried dog food rather than berries and acorns, and are given treats
by zoo visitors. Neither practice boosts their chances of adapting.
   In addition, their cages are sometimes bereft of places to climb
and hide, a more natural environment, and they're allowed too much
contact with humans.
   Several years ago, the state prohibited the caging of Tennessee
black bears in areas other than bona fide zoos or zoological parks.
The law doesn't require special diets or cages to help the bears
survive in the wild if the need arose.
   ``My hope is that the state game people say to the people who
generate these animals, `We need to do a,b,c and d. Otherwise, we
can't work with you,''' Pelton said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0191 </DOCNO>
