<HEAD>Algae Could Lead to Agricultural Economies In Arid Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algae growing in ponds in the Israeli desert
could lead to new products to bring agriculture to arid regions.
   ``We are seeding plants that would never grow in the desert,''
said Duke University botanist Joseph Ramus. ``This project is in
its infancy. What we are developing now will come to fruition in
the year 2000 and later.''
   Ramus and Ben Gurion University researchers are growing algae in
labs and transferring them to ponds in the Valley of Arava in the
Negev. The ponds, fed by fossil water from 3,000-foot wells, each
hold a different type of algae.
   They also are growing Saint Peter fish in the ponds. The fish
produce nitrogen to help the algae grow and bring a good price at
market. ``Aquaculture of Saint Peter fish is becoming a big
industry there. It's a real delicacy for them,'' Ramus said. ``One
fish is enough for a meal. It's like the catfish or crawfish
industry in the Southeast.''
   The algae can be used to produce beta carotene, a source of
Vitamin A; phycolloids, which are food thickeners; and
biliproteins, which can be used in food colorings, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Marsh Grass Research Aimed At Preventing Coastal Erosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN MEADOW, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers in this small town are
watching the grass grow _ and hoping to protect coastal wetlands
from wind, waves and development that erode thousands of acres a
year.
   The grass grown on 11 acres of ponds aren't protected from
disease or weather, they're not fertilized and the only thing out
of the ordinary they get is a daily dose of saltwater, from pumps
that simulate the tide.
   U.S. Soil Conservations Service researchers hope the smooth
cut-grass, giant cut-grass and gulf cord grass will prevent the
coastal erosion that takes some 32,000 acres a year of Louisiana's
3.2 million acres of coastal wetlands.
   A tough, reedy carpet of such marsh grass can form a natural
barrier against tides, waves, wind and the effects of dredging
canals and exploring for oil while the roots hold the soil in
place, said the agency's Jack Cutshall.
   The project began in 1984 on land owned by the Louisiana Land
and Exploration Co., an oil and gas company, and researchers expect
to know within a year what types are promising and within five
years those that are suitable for seed production and aerial
seeding projects.
   ``We've learned an awful lot with these plants,'' Cutshall said.
``There was virtually no information on how gulf cord grass grows,
so we've done some original work there. And we've done some
original work on smooth cut-grass.''
   What remains, he said, ``is to find a plant that has the best of
everything.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Heating Young Chickens Can Make Them Heat-Resistant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chickens die during heat waves because
they can't sweat, but heating chicks seems to make them more
resistant as adults, says a researcher who doesn't have ``the
foggiest idea'' why.
   Chickens exposed to 95 to 100 degree temperatures when they are
5 days old, and again when they are 6 weeks old, seem to have a
survival rate 70 percent to 95 percent better than unheated
chickens, said Michael Denbow, a Virginia Tech associate professor
of poultry science. ``It's kind of neat.''
   Asked how it works, he said, ``We don't have the foggiest idea.''
   Chickens cool off by panting, which evaporates water through
their respiratory systems, said Denbow, who has spent three years
testing the birds. Broilers are usually ready for market at about
six to seven weeks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End of Adv05</HEAD>
