<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeFurnishings:Trends     08-08 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Furnishings: Trends,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: Trends</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY711</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After last year's record growth,
furniture industry analysts projected business would flatten out in
1988.
   So far, their projections are on the mark. But that doesn't mean
the furniture manufacturers, many of them in North Carolina, are
sitting on their hands.
   Faced with the industry's first prolonged no-growth period since
1982, the manufacturers are developing innovative ways to attract
retailers and consumers.
   Some are pushing new furniture lines to catch the eyes of
potential customers. Others are working to improve services. Prices
have been sharpened and new marketing strategies devised.
   ``The people who will be successful will do their homework, come
out with some new lines and sharpen their pricing,'' said High
Point designer Randy Culler.
   Culler, who designs furniture for 10 different companies, feels
it will take good business acumen rather than exotic designs if
manufacturers are to entice consumers to buy as they did in 1987.
   ``I've always said 80 percent of what we do is merchandising and
20 percent (is) design,'' he said in an interview.
   William DiPaolo, vice president of the Southern Furniture Market
Center in High Point, said the business slowdown during the first
few months of this year caused some difficulties for some factories.
   ``Their cash flow has become squeezed,'' he said in an
interview. ``We might start seeing some shorter work weeks.''
   Marty Reddan, an economist for the American Furniture
Manufacturers Association, said shipments and orders from factories
to retailers have been flat this year, when compared with the
record levels of a year ago.
   First quarter shipments, measured by units, were up less than 1
percent over the same period in 1987, he said.
   Jerry Epperson, a furniture industry analyst with Wheat, First
Securities, a Richmond, Va., brokerage house, said the reductions
could lead to shorter work weeks and smaller backlogs in orders.
   ``It's not that business is not clipping along at a good rate,''
he said. ``Retailers are not ordering as far in advance because the
backlogs aren't as large. Business in the popular price points has
been tough most of the year. But it's more complicated than to just
say consumers aren't buying furniture.''
   Epperson said many furniture retailers have been struggling to
comply with the federal tax reforms of 1986. No longer can they pay
their taxes on an installment basis and defer some payments, he
said.
   ``Now they have to pre-pay the government before taking out of
their inventories,'' he said. ``They are less generous in credit
terms and stricter in inventories.
   ``We've seen a year of significant inventory liquidation,''
Epperson said.
   Reddan stressed that 1987 was a record year for shipments and
orders.
   ``You must remember that employment is at an all-time high in
the furniture industry,'' he said. ``Flat is very good _ a lot
better than some people had feared.''
   Until last October's stock market crash, optimism was strong in
North Carolina, the nation's leading producer of household goods.
In 1987, manufacturers shipped nearly $15.8 billion worth of
furniture, a 10 percent increase over 1986. Retail sales last year
advanced 5 percent to $27.2 billion.
   Topping those figures is difficult when the growth in the
national economy has slowed, especially when new home starts,
housing resales and interest rates also reflect a slowdown over
1987.
   ``It will be a flat year at retail, down between 3 to 5 percent
below last year in unit terms,'' Epperson said.
   Prior to last April's Southern Furniture Market in High Point,
some analysts were predicting that manufacturers would bring out
many new product lines to generate business.
   Epperson said that didn't turn out to be the case.
   ``If anything, many factories are cutting back on the number of
items they offer,'' he said. ``When you produce 600 sofas at one
time, the cost is less.''
   Many manufacturers are working to strengthen their relationship
with a smaller number of retailers by providing better services _
such as accelerated delivery, guaranteed delivery or better credit
terms, Epperson said.
   Richard Barentine, executive director of the Furniture
Factories' Marketing Association of the South, said prospects are
picking up for the fall furniture market.
   ``If interest rates remain stable as well as housing starts, and
consumer demand is strong, we'll be OK,'' he said.
   Barentine said many manufacturers have decided to stay with
successful lines rather than try to push new ones. They also follow
consumer preference _ for example, in case goods.
   ``They're willing to pay and in return they demand high
quality,'' Barentine said.
   Judith Cushman, of Furniture Today, a trade publication based in
High Point, said she doesn't anticipate that manufacturers will
respond to sluggish sales by introducing more new lines of
furniture than they usually do at the twice-yearly markets in High
Point.
   ``I don't think we can say across the board there will be a lot
of innovation in order to boost sales,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
