<DOCNO> AP880808-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeFurnishings:WithTrends-Marketing     08-08
0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Furnishings: With Trends-Marketing,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: With Trends-Marketing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One controversial furniture industry
marketing tool has become the focus of a lawsuit filed by 13 North
Carolina retailers against Thomasville Furniture Industries, which
implemented a policy in April restricting catalog and telephone
sales.
   To continue as dealers of Thomasville's high-end products,
Thomasville said, its 51 retailers in North Carolina must install a
gallery. Like other manufacturers, Thomasville started a gallery
program in 1982 in which its furniture is displayed in a room-like
setting.
   ``It's a period of adjustment,'' said Judith Cushman, of
Furniture Today, a trade publication. ``The gallery alignment is a
challenge facing the industry. It creates a strong relationship
between the manufacturer and the retailer.''
   Ms. Cushman said many smaller stores are reluctant to devote
valuable floor space to one manufacture's furniture. The result is
fewer dealers selling the products, she said.
   In Thomasville's case, it was a profitable move. In 1982,
Thomasville reported sales of $130 million through 4,000 retailers.
Last year, the number of dealers stood at 555 _ with sales at $260
million.
   However, the 13 plaintiffs allege that restrictions on telephone
and catalog sales violate antitrust laws. The 13 are among 40 North
Carolina retailers that have signed up for the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
