<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--HomeFurnishings:Bargains     08-08 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Furnishings: Bargains,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>HOME FURNISHINGS: Bargains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Furniture bargains are out there, somewhere, says a prominent
furniture restorer _ ``They're just hiding where you'd least expect
to find them.''
   One way to find them, says Homer Formby, is to run an ad in the
local newspaper announcing, ``I Buy Used Furniture.'' It's better
to say ``used'' furniture rather than ``antique,'' he says, to keep
prices reasonable. Then make appointments with callers and go out
on weekend ``treasure hunts.''
   ``You'd be surprised at the number of people who have $20,000
worth of old furniture stuck in a dusty attic or musty basement,''
says Formby.
   Other places to look: ``Flea markets, junk shops and auctions .
.. real estate sales and garage sales. Often, people have lived
with this furniture all their lives, and they're eager to get rid
of it.
   ``Take your time looking, and be thorough. Look in all the nooks
and crannies _ even behind doors.''
   Formby says furniture doesn't have to be 100 years old to be
worth restoring.
   ``I've come across a lot of 50- and 60-year-old reproductions
worth as much, or more, than some 100-year-old antiques,'' he says.
``So think twice before passing over any piece that's made of solid
wood.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
