<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   08-08 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0502</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal has board ordered a Postal Service
contract with Texas computer billionaire H. Ross Perot voided
because the way in which the contract was awarded violated proper
procedures.
   The contract had been suspended on July 8 after a preliminary
ruling which the Postal Service is challenging in the U.S. Court of
Appeals.
   The board concluded Friday that the Postal Service violated
federal rules by failing to provide any advance notice of the
contract and awarding the contract to Perot without seeking
competitive bids.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Social Security Administration has been
inundated with calls for its new, personalized benefit estimates,
and the agency's chief said she was adding 100 phone lines to
handle the demand.
   Many callers were getting busy signals when they dialed the
toll-free number _ 1-800-937-2000 _ to request copies of the
application form, SSA-7004.
   ``The phones are ringing off the hook, but we're getting
there,'' Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' parent will keep the $500
million it will receive from selling part of Covia, the company
that operates its computerized reservation system.
   Some of the proceeds will be used to buy new planes for the
carrier, which currently has a fleet of 388 aircraft, Rob Doughty,
a spokesman for Chicago-based UAL Corp., said Friday.
   UAL announced May 2 it had sold 50 percent of Covia to five
airlines: Alitalia Airlines, British Airways, KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines, Swissair, and USAir.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community has
criticized the landmark U.S. trade bill and warned the measure may
prompt ``strong reactions'' from America's trading partners.
   Willy De Clercq, the Community's top trade official, said Friday
that the measure contains ``several protectionist elements and ...
increases the possibilities of recourse to unilateral action.''
   He said the bill, expected to be signed shortly by President
Reagan, raises questions about whether the United States is
``really committed to the success'' of international trade
negotiations.
