<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-08 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in late-morning European
trading today, though dealers said its rise had been temporarily
halted by West German central bank intervention.
   The Bundesbank started selling dollars for West German marks
early in the session to stem the U.S. currency's rise and dealers
said the market was not fazed initially. But by late morning, the
intervention had at least temporarily halted the dollar's advance.
   ``It has put the dollar under control,'' said one trader in
Milan.
   The dollar was boosted late Friday by good U.S. employment data
for July, which fueled market speculation that the U.S. Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates soon. Higher interest rates make
the dollar a more attractive investment.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.85 Japanese yen to a closing 133.97.
Later, in London, it was quoted slightly lower at 133.93 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9004 West German marks, up from 1.8890; 1.5887
Swiss francs, up from 1.5757; 6.4085 French francs, up from 6.3675;
2.14575 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1315; 1,400.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,393.00; 1.2078 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2050.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.6915 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6977 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $431.60 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $431.85. Both prices were down from Friday's
late bid of $432.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $431.90, down from $433.00 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $434.00, up a penny
from Saturday's $433.99.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.80 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.89.
</TEXT>
