<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Condoms-Women     08-08 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condoms-Women,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>To Maintain Growth, Condom Companies Targeting Women Buyers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New for PMs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE FALLS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condom market is leveling off
after heavy growth spurred by fear of AIDS, and the nation's two
biggest manufacturers hope to maintain consumer interest by
targeting female buyers, according to industry officials.
   Carter-Wallace Inc. of New York and Schmid Laboratories of
Little Falls plan soon to release products in feminine-style
packaging that they hope will encourage more women to buy the
prophylactics.
   Women account for an estimated 40 percent of condom purchases,
industry experts say. Schmid Laboratories, the nation's
second-biggest condom seller with 35 percent of the market, wants
to shore up declining sales by appealing to them.
   Last month, the company laid off 150 temporary workers at its
Anderson, S.C., manufacturing plant because of a drop in demand.
   One reason for the slower sales was the higher prices condom
manufacturers recently began paying for Malaysian latex used to
make most of the products. Officials also say new regulations by
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration have trimmed profit margins
by mandating a tenfold increase in condom testing.
   Schmid president Don Falk said sales remain strong, but are not
near the lofty numbers that followed Surgeon General C. Everett
Koop's advice last year to use condoms to avoid transmitting
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``People realized the initial impact was not going to continue
forever,'' Falk said of the sales surge. ``But we are at a higher
production level now than pre-AIDS.''
   Diana Temple, a Salomon Brothers Inc. analyst who follows
Carter-Wallace, says women can be important to the market if more
begin relying on condoms for contraception, as recent studies show
they are.
   ``I think (sales) are moderating,'' Ms. Temple said. ``People
appear to be buying them. The key is if they are using them.''
   Condom company officials would not estimate the dollar amount of
their sales but said the industry estimates it will sell about $404
million worth of condoms in the United States this year, which Ms.
Temple said would represent a 20 percent rise in sales.
   To maintain consumer interest, Carter-Wallace, which controls
half of the market, soon will be marketing Trojans for Women,
spokeswoman Liz Stecher said.
   Schmid soon will introduce Ramses for Her and She's Sheik
condoms, variations on two of the company's top-selling lines.
Among the added feminine touches in the new products are a carrying
case for each condom and disposable envelopes.
   ``The emphasis now is on educating young people to use condoms
if they are sexually active and non-monogomous. We think young
women are more likely to respond to this than young men,'' Falk
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
