<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0755EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RFD-TV     08-08 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RFD-TV,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RFD-TV Hopes For Good Harvest of Viewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock 'n' rollers have MTV, sports fans have
ESPN and investors have the Financial News Network. Now, there's
RFD-TV for farmers _ an idea its developers hope will reap a
bountiful harvest of profits.
   ``We're a whole new concept and we're delivering stories that no
one else is delivering,'' said Patrick Gottsch, chairman and chief
executive officer of the satellite network scheduled to go on the
air Aug. 15.
   ``It seems like there's always something going on with
agriculture,'' he said. ``But one problem is farmers are not
getting accurate or timely information on a daily basis or even an
hourly basis.''
   RFD-TV hopes to change that with 24-hour, seven-day a week
programming available to households with a satellite dish, Gottsch
said in a recent interview, as workers scrambled to build sets and
uncrate equipment in time for the network premiere.
   He said plans call for RFD-TV, named after the U.S. Postal
Service's old acronym for rural free delivery, to grow like the
crops that will be its subject matter, expanding to cable and
low-power television systems.
   Gottsch, who was raised on a farm near Elkhorn and later worked
as a commodity broker and satellite dish dealer, said he came up
with the idea for RFD-TV about three years ago.
   There are 2.8 million home satellite dishes in the United States
and 250,000 in Canada. About 60 percent are in rural areas, Gottsch
said.
   ``It's just a common sense project,'' he said. ``If you take a
drive in the country you see a lot of dishes and they're going to
be watching us.''
   The programming won't be reruns of ``Hee-Haw,'' ``The Real
McCoys'' or ``Mayberry R.F.D.,'' Gottsch said.
   He described the network as a cross between the Financial News
Network, ESPN and the Cable News Network, but geared toward rural
America.
   Universities in all 50 states will produce shows for RFD-TV and
a live prime-time interview show in which viewers may phone in
questions is planned.
   RFD-TV also will have its own barnyard take-off on home shopping
_ video livestock auctions to give farmers a chance to expand their
herds without leaving their living rooms, Gottsch said.
   ``We're very confident people are going to like what they see on
our air _ we're not doing things half-cocked,'' Gottsch said.
``They're going to see a very shiny farm network that they're going
to want to watch.''
   The fledgling Omaha-based network has a 21-member news staff,
with bureaus in Chicago, Washington, Kansas City, Mo., and Fresno,
Calif., Gottsch said.
   The staff will produce seven hours of live news, weather and
markets coverage every week day, and several half-hour summaries
daily.
   ``Currently, agricultural programming is scattered throughout
the television system,'' Gottsch said. ``There is hit-and-miss
coverage on local stations and some largely irrelevant feature
material on the major networks.''
   Advertisers and home satellite dish dealers are excited about
the network.
   ``There is a definite `What do we have to lose?' attitude among
major advertisers,'' Gottsch said. ``Because of satellite
communications, our ad rates are lower than a local TV station.''
   Agricultural advertisers also have been supportive because
``there's a need for a rifle shot approach to the farmer instead of
the shotgun approach,'' he said.
   Because RFD-TV is a free, unscrambled service, the network could
spur lagging satellite dish sales, Gottsch said.
   ``We're the first free and clear channel on satellite in the
last two years. We're good news for the home satellite dealer. We
are definitely a reason for someone to buy home dish,'' he said.
   Despite high start-up costs of more than $3 million, Gottsch
predicted the channel will turn a profit in its first year.
   ``We have built-in shows with built-in audiences with built-in
advertisers,'' said Gottsch, who is among the network's investors.
   ``We only have to sell 13 percent of our available ad time to
turn a profit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AdvertisingMail     08-08 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Advertising Mail,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Not `Junk Mail' to Everyone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may be ``junk mail'' to some people, but
more than one American in four would like to receive more
advertising mail, according to a survey done by the Postal Service.
   Thirty-one percent of the people surveyed said they found the
information in mailed advertising useful, and 27 percent said they
would like to receive more, reports John R. Wargo, assistant
postmaster general for marketing.
   In contrast, 15 percent said they wish they received less
advertising in the mail.
   Third-class has been the fastest-growing category of mail in
recent years, raising the U.S. Postal Service to the status of the
nation's third largest advertising medium, trailing only newspapers
and television, said Wargo.
   ``The reason that we're in business is because of the receivers,
and we need to find out what they want and we need to tell the
senders,'' Wargo said of the survey covering 5,300 homes across the
nation.
   The study, done last year, was disclosed to business mailers at
a meeting in Los Angeles and later discussed by Wargo in an
interview.
   He said the study found that the Postal Service handles 17
percent of advertising, compared to 27 percent for newspapers and
22 percent for television.
   ``We believe that we've got a better opportunity to grow if our
receivers are satisfied, they react favorably, and they read it.
What were trying to do is help the sender improve their ability to
get a favorable reaction and more business. And that's going to
keep us in business. It's a straight business proposition.''
   Third-class advertising mail increased 173 percent between 1972
and 1987, while other categories increased by only 44 percent.
   For the average household, third class mail went from three
items a week in 1972 to 8.7 last year. Over the same period the
volume of first-class mail per household went up from 7.4 to 8.6
items a week, while newspapers and magazines dropped from 2.3 to
1.6, according to Wargo's study.
   But while Americans are getting more advertising mail, do they
read it?
   As volume increased, readership has declined, Wargo found.
   Last year 51 percent of third-class mail was read, according to
the study, down from 83 percent in 1972.
   The higher the household income, the more advertising mail
received, but the less that was read, the study found. And yet the
higher income households were more likely to order something, and
ordered more often via mail.
   The most important factor in getting someone to open the ad,
read it and perhaps buy something, Wargo found, was familiarity
with the advertiser.
   ``The highest open-and-read rate is a result of the person
knowing who the company is and having done business with them,''
said Wargo.
   The increase in mail advertising places conflicting demands on
the Postal Service, he said, including a need to see that those
receiving the mail are not offended or bothered by it.
   ``I think there are going to be some senders who say, `Your job
is only to take what we give you.' I don't think we're going to
accept that. On the other hand the receivers are going to say, `You
should screen everything' and I don't think were going to do
that,'' Wargo said.
   ``We're very, very concerned that if this audience does not
continue to have a high level of satisfaction we won't have
anything to sell to'' other advertisers, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Twilight-MovieSafety     08-08 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Twilight-Movie Safety,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmaking More Dangerous Now, Says Stunt Accident Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer seeking legislation to promote
safety on movie sets says filmmaking is more dangerous now than
when three people were killed on the set of ``Twilight Zone: The
Movie.''
   With pressure for bigger and more spectacular special effects in
movies, attorney Jerry Kroll says stuntmen and women are risking
injury and death daily.
   ``First they were jumping out of cars. Then it was jumping off
buildings, then out of airplanes. Next it will be the Concorde,''
said Kroll.
   ``I think Hollywood is more dangerous today than ever.''
   Kroll, who is handling six lawsuits resulting from movie and TV
set accidents, says the situation is unlikely to change without
legislation.
   ``The `Twilight Zone' focused public attention on safety,''
Kroll said of the 1987 trial that ended with the acquittal of
director John Landis and four co-defendants on involuntary
manslaughter charges.
   ``But the public got to watch John Landis being acquitted, and
the question is was that an acquittal of the industry? I say he was
on trial and not the industry.
   ``If we learned anything from `Twilight Zone,' it's that the
criminal justice system isn't going to make the industry safer,''
said Kroll. ``We have to do it some other way.''
   He is pushing for passage of a bill that would require licensing
of stunt coordinators and special effects coordinators and would
forbid moviemakers to use film footage of any stunt that resulted
in injury or death.
   One of Kroll's clients, stuntman Max Maxwell, was injured in a
special effects explosion during filming of a 1985 action movie.
   ``The film contains footage of my client getting blown up,''
said Kroll. ``It's just not right.''
   ``If filmmakers know they can't use that kind of footage,'' said
Kroll, ``they will have a financial motivation to make sure the
scene is safe when they shoot it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880808-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0811EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TwilightZoneRevisited     08-08 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Twilight Zone Revisited,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lingering Turmoil Surrounds Movie Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six years after Hollywood's deadliest movie
accident and a year after a celebrated trial, the ``Twilight Zone''
remains a nagging dilemma for the movie industry.
   Scrutiny of the helicopter crash that killed veteran actor Vic
Morrow and two child actors has resumed with the publication of a
book about the trial of the director, John Landis, and four
co-defendants. Another book on the subject is due next month.
   Participants still debate details of the crash that occurred
July 23, 1982, during filming of a Vietnam War scene for ``Twilight
Zone: The Movie.'' The helicopter crashed during special effects
explosions, also killing 6-year-old Renee Chen and Myca Dinh Le, 7.
   Attorney James Neal, who successfully defended Landis against
manslaughter charges in Los Angeles County Superior Court, says the
case should be ``over and done with.''
   ``The reason it won't go away,'' says attorney Harland Braun,
``is because the system never assessed moral responsibility and no
one accepted moral responsibility.
   ``Landis has never said, `I did the wrong thing,''' said Braun,
who represented associate producer George Folsey Jr. at the trial.
   Despite a jury's acquittal of Landis, Folsey and the
co-defendants of involuntary manslaughter, Braun and two other
defense attorneys _ Arnold Klein, representing special effects
coordinator Paul Stewart, and Eugene Trope, representing pilot
Dorcey Wingo _ believe an acknowledgment of responsibility was
called for.
   ``I don't think much of Landis,'' said Klein. ``He had a
cowardly defense where he blamed everyone else. He never came out
and said he was deeply sorry for that which he was responsible
for.''
   Author Ronald Labrecque, whose book ``Special Effects'' is due
next month, said Landis fuels controversy with his own actions. For
example:
   _In early summer, Landis gave a dinner party at a trendy Beverly
Hills restaurant on the first anniversary of his acquittal.
Attorney Leonard Levine, a guest, said it was a ``nice'' gesture by
Landis to thank those who stood by him.
   _In June, Landis invited the trial jurors to a private screening
of ``Coming to America,'' the Eddie Murphy film he directed. The
jurors accepted, and Landis' action drew more criticism.
   In their newly published book, ``Outrageous Conduct: Art, Ego
and the Twilight Zone Case,'' authors Stephen Farber and Marc Green
sharply criticize Landis, the prosecutor who lost the case and the
movie industry that failed to penalize Landis for the deaths.
   ``There are elements of Hollywood that are morally bankrupt,''
said Green. ``They believe only in the bottom line, and as long as
John Landis' name is above the title of a movie that is the highest
grossing non-sequel in history (``Coming to America''), John Landis
will be welcome in those quarters.''
   ``No one asks questions,'' said Farber.
   Landis refused to be comment on the matter. His Los Angeles
lawyer, Joel Behr, said the director was in Europe and would not
comment even if he were here.
   Neal said Landis acknowledged his role in the accident when he
testified at the trial and should be allowed to ``get on with his
life.''
   ``They did wrong, and certainly it can be argued they were
guilty of violating child labor laws. But it should be over and it
should be done with,'' he said.
   Neal, his associate, James Sanders, and Levine, who represented
production manager Dan Allingham in the manslaughter trial, have
cameo roles in ``Coming To America.''
   Another key player in the ``Twilight Zone'' drama continues to
make news.
   Lea Purwin D'Agostino, the deputy district attorney who spent 10
months prosecuting the case, ran for District Attorney against her
boss, Ira Reiner, in June. She lost and has been transferred to a
lesser job. She calls the reassignment retaliation.
   ``No one is letting me forget it,'' she said. ``Probably,
because it's Hollywood. But there's also the enormity of the
horror, the absolutely needless loss of life for a lousy movie.''
   But Chief Deputy District Attorney Gilbert Garcetti denied the
reassigment was vindictive. He said plans to move Mrs. D'Agostino
to the other job were made several months ago and were not related
to the ``Twilight Zone'' verdict.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
