<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 0815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MinutesWar     08-08 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minutes War,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tree Farmer Chronicles Town Meeting Minutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANCOCK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From his farm in the Berkshire Hills,
Frank Patterson wages war on small-town autocrats, wresting from
them the minutes of meetings that even he admits can make pretty
boring reading in his Bulletin.
   So boring, in fact, that Patterson recently cut back publication
of his newsletter from twice monthly to once a month. ``I got an
inkling that too much was too much,'' he said.
   But the tree farmer has vowed to keep publishing the recorded
gatherings of selectmen, assessors, school and health boards for
his 250 readers as long as the money holds out.
   ``We've been operating in the red and I guess we will always
be,'' he said.
   The not-for-profit newsletter celebrates its first anniversary
next month. It has grown to six editions, one for each of the six
towns that hand over their minutes, and contains as many minutes as
Patterson can get. They include such mundane revelations as this,
from the May 5 meeting of the Hancock board of selectmen:
   ``Mr. Bowman appeared before the board with 104 lbs. of rocks,
stating that they had been picked up on 1,000 ft. of road frontage
on his property.''
   And this, from the May 8 meeting of the Hancock health board:
   ``Ruth Bush came to request rent for the landfill. She says she
was not paid for 1987. We will check.''
   About 100 copies are sent free to libraries, post offices and
other town offices, but Patterson has managed to talk the rest of
the subscribers into donations ranging from $5 to $100. Without
such gifts, he said, the paper would not survive.
   He applies the same persuasive logic to advertisers. Recalling a
restaurant that recently pulled a $50 ad the size of a business
card, Patterson said: ``I couldn't convince them that this is a
civic thing. No one is going to come to their restaurant to eat
because of that ad. It costs $100 to eat there anyway.''
   Patterson said he founded the newsletter to keep busy in his
retirement. He is a former purchasing agent for an electric company
who now runs a Christmas tree farm with his wife, Eleanor, 72, who
heads the board of selectmen in their town.
   ``I'm 71 and at my age, if you don't take up something new, your
mind begins to fall into pieces,'' he said.
   The newsletter proudly lists among its supporters two
newspapers, a retired publisher and Pulitzer Prize-winning
historian James MacGregor Burns, who called Patterson ``a local
friend doing what I think are good things.''
   But some apparently disagree.
   Patterson said officials in a few towns balked at releasing
their minutes and complied only after the state attorney general's
office told them they were obligated to make the minutes public.
   In at least one case, Patterson said, his request prompted town
officials to take minutes of their meetings for the first time.
   He said he is still trying to get minutes from New Ashford and
Richmond but is loathe to ask the state for help again.
   ``I'm afraid to stir them up,'' he said of the town officials.
``Then they'll never give them to me.''
   The head of the board of selectmen in New Ashford, one of the
state's smallest towns, with a population of 150 people, said he
has refused to mail the minutes to Patterson's home because of the
expense.
   ``The records are there. All he's got to do is come and get
them,'' said head selectman John H. Haig.
   Marguerite Rawson, head of the Richmond board, said she hasn't
sent minutes to Patterson because she has no time to edit them for
publication by the time they are typed up, usually several weeks
after the meeting.
   ``If he wants, he can sit down at our meetings and take notes,''
she said. ``But I don't have time to play around with his
newsletter. ... It's a sticky situation. I'm not trying to keep
anything from him, but I'm a busy woman. I work days and do this
(board business) at night.''
   Patterson said he's lost $2,500 so far on the newsletter, but he
plans to get it up to 20 editions before calling it quits.
   ``If I can do it here, by George, I can do it anywhere,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
