<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Tour,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tour Company Walks Customers Through City's Murder Sites</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note content</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though murder is not one of New York's selling
points, people are paying for the privilege of reliving some of the
city's macabre moments.
   A tour company with the innocuous name of Sidewalks of New York
is offering walking tours of murder sites to curiosity seekers who
want to know where some of the city's better-known victims took
their last breath, according to a report in today's editions of the
New York Post.
   ``I love a good murder,'' publicity agent Marnie Goodman said
while on her tour last Saturday.
   The sites in the $10 two-hour tour include the Omni Park Hotel
on 56th Street and Seventh Avenue, formerly the Park Sheraton,
where organized crime figure Albert Anastasia was riddled with
bullets while getting a shave in a barber shop in 1957. Also
featured are the tree in Central Park under which the body of
Jennifer Levin was found two years ago and the Dakota building on
72nd Street and Central Park West, where Beatle John Lennon was
murdered.
   A real estate broker who happened to be walking by the tour
group with a prospective client for an apartment on West 72nd
Street last week was no doubt less than pleased to hear the guide
refer to a seventh-floor studio as the place where the ``Looking
for Mr. Goodbar'' victim was strangled.
</TEXT>
