<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chubb-Farmers     08-08 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chubb-Farmers,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chubb Offers Farmers Double-Premium Refund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 3,300 of the 8,717 applicants for
insurance by the Chubb Group of Insurance Companies in Ohio and
nine other Midwestern states have accepted the company's offer to
refund double their premiums.
   Chubb made the offer last month after agents sold $400 million
in drought insurance coverage to farmers. The underwriter had
authorized only $30 million worth of the coverage to be sold. Chubb
contends that a flood of applications in the last days the
insurance was available caused it to be oversold.
   The company operated a 125-person telephone bank during the
weekend to call 3,500 other applicants, even though the deadline
for the double-premium refund expired Friday.
   Chubb said Friday that 852 farmers had accepted the drought
insurance policies originally offered and 106 farmers who were
offered policies decided instead to take the double-premium offer.
Another 359 farmers were ruled ineligible for the insurance because
their applications were too late.
   Chubb offered up to $40 million of insurance nationwide in July
to the applicants on a first-come, first-served basis. Other
farmers who met the deadline were offered double their premiums
back.
   Ohio regulators investigating the drought insurance issue will
subpoena more people next week to explain how the insurance was
marketed.
   ``More questions have been triggered by some of the testimony
we've heard'' during the first week of public meetings, said George
Fabe, director of the Ohio Department of Insurance.
   The department next week will try to sort out which questions
remain and who should be called in to answer them, Fabe said.
Public meetings will probably resume the following week.
   The drought insurance was structured to pay farmers for the lack
of rain between June 1 and Aug. 31, based on a sliding scale. About
600 Ohio farmers applied for the insurance.
</TEXT>
