<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-InterestRates     08-08 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Interest Rates,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commercial Banks Raise Interest Rates to 11 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's leading commercial banks, heeding a
signal from the Bank of England, announced on Monday a half-point
increase in their base lending rate to 11 percent.
   The central bank, seeking to control inflation, has signaled
seven half-point increases in the benchmark lending rate since
early June, when the rate stood at 7.5 percent. The last increase
was announced on July 18.
   Britain's annual inflation rate stood at 4.6 percent in June.
   A spokesman for the central bank, who wasn't identified in
accordance with British practice, said the latest increase was made
to ``assert the counter-inflation strategy.''
   The Treasury said it was the government's view that the economy
was growing ``at an unsustainable rate and needed to be slowed down
a bit.''
   The Bank of England signaled the rate rise at about midday by
announcing that it was raising its own money market rates.
   Barclays Bank PLC, Midland Bank PLC, Lloyds Bank PLC and
National Westminster Bank PLC quickly raised their base rate.
   Corporate borrowers can obtain loans at one percentage point
above the commercial banks' base lending rate.
   The pound rose after the announcement, which dealers said took
the market by surprise. The pound was selling for $1.6960 after the
bank's signal, up from $1.6915 in late-morning trading.
</TEXT>
