<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-Bonds     08-08 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Bonds ,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China to Open Nationwide Bond Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China will open a nationwide bond market at the
end of this year to curb black market trading in sought-after
government bonds, the Finance Ministry said.
   A ministry spokesman said the decision to open the market for
Treasury bonds came after experiments with bond markets in 61
Chinese cities in the first half of the year, the official People's
Daily reported Monday.
   A main purpose of the new market will be to stop
``bond-speculating lords'' who purchase non-matured bonds at low
values and resell them at higher prices, the newspaper said.
   Bonds have become popular among the Chinese because they offer
higher interest rates than regular savings accounts. Bonds issued
in 1985 earn an annual interest rate of 9 percent redeemable after
five years, while 1986 and 1987 bonds pay 10 percent interest.
   China issued 36.2 billion yuan, or about $9.8 billion, worth of
government bonds from 1981 to 1987 to help finance its economic
development programs.
   The government also has permitted some state and collective
enterprises to raise funds by issuing bonds and stocks, and small
stock exchanges are operating in Shanghai, Beijing and some other
cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
