<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun-Times Publisher,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Sun-Times Names New Acting Publisher To Replace Page</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to correct category code</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles T. Price, senior vice president and
general manager of the Chicago Sun-Times, has been named acting
publisher of the newspaper until a replacement is found for Robert
E. Page.
   Price's interim appointment was announced Saturday by Sun-Times
Chairman Leonard P. Shaykin. Shaykin is a managing partner of Adler
& Shaykin, the investment firm that spearheaded a $145 million
leveraged buyout of the newspaper from international media magnate
Rupert Murdoch in 1986.
   Page announced on Thursday that he was selling his minority
interest in the newspaper company to the investor group that owns
it and stepping down as the Sun-Times' president and publisher.
   Shaykin said Price would serve as acting publisher while the
search for a new publisher continues.
   Price, 44, formerly was a partner in the Cleveland law firm of
Baker & Hostetler, where he represented the Sun-Times and other
newspapers.
   The 52-year-old Page decided to leave the newspaper about a
month ago and the deal to buy out his stake _ believed to be around
10 percent _ was consummated Thursday for as much as $2.5 million,
the Tribune said.
   Page came to Chicago from Murdoch's Boston Herald to serve as
the Sun-Times' president and publisher in 1984 after the
Australian's News America Publishing Corp. bought the paper from
its long-time owners, the Field family of Chicago.
   When Murdoch sold the Sun-Times to the investors' group, Page
said he was embarrassed by some of the newspaper's sensationalism
under Murdoch and promised ``a more serious, more purposeful'' look.
</TEXT>
