<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Royalties     08-08 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Royalties,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Companies Paid $321 Million in Technology Royalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean companies paid $321
million in royalties for high-technology imports from the United
States and other countries during the first half of the year,
government figures show.
   Statistics published Monday by the Ministry of Finance showed
that the royalty payment for the first half was up from $226
million in the same period in 1987.
   Officials attributed the sharp increase to South Korea's growing
demand for high technology for electric, electronic and chemical
products and machinery.
   Royalties for electric and electronic technology more than
doubled, to $134 million from $66 million a year earlier, according
to the statistics.
   Royalty payments for machinery during the six-month period rose
19.6 percent, to $61 million. Royalties for oil refining and
chemicals doubled, to $54 million.
   The United States was the largest supplier of technology to
South Korea during the period with $161 million, followed by Japan
with $112 million, West Germany with $10 million and France with $8
million.
</TEXT>
