<2ND_LINE>BC-Cocoa Futures,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malaysian Exchange Launches Cocoa Futures to Coincide With 8888</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kuala Lumpur Commodity
Exchange launched trading in cocoa futures Monday to coincide with
the date 8-8-88 which many Chinese and others in Malaysia believe
brings great prosperity.
   Eight in the Cantonese Chinese dialect is pronounced phat, which
means prosperity, and 8888 means prosperity multiplies.
   Cocoa is the fourth commodity to be traded on the 8-year-old
exchange, along with tin, palm oil and rubber. The Kuala Lumpur
exchange is the first futures market for cocoa in Asia.
   Malaysia is the world's third-largest producer of cocoa after
the Ivory Coast and Brazil.
   Trading in cocoa futures was officially launched by Malaysian
Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng Yaik with a stroke at the
``bedok,'' a traditional village drum of the coastal Bajau
community. Trading was described as brisk.
   The cocoa contract for delivery in September opened at $1,280 a
ton.
</TEXT>
