<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Sharply Lower On Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to
heavier-than-expected weekend showers on the northern and western
edges of the Corn Belt.
   The thunderstorms were expected to roll into the central Midwest
today, bringing badly-needed moisture and cooler temperatures to
drought-stressed corn and soybean fields.
   ``The weather over the weekend and the next couple of days looks
to be much better than expected,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Prices for future delivery of corn and soybeans flirted with
their respective daily limits of 10 cents and 30 cents a bushel in
early trading. Rain would improve the condition and yield prospects
of those crops, especially with most soybean fields in their
critical pod-filling stage.
   Traders are anxiously awaiting Thursday's crop progress report
from the Agriculture Department, which is expected to reveal a
worsening of crop conditions during July.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.74 a bushel; corn was 6{
cents to 10 cents lower with September at $2.99 a bushel; soybeans
were 21 cents to 31{ cents lower with the limitless August contract
at $8.45 a bushel; oats were 4{ cents to 9 cents lower with
September at $2.78{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .47 cent lower to .23 cent higher with August
at 68.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .20
cent higher with August at 79.55 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent
lower to .18 cent higher with August at 45.85 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .13 cent to .85 cent higher with August at 32.80
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
