<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBS-TVStation     08-08 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS-TV Station,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Agrees To Buy Miami TV Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cash-rich CBS Inc., announcing its first
television station purchase since Laurence A. Tisch took over as
president nearly two years ago, said today it has agreed to buy
WCIX-TV in Miami for $59 million.
   CBS said it also agreed to assume certain program obligations
valued at about $13 million as part of the deal for the station,
which operates on Channel 6 in Miami and is owned by TVX Broadcast
Group Inc. of Norfolk, Va.
   Completion of the deal is subject to regulatory approval.
   WCIX is an independent station, and its acquisition would
increase the number of TV stations that CBS owns and operates to
five, reaching about 20.8 percent of the country. CBS also operates
the CBS television network.
   CBS has faced criticism from its affiliates for failing to
expand its station holdings, particularly in light of the $3
billion in cash that the company has built up as it sold
non-broadcast assets, such as its records and magazines divisions,
over the past two years.
   The companies that own the other two major networks each own
more stations. ABC's parent owns eight stations and NBC's parent
owns seven.
   Tisch has responded by saying that while he wanted to make a
station purchase, the prices being asked were too high.
   CBS currently owns stations in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles
and Philadelphia that reach about 19.4 percent of the country's
viewers.
   Federal regulations limit a network to owning no more than 12
stations reaching a maximum 25 percent of the country.
   CBS already has an affiliate in Miami, but the station, WTVJ,
was acquired by NBC last year for about $270 million. That station
has continued to carry CBS programs, however, under an affiliation
agreement that ends in January.
   Miami is the nation's 16th largest television market. ``The
exciting and fast-growing Maimi market offers a terrific expansion
opportunity for us,'' said Eric Ober, president of the CBS-owned
television station division.
   Tisch was quoted in a statement as saying the purchase
``reflects the commitment of the board and senior management to
make sound investments in good broadcast properties in attractive
local markets.''
   ``We are continuing to evaluate other potential properties with
an eye toward further acquisitions,'' he said.
   Ths acquisition would be the second major purchase by Tisch in
the past four months. CBS bought the broadcast rights for 1992
winter Olympics for $243 million in May.
</TEXT>
