<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stWritethru   08-08 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Writethru,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Little Changed After Interest Rate Hike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices were little changed on London's Stock
Exchange Monday after the market stumbled on news of an unexpected
hike in British interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index settled up
0.1 point, or 0.01 percent, at 1,876.0.
   Trading volume was a light 369.2 million shares, sharply lower
than Friday's volume of 416.4 million shares.
   Most of Monday's trading volume came within the first three
hours of business.
   Prices rose to their best levels in early trading on the back of
buying by institutional investors and on widespread positive
sentiment, reinforced by favorable weekend press comment about
London equities.
   But a signal by the Bank of England for a rise in bank base
lending rates to 11 percent from 10.5 percent pulled prices sharply
lower after midday.
   Market watchers said the rate rise caught them completely off
guard.
   ``It was a bolt of lightning from out of the blue,'' one analyst
said.
   Grand Metropolitan PLC, a British liquor and restaurants group,
was the largest gainer on the day, jumping 26 pence, or 44 cents,
to 522 pence a share after the company said it was considering
selling its Inter-Continental Hotels unit.
</TEXT>
