<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     08-08 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains Except Against Pound, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against all the major
currencies except the British pound in European trading Monday.
Gold prices were mixed.
   The pound rose after British commercial banks raised their base
lending rate by half a percentage point to 11 percent, the second
increase in less than a month.
   Traders said the dollar gained after the news late last Friday
of a higher-than-expected rise in the number of Americans at work.
That would pump more money into the American economy and started
speculation that U.S. interest rates will be raised soon to control
inflation.
   The West German central bank and the U.S. Federal Reserve made
concerted sales of dollars Monday to stem the dollar's rise and
pulled the dollar back from its highest levels of the day, dealers
said.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7022 late Monday, more
expensive for buyers than Friday's late $1.6977.
   Other late rates Monday, compared with Friday's late rates,
included: 1.9000 West German marks, up from 1.8890; 1.5857 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5757; 6.3950 French francs, up from 6.3675;
2.1435 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1315; 1,399.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,393.00; 1.2097 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2050.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar exchanged at 133.97 Japanese yen at
the close, up from 133.12 yen. In London later the dollar traded at
133.60 yen.
   Gold bullion prices were higher in London, the major market, and
lower in Zurich. Swiss traders said trading was dull and low in
volume.
   Gold closed in London at a bid $432.25 a troy ounce, up from
$432.10 late Friday, and in Zurich at $432 bid, down from $433.
   Gold in Hong Kong closed at $434 bid, up from Saturday's $433.99.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.78 a troy
ounce, down from $6.89.
</TEXT>
