<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AmericanBrands-Suit     08-08 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Brands-Suit,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bondholders File Suit Against American Brands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 19 institutional investors filed suit
Monday charging that American Brands Inc. violated securities laws
by misstating facts when it offered to buy $1.5 billion in debt as
part of its acquisition of E-II Holdings Inc.
   The complaint, filed against both companies in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, seeks $350 million in damages.
   Holders of E-II's long-term debt passed up an opportunity to
sell out in late February. American Brands offered to buy two
issues of debt at 103 percent and 104 percent of face value plus
accrued interest, but the offer expired without the company
receiving anywhere near the 51 percent response needed to trigger
the purchases.
   The bonds currently are trading below the price offered by
American Brands.
   The bondholders, led by Prudential Insurance Co., Columbia
Savings and Loan Association and Forstmann-Leff Associates, claim
they based their decision not to sell on American Brands' assertion
that it would retain E-II as a wholly owned subsidiary.
   The plaintiffs, who hold about $600 million of E-II's $1.5
billion in outstanding debt, had expected American Brands to sell
only a ``few segments of E-II's businesses that did not fit into
the core business strategy.''
   Four months later, however, American Brands announced it would
sell most of E-II _ including its debt _ to Riklis Family Corp.
American Brands paid Riklis to retain five E-II businesses.
   E-II's outstanding debt is now the obligation of Riklis.
   In their lawsuit, the bondholders allege American Brands
``pursued a secret strategy completely inconsistent with the
statements made in the tender offer document'' when it was
acquiring E-II shares in February for $17.05 a share, or about $2.7
billion including debt.
   American Brands spokesman Daniel Conforti said the company had
been advised that ``the suits are without merit.'' He said American
Brands ``made it clear at the outset that we would not assume the
indebtedness.''
   American Brands disclaimed any legal responsibility for the
bonds before the merger with E-II was completed, saying the debt
would remain E-II's responsibility once it became a subsidiary.
   The suit seeks compensatory and punitive damages. The two bond
issues in question come due in March 1997 and March 1999. Interest
payments on the debt total about $194 million, according to
published estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
