<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-08 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Plunge Their Limits On Rain Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn, oat and soybean futures plunged their
permitted daily limits on the Chicago Board of Trade Monday in
reaction to unexpectedly heavy showers sweeping slowly across the
Corn Belt.
   Wheat futures also closed lower.
   A storm system that brought up to an inch of rain to much of
Minnesota, Wisconsin and northern Iowa on Sunday was expected to
pour water Monday night and Tuesday on drought-stressed crops in
the central Midwest.
   ``There's rain around and there's more rain coming,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for the investment firm Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. ``That's what broke the back of the bulls today.''
   Cooler temperatures were expected in the storm system's wake.
The crops were badly in need of both moisture and cooler
conditions, especially the soybean crop, which is in the middle of
its most vulnerable growth phase.
   Lespinasse called the sell-off ``very gradual, very orderly.''
   Prices opened sharply below Friday's closing levels, then
gradually fell their limits _ 10 cents a bushel for corn and oats,
and 30 cents a bushel for all soybean contracts except the August
contract, on which limits has been removed pending its expiration
on Aug. 22.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.76 a bushel; corn was 6{
cents to 10 cents lower with September at $2.96} a bushel; oats
were 8{ cents to 10 cents lower with September at $2.73{ a bushel;
soybeans were 15 cents to 34{ cents lower with August at $8.42 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
