<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   08-08 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0504</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted its third straight loss
Monday, still mired in uncertainty about the outlook for inflation
and interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 14.94 points last
Thursday and Friday, fell another 11.73 to 2,107.40.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
585 up, 781 down and 578 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 148.80 million
shares, up from 113.40 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 168.99 million shares.
   Analysts said traders remained concerned about a possible
increase in inflationary pressures and rising interest rates.
   News on Friday of continuing expansion in payroll employment
during July prompted increased talk that the Federal Reserve might
tighten credit further.
   ``The Fed is being restrained and cautious in its moves toward
firmness, but the economic data continue to argue that a still
firmer stance is likely in the near future,'' said analysts William
Griggs and Leonard Santow at Griggs & Santow Inc. in their
financial commentary for this week.
   But brokers also said recent evidence of a strong economy
suggested that the large increases in corporate earnings posted in
the second quarter might continue at least for the balance of 1988.
   Losers among the blue chips included American Express, down ~ at
28; International Business Machines, down } at 123[; Ford Motor,
down } at 53; General Electric, down \ at 41{, and Philip Morris,
down | at 91}.
   Interco climbed 4\ to 72\. City Capital Associates raised its
offer for the company from $64 a share to $70 a share.
   Federal National Mortgage rose | to 49{ on large volume, trading
at record highs. The stock of the company, commonly known as Fannie
Mae, got as high as 48] before the crash last fall, then fell into
the upper 20s when the market collapsed.
   More recently Fannie Mae, which buys, sells and guarantees
mortgages, has regained favor among a good many investors with the
help of sharp earnings gains.
   Chrysler, discussed in a Wall Street Journal column as a ``value
play'' in the eyes of some analysts, edged up [ to 23{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $8.95 billion, or 0.33
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slumped .57 to 152.52.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 1.28 to 310.93, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 1.17 at 269.98.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped .05 to 387.66. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 304.23, down .72.
</TEXT>
