<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Philips-Conoco 1stLd-Writethru f0120 08-08 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philips-Conoco, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0120,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phillips Joins Companies Selling Reserves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 4th grafs pvs, Since 1985 ... to fix state for Tioga
to North Dakota sted Montana. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Conoco, a
subsidiary ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phillips Petroleum Co. will sell its
oil and gas holdings in the Williston Basin of Montana and North
Dakota to Conoco for an undisclosed sum, company officials
announced Monday.
   The sale is part of Phillips' strategy to divest non-strategic
assets, company spokesman Dan Harrison said.
   ``It did not have a good fit for us,'' Harrison said of
Williston Basin.
   Since 1985, Phillips has sold gas plants at Williston and Tioga,
N.D., Harrison said.
   Conoco, a subsidiary of Du Pont Co., will obtain Phillips'
interest in about 175 oil and gas wells that produce about 4,000
barrels of oil and 2.8 million cubic feet of natural gas a day.
   Also included in the sale are 234,000 undeveloped acres in
eastern Montana and western North Dakota.
   Harrison said Phillips' interest in the Williston property
amounted to about 2,000 barrels of oil and 1 million cubic feet of
gas a day. He said Phillips' U.S. production last year was 113,000
barrels of oil and 772 million cubic feet of natural gas a day.
   Industry analysts say the amount of domestic oil and gas
reserves up for sale has about doubled in the past year because of
the market created by high exploration costs.
   The transactions usually reflect the seller's need to reduce
debt and the buyer's desire for proven production at a cost lower
than that of exploring for new reserves, the analysts said.
</TEXT>
