<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Airlines 1stLd-Writethru f0133 08-08 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0133,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air's Loss Widens Sharply; TWA's Profit Nearly Doubles</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with Texas Air results; changes
dateline and summary line; ADDS more reasons for TWA gains; No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest airline company, Texas Air Corp., reported
Monday that its second-quarter net loss widened sharply, while
Trans World Airlines Inc. said its profit after taxes nearly
doubled.
   Houston-based Texas Air said its net loss widened to $255.9
million from a loss of $27 million in the second quarter of 1987.
The company blamed a significant part of the loss on government
investigations of alleged safety problems at its two main
subsidiaries, Continental Airlines and Eastern Airlines.
   Texas Air's second-quarter revenue slipped 1.4 percent, to $2.13
billion from $2.16 billion a year earlier.
   The Department of Transportation and the Federal Aviation
Administration launched investigations of Eastern and Continental
in mid-April that were unprecedented in their scope. The probes,
which continued for most of the second quarter, concluded that both
airlines were being run safely.
   However, a federal report concluded that labor turmoil at
Miami-based Eastern must be defused before it creates risks to
passengers.
   Texas Air said Monday the investigations cost Eastern and
Houston-based Continental a total of more than $60 million in lost
revenue and $14 million in expenses such as overtime, advertising
and legal and accounting fees.
   ``Both airlines have implemented various marketing and service
programs to counter the effects of these investigations on consumer
confidence, but the companies have continued to experience some
revenue losses beyond the second quarter due to them,'' Texas Air
said in a press statement.
   At Eastern, the second-quarter net loss was $89.8 million,
compared with net income of $27.1 million a year earlier. Eastern's
revenue in the most recent quarter declined to $1 billion from $1.2
billion.
   Continental posted a $19.9 million loss before a $131 million
adjustment associated with a re-estimation of its air traffic
liability. The adjustment had been announced earlier and had no
impact on Continental's cash position, Texas Air said.
   Including the adjustment, Continental lost $150.9 million on
revenue of $1.1 billion in the second quarter. In the same period a
year earlier, the airline lost $71.1 million on revenue of $1
billion.
   The results in the latest quarter brought Texas Air's net loss
for the first half of the year to $380.1 million, widened from a
loss of $127.7 million in the first six months of 1987.
   Texas Air's first-half revenue rose 1.4 percent, to $4.26
billion from $4.20 billion.
   New York-based TWA said its net profit almost doubled in the
second quarter from a year earlier, largely due to a cash payment
it received from a lawsuit against its former owner, the late
Howard Hughes.
   The nation's seventh-largest airline said its net income jumped
to $97.2 million, or $2.70 a share, from $52.8 million, or $1.28 a
share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   In addition to a $49.9 million gain from the Hughes lawsuit, TWA
said its earnings also benefitted in the quarter from cost
controls, a rebound in international passenger traffic which had
been hurt by fears of terrorism, and the long-term advantages of
TWA's merger with Ozark Air Lines.
   TWA's second-quarter revenue rose 8.6 percent, to $1.14 billion
from $1.05 billion a year earlier.
   Profit in the latest quarter includes the $49.9 million gain
from a cash judgment awarded to TWA in 1987 in its long-standing
lawsuit against Hughes. The TWA management's suit, originally filed
in 1962, alleged that the eccentric multimillionaire failed to
provide the carrier with adequate aircraft.
   Although a Delaware court decided in TWA's favor last year, the
payment was not made until the second quarter.
   In the first half of the year, TWA earned $44.7 million, or 50
cents a share, compared with a net loss of $2 million in the first
six months of 1987.
   First-half revenue increased 9.6 percent, to $2.06 billion from
$1.88 billion.
</TEXT>
