<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hershey-Friendly     08-08 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hershey-Friendly,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hershey Foods Selling Friendly Ice Cream</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HERSHEY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hershey Foods Corp., deciding to jettison
its nine-year venture into the restaurant industry, said Monday it
is selling its Friendly Ice Cream Corp. to Tennessee Restaurant Co.
for $375 million.
   Richard A. Zimmerman, Hershey's chairman and chief executive,
said the company felt it could better use its resources
concentrating on its primary business _ consumer food products.
   ``Although Friendly has been a significant part of Hershey
Foods, our decision to sell Friendly is based upon our continuing
review of our strategic plan and evaluation of our business
portfolio,'' Zimmerman said in a statement.
   Hershey spokesman Carl Andrews said declining income and other
difficult conditions in the restaurant industry figured in
Hershey's decision.
   Income from the restaurant chain fell to $45.6 million in 1986
from $50.4 million in 1986.
   In its 1986 annual report, Hershey noted heightened competition,
lack of real sales growth, a decrease in customers and difficulty
finding workers.
   Two-thirds of the company's sales gain in the restaurant
division from 1985 to 1986 came from new and acquired restaurants
rather than from higher volume at existing restaurants.
   Besides its chocolate and confectionery products, Hershey also
produces several brands of pasta, including San Giorgio, Skinner
and American Beauty.
   Friendly, based in Wilbraham, Mass., owns and operates a chain
of about 850 restaurants, which feature moderately priced menu
items and ice cream specialities. Friendly's 1987 sales were $572
million.
   Hershey Foods said the transaction, which will give it an
after-tax gain, should be completed within three months, subject to
government approval.
   TRC, a private restaurant holding company based in Chicago, owns
about 51 percent of Perkins Family Restaurants, a publicly traded
limited partnership, and 100 percent of Perkins Management Co. Inc.
   Perkins owns and franchices more than 330 restaurants, primarily
in Minnesota, Ohio, Pennsylvania, New York and Florida.
   ``We are pleased to enter phase two of TRC's development with a
company boasting the high-quality reputation of Friendly,'' said
Donald N. Smith, TRC chairman and chief executive officer.
   He said Friendly has strong name recognition andd excellent
market penetration in the Northeast. Friendly will provide a solid
foundation for future growth, Smith said.
   Perkins and Friendly will be operated as separate companies,
Smith said.
   Hershey's move comes shortly after it announced plans to
purchase the U.S. confectionery operations of Cadbury-Schweppess
PLC of England for $270 million plus the assumption of $30 million
in debt.
   The purchase, still in progress, will give Hershey a wide array
of candy lines, stretching from its own well-known products,
including Reeses peanut butter candies, to Cadbury's Peter-Paul and
York products and Luden's 5th Avenue bar and cough drops.
   ``What we're finding is our area of strength is manufacturing,
with a primary focus on snacks and confectionery products,''
Andrews said.
   ``We do think that puts us in a leadership position of the total
U.S. confectionery market,'' he added.
</TEXT>
