<FILEID>AP-NR-08-08-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DetroitNewspapers-Reax     08-08 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Detroit Newspapers-Reax,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Free Press Employees Celebrate Approval Of Partial Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT6 and DT7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper employees and executives by turns
praised and criticized Attorney General Edwin Meese's approval
Monday of a partial merger of the Detroit Free Press with the
Detroit News.
   Champagne flowed in the newsroom at the Free Press, where the
decision brought relief after months of uncertainty over whether
Meese would approve the joint operating agreement between the
newspaper, the nation's 10th-largest, and the rival News.
   ``It was like a rush. Waiting for the decision is like living on
death row,'' said senior managing editor Neal Shine, who had been
assigned to write the newspaper's obituary if the joint operating
agreement with the News was denied.
   But critics labeled the deal a blow to competition in the
newspaper business.
   ``This is a travesty of the Newspaper Preservation Act,'' said
Lou Mleczko, a News reporter who is president of Newspaper Guild
Local 22. ``The two largest media companies in the world can take
two newspapers that are in a dead heat and get a monopoly.''
   Knight-Ridder Inc. had said it would close the 157-year-old Free
Press if the JOA with the News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., was
denied.
   In Miami, top Knight-Ridder executives praised Free Press
employees for persevering under difficult conditions and praised
Meese for approving the JOA.
   ``This is good news for the loyal readers and advertisers of the
Free Press, for our hard-working and dedicated employees in Detroit
and for our shareholders who have shared the burden of enormous
operating losses in Detroit since 1979,'' Knight-Ridder chairman
Alvah H. Chapman Jr. said in a statement.
   Gannett chairman Allen Neuharth and president John J. Curley
also praised the decision.
   ``We said all along that the JOA was the only way to preserve
two independent news and editorial voices,'' they said in a
statement issued from Gannett headquarters in Arlington, Va. ``The
attorney general's decision is in the best interest of the
community, the readers, the advertisers and the employees.''
   Newspaper Guild Local 22, the last of the newspapers' unions to
drop its opposition to the JOA, nevertheless was critical of the
decision. The Guild, which has 1,100 members in the two newsrooms,
held out for better economic terms before agreeing to withdraw its
opposition.
   ``The losers in this are going to be the readers and advertisers
in southeastern Michigan and it could set a precedent where you'll
see the elimination of competitive journalism in cities throughout
the United States,'' said Mleczko.
   Mike Lloyd, editor of the Grand Rapids Press, the state's
third-largest paper, said he was pleased as a journalist that the
merger was approved.
   ``The loss of any daily newspaper would be considered a bad day
in journalism by even those of us who think of the Free Press as
serious competition,'' said Lloyd.
   Bruce McIntyre, publisher of the Oakland (Mich.) Press, said he
was surprised Meese would disregard the recommendation of the
administrative law judge who presided over hearings on the proposed
JOA.
   ``Judge (Morton) Needelman sat and listened to these things and
made a very studious decision on it, and it's hard to believe the
attorney general would so easily overturn what his own
administrative law judge recommended,'' McIntyre said.
   Reactions from Michigan politicians also varied.
   State Senator John Kelly of Detroit, who unsuccessfully sought a
new law blocking the JOA, said ``What has really happened is the
annihilation of the Free Press. It will be `Gannettized' and the
quality staff will be reduced because there will be no incentive
without any real competition.''
   But U.S. Sen. Carl Levin, a longtime Meese critic, complemented
the attorney general.
   ``Today's announcement shows what a united community can do and
what a united Michigan congressional delegation can do. Attorney
General Edwin Meese's response to that united community is very
gratifying indeed,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
