<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0274 08-08 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0274,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Lower In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Nikkei morning closing,
details, comments. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher against the Japanese
yen in morning trading Tuesday, while stock prices eased.
   After opening at 133.62 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.97
yen, the dollar traded in a narrow range and by late morning was
changing hands at 133.70 yen.
   Traders said most currency market participants were monitoring
the dollar's movements against the West German mark. West Germany's
Bundesbank intervened in the market sporadically to keep the dollar
from rising too sharply against the mark in overseas markets.
   The dollar reached 1.90 marks during Monday trading, a level not
seen since January 1987.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, down 109.06 points on Monday, fell another 37.81
points to finish the morning session at 28,215.31.
   Dealers on the stock exchange said the market remained
relatively quiet as participants relaxed because of the summer
holidays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
